1
00:00:30,976 --> 00:00:34,713
All three of our chefs

2
00:00:34,713 --> 00:00:37,950
have now reached day three.

3
00:00:37,950 --> 00:00:40,386
We are already past the halfway mark

4
00:00:40,386 --> 00:00:42,154
of the promised five days.

5
00:00:42,154 --> 00:00:43,155
Time really went by fast.

6
00:00:43,155 --> 00:00:45,958
[First promotion: Hee Tae in Parma]
Chef Sam Kim was the first one

7
00:00:45,958 --> 00:00:47,526
to get promoted last week.

8
00:00:47,526 --> 00:00:49,795
[Currently leading the three chefs]
He actually has the best record right now.

9
00:00:49,795 --> 00:00:52,264
I really was not expecting that result at all.

10
00:00:52,264 --> 00:00:54,633
[An acceptance speech out of nowhere?]

11
00:00:54,633 --> 00:00:56,302
- You can probably tell from the footage,
- You were not expecting much.

12
00:00:56,302 --> 00:00:58,237
- I was just so happy.
- I know.

13
00:00:58,237 --> 00:00:59,538
We could tell from your face.

14
00:00:59,538 --> 00:01:01,140
- I was thrilled.
- Your face showed it all.

15
00:01:01,140 --> 00:01:04,943
You literally could not hide your joy.

16
00:01:06,879 --> 00:01:08,280
Meanwhile, the Jung-Kwon siblings...

17
00:01:08,280 --> 00:01:09,849
- Watching that, I was just thinking...
- Wait, out of nowhere?

18
00:01:09,849 --> 00:01:12,418
Both of you had the exact same strategy.

19
00:01:12,418 --> 00:01:14,487
You both thought,
"We will use the staff meal...

20
00:01:14,487 --> 00:01:15,888
- Exactly.
- to impress them and get promoted."

21
00:01:15,888 --> 00:01:17,790
Both of you came up with the same plan.

22
00:01:17,790 --> 00:01:19,258
But I am telling you, that does not work.

23
00:01:19,258 --> 00:01:20,659
Wasn't he just lucky?

24
00:01:20,659 --> 00:01:21,760
You think it was just luck?

25
00:01:21,760 --> 00:01:23,529
No, from what I can tell,

26
00:01:23,529 --> 00:01:26,465
I think you just have to be genuine.

27
00:01:26,465 --> 00:01:28,634
- I am genuine too!
- Unlike us, who are overthinking

28
00:01:28,634 --> 00:01:30,469
and trying to scheme...

29
00:01:30,469 --> 00:01:32,304
- I was not scheming!
- Trying to be strategic...

30
00:01:32,304 --> 00:01:33,906
Why do you keep lumping us together?
I am not like you!

31
00:01:33,906 --> 00:01:36,375
- I guess people can just see right through us
- What are you talking about?

32
00:01:36,375 --> 00:01:38,177
- when we try to be clever.
- No.

33
00:01:38,177 --> 00:01:39,345
Stop lumping me in with you!

34
00:01:39,345 --> 00:01:41,747
[Drawing a firm line]
Let's draw a line right here.

35
00:01:41,747 --> 00:01:43,415
Anyway, speaking hypothetically.

36
00:01:43,415 --> 00:01:48,420
If we could go back to day one right now,

37
00:01:48,420 --> 00:01:52,958
is there anything you wish
you had done differently?

38
00:01:52,958 --> 00:01:55,227
I feel like Chef Sam Kim definitely has one.

39
00:01:55,227 --> 00:01:58,163
- Do you not?
- He definitely has at least one.

40
00:01:58,163 --> 00:02:01,000
- Let's hear it.
- Looking back...

41
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:02,468
[Look at this]
if I had to pick a regret...

42
00:02:02,468 --> 00:02:04,370
- This...
- I should have paid much closer attention

43
00:02:04,370 --> 00:02:06,772
- to the shapes of the pasta.
- Ah, paying attention to the shapes.

44
00:02:06,772 --> 00:02:09,441
- The potato pasta.
- And I would give my own staff...

45
00:02:09,441 --> 00:02:12,912
at least three chances.

46
00:02:12,912 --> 00:02:14,921
- Oh, seriously.
- That is not easy.

47
00:02:14,921 --> 00:02:18,517
This show really teaches you
some huge life lessons.

48
00:02:18,517 --> 00:02:20,686
For me,

49
00:02:20,686 --> 00:02:23,915
I would have styled my hair better.

50
00:02:23,915 --> 00:02:25,457
- Wasn't that your strategy?
- Grooming.

51
00:02:25,457 --> 00:02:27,927
- No.
- I thought you strategically

52
00:02:27,927 --> 00:02:29,695
- left your hair...
- I was going for a natural look,

53
00:02:29,695 --> 00:02:31,664
but I didn't know it was that bad.

54
00:02:31,664 --> 00:02:33,065
I didn't know it was that bad,

55
00:02:33,065 --> 00:02:35,034
and I should have skipped
the pizza and burgers.

56
00:02:35,034 --> 00:02:37,236
[Munching]
My face was so swollen.

57
00:02:37,236 --> 00:02:38,637
My face was so puffy from all the salt.

58
00:02:38,637 --> 00:02:40,472
[His only crime: loving Naples pizza too much]

59
00:02:40,472 --> 00:02:42,374
[Parma, Italy. Hee Tae, not Sam Kim]
So this is day two,

60
00:02:42,374 --> 00:02:44,276
[Undercover Day 2, wrapping up dinner shift]
during the dinner shift.

61
00:02:44,276 --> 00:02:46,011
Tomorrow...

62
00:02:47,012 --> 00:02:49,181
No pasta!

63
00:02:49,181 --> 00:02:51,717
Let's have you slice some ham over there!

64
00:02:51,717 --> 00:02:54,653
[The No. 2 station]

65
00:02:54,653 --> 00:02:55,921
- Oh, he must be so nervous.
- Me?

66
00:02:55,921 --> 00:02:57,990
- Really?
- Yes.

67
00:02:57,990 --> 00:03:00,926
[My station!]
[Moving to Simone's No. 2 station]

68
00:03:00,926 --> 00:03:03,728
- Next step.
- Look how happy he is.

69
00:03:04,530 --> 00:03:06,732
If he is that happy, even I would...

70
00:03:06,732 --> 00:03:09,802
- I'd want to promote him, too.
- Right.

71
00:03:09,802 --> 00:03:11,936
I was so happy, honestly.

72
00:03:12,705 --> 00:03:14,573
Sam Kim is so pure.
Seriously, the more I watch him...

73
00:03:14,573 --> 00:03:16,308
- I don't think I can sleep.
- I need to study!

74
00:03:16,308 --> 00:03:17,710
[A thrilling promotion just 2 days in]

75
00:03:17,710 --> 00:03:19,912
- Thank you.
- Look at his eyes!

76
00:03:19,912 --> 00:03:21,746
His hair looks great, too.

77
00:03:24,183 --> 00:03:27,752
Now, let's write down
tomorrow's prep list, and...

78
00:03:28,721 --> 00:03:32,024
[You know what today is, right?]

79
00:03:32,024 --> 00:03:34,126
- A little party!
- He said they were going out for drinks today.

80
00:03:34,126 --> 00:03:36,495
[A little party?]

81
00:03:36,495 --> 00:03:39,131
So that is today.

82
00:03:39,131 --> 00:03:41,266
[Five minutes before the promotion]
Happy birthday, Simo!

83
00:03:42,368 --> 00:03:45,203
It was Simone's birthday.

84
00:03:45,203 --> 00:03:46,505
Where are we going?

85
00:03:46,505 --> 00:03:47,627
Evolution!

86
00:03:47,627 --> 00:03:48,707
The place is called Evolution?

87
00:03:48,707 --> 00:03:50,075
Evolution?

88
00:03:50,075 --> 00:03:51,110
Sounds intense.

89
00:03:51,110 --> 00:03:53,379
[Party!]

90
00:03:53,379 --> 00:03:54,613
You don't drink at all, right?

91
00:03:54,613 --> 00:03:56,148
- Yeah, almost never.
- Party.

92
00:03:56,148 --> 00:03:58,651
You can just drink a little for the toast.

93
00:03:58,651 --> 00:04:01,052
Just have a little, and then you can go to bed!

94
00:04:03,355 --> 00:04:06,425
- Doesn't he have to go?
- He has to. He can't just skip it.

95
00:04:06,425 --> 00:04:10,029
[It's already 11 PM...]

96
00:04:10,029 --> 00:04:14,066
It is amazing. I don't know how chefs can
go out like that after a shift.

97
00:04:14,066 --> 00:04:16,335
- Physically, it is...
- Their stamina is insane.

98
00:04:16,335 --> 00:04:17,503
[Hee Tae... You're coming to my party, right?]

99
00:04:17,503 --> 00:04:19,171
No?

100
00:04:19,171 --> 00:04:21,473
[Right, I just got promoted...]
- He can't exactly say no. - Right.

101
00:04:21,473 --> 00:04:22,941
If he doesn't go,
they won't talk to him tomorrow.

102
00:04:22,941 --> 00:04:23,876
- Exactly.
- Seriously.

103
00:04:23,876 --> 00:04:27,312
- Yeah, he has to go.
- Yeah, they literally won't talk to him!

104
00:04:27,312 --> 00:04:29,481
- Going out for drinks is an extension of work.
- True.

105
00:04:29,481 --> 00:04:31,349
[The 49-year-old rookie follows his seniors...]

106
00:04:31,984 --> 00:04:33,986
[How will Hee Tae's night out go?]
Okay.

107
00:04:33,986 --> 00:04:37,089
[Parma, past midnight, 12:00 AM]

108
00:04:37,089 --> 00:04:40,926
[Parma's night streets
look completely different]

109
00:04:40,926 --> 00:04:43,862
All the young people in Parma are here.

110
00:04:44,997 --> 00:04:49,168
Alright! Let's go in!

111
00:04:49,168 --> 00:04:52,304
[Already chaotic]
You go first.

112
00:04:52,304 --> 00:04:54,038
Oh, my gosh.

113
00:04:56,442 --> 00:04:58,077
[The bass thumping in their ears]

114
00:04:58,077 --> 00:04:59,978
Listen to that volume.

115
00:04:59,978 --> 00:05:03,215
[A club DJ right between the huge speakers!]

116
00:05:03,215 --> 00:05:05,984
[Thump]
What? They have a DJ here?

117
00:05:06,652 --> 00:05:09,722
[A local hotspot packed even at midnight]

118
00:05:09,722 --> 00:05:12,291
It seemed like the local hotspot.

119
00:05:12,291 --> 00:05:14,126
Man, the atmosphere is amazing.

120
00:05:14,126 --> 00:05:17,129
[One person shocked by this flashy club]

121
00:05:17,129 --> 00:05:19,364
Oh, I could never go to a place like this!

122
00:05:24,236 --> 00:05:25,938
[Dazed...]

123
00:05:25,938 --> 00:05:27,272
Man, I was in shock yesterday.

124
00:05:27,272 --> 00:05:31,276
I have been to Italy so many times,
but I have never been to a place like this.

125
00:05:32,611 --> 00:05:34,379
[Mentally checked out]

126
00:05:34,379 --> 00:05:37,416
Man, it has been over 20 years.

127
00:05:37,416 --> 00:05:41,019
[Going to a club after 20 years...]
Who even goes to clubs these days?

128
00:05:41,019 --> 00:05:43,621
Let's dance later!

129
00:05:45,324 --> 00:05:47,459
- Are you tired?
- Not at all!

130
00:05:47,459 --> 00:05:49,861
Yes, he's tired.

131
00:05:50,829 --> 00:05:56,729
[Exhausted, but desperately holding on]

132
00:05:57,369 --> 00:06:01,206
I have never been to a place like this!

133
00:06:01,940 --> 00:06:04,977
Hee Tae says he has never been to a club!

134
00:06:04,977 --> 00:06:07,045
You have never been to a club?

135
00:06:07,045 --> 00:06:08,547
- Are you crazy?
- No way!

136
00:06:08,547 --> 00:06:11,283
[Intense reaction]
No way.

137
00:06:11,283 --> 00:06:14,486
Korean ID.

138
00:06:14,486 --> 00:06:15,954
Cut!

139
00:06:15,954 --> 00:06:19,792
[Immediately understands]
Is it because of your age?

140
00:06:19,792 --> 00:06:23,996
[He doesn't get it]

141
00:06:23,996 --> 00:06:26,531
[47-year-old gets defensive]
Age doesn't matter here.

142
00:06:27,599 --> 00:06:28,700
[52-year-old shakes his head...]

143
00:06:28,700 --> 00:06:30,803
Italy is different.

144
00:06:30,803 --> 00:06:35,707
In Italy, the kids go to sleep,
and the older people go out to dance.

145
00:06:37,843 --> 00:06:39,011
[I wish I were a kid right now...]

146
00:06:39,011 --> 00:06:40,778
"Now."

147
00:06:43,715 --> 00:06:46,218
[Under the flashy lights]

148
00:06:46,218 --> 00:06:47,686
He spaced out.

149
00:06:47,686 --> 00:06:49,855
It's like...

150
00:06:49,855 --> 00:06:51,790
Is your mother a chef?

151
00:06:51,790 --> 00:06:54,692
[Simone's sudden question]
Is your mother a cook?

152
00:06:55,294 --> 00:06:57,196
Yeah.

153
00:06:57,196 --> 00:07:03,196
Have you always been a farmer?
What did you do before organic farming?

154
00:07:04,136 --> 00:07:05,704
He needs to come up with a good lie right here.

155
00:07:05,704 --> 00:07:08,607
[The No. 1 Chef is curious about his past job]

156
00:07:08,607 --> 00:07:11,043
Were you a farmer your whole life?

157
00:07:11,043 --> 00:07:12,937
Yes.

158
00:07:12,937 --> 00:07:14,613
[Oh, really?]
[Glancing around]

159
00:07:14,613 --> 00:07:16,973
[Cracking up]

160
00:07:16,973 --> 00:07:20,018
[Getting tense]
Man, what is he going to do?

161
00:07:20,018 --> 00:07:23,163
I didn't expect to have
this conversation at a club.

162
00:07:23,163 --> 00:07:26,766
By the way, how do you know English so well?

163
00:07:27,659 --> 00:07:31,930
[Right... I'm supposed to be a lifelong farmer]

164
00:07:31,930 --> 00:07:34,099
I studied in the US!

165
00:07:34,099 --> 00:07:35,434
- The US?
- Yes.

166
00:07:35,434 --> 00:07:37,469
- Where in the US?
- LA!

167
00:07:37,469 --> 00:07:40,172
- Los Angeles!
- Los Angeles?

168
00:07:40,172 --> 00:07:42,941
How many years were you there?

169
00:07:42,941 --> 00:07:44,809
12 years!

170
00:07:45,944 --> 00:07:47,012
[12 years?]

171
00:07:47,012 --> 00:07:48,280
Huh?

172
00:07:48,280 --> 00:07:50,649
- Wait a minute.
- All of a sudden?

173
00:07:50,649 --> 00:07:52,384
He's being way too honest right now.

174
00:07:52,384 --> 00:07:53,676
- Wait a minute.
- All of a sudden?

175
00:07:53,676 --> 00:07:56,560
You've been a farmer your whole life,
but suddenly spent 12 years...

176
00:07:56,560 --> 00:07:57,764
He said he was a lifelong farmer.

177
00:07:57,764 --> 00:08:00,025
- Just watch, now I tell them what I studied.
- No, wait a minute.

178
00:08:00,025 --> 00:08:01,593
[Sleep-deprived rambling kicks in]

179
00:08:01,593 --> 00:08:03,695
- You went there to do what?
- To study.

180
00:08:03,695 --> 00:08:06,832
[You lived in LA for 12 years?]

181
00:08:06,832 --> 00:08:10,235
That next question is
when my brain just stopped working.

182
00:08:10,235 --> 00:08:12,638
[The truth and his cover story
are officially tangled]

183
00:08:12,638 --> 00:08:15,107
So you weren't just doing organic farming?

184
00:08:15,107 --> 00:08:17,743
Didn't you say you lived
in Los Angeles for 12 years?

185
00:08:17,743 --> 00:08:19,690
He's busted. Totally busted.

186
00:08:19,690 --> 00:08:20,746
[Uh-oh...]

187
00:08:20,746 --> 00:08:23,282
Those questions were razor-sharp.

188
00:08:23,282 --> 00:08:25,417
This was basically an interrogation.

189
00:08:25,417 --> 00:08:29,254
He's about to just blurt out the truth.

190
00:08:29,254 --> 00:08:31,889
What did you study?

191
00:08:32,858 --> 00:08:36,795
[Should fix this fast...]

192
00:08:36,795 --> 00:08:39,197
I didn't know what to say.

193
00:08:39,197 --> 00:08:41,332
Farm... farming?

194
00:08:42,200 --> 00:08:44,036
- In LA?
- In LA?

195
00:08:44,036 --> 00:08:45,103
In LA?

196
00:08:45,103 --> 00:08:46,438
- That could happen.
- In Los Angeles?

197
00:08:46,438 --> 00:08:47,773
He went to ag school. Ag school.

198
00:08:47,773 --> 00:08:50,108
So he's an LA ag school grad now?

199
00:08:50,108 --> 00:08:52,044
[Whatever, screw it!]
Smart farming.

200
00:08:52,044 --> 00:08:52,744
Yeah, that could work.

201
00:08:52,744 --> 00:08:54,646
- Smart farming.
- Smart farming.

202
00:08:54,646 --> 00:08:55,814
I see.

203
00:08:55,814 --> 00:08:57,115
[Presumed LA ag school grad,
runs a smart farm somewhere in LA]

204
00:08:57,115 --> 00:08:59,718
Man, last night was just...

205
00:08:59,718 --> 00:09:02,987
The owner doesn't miss a thing.

206
00:09:04,589 --> 00:09:08,827
So what do you do with the crops you grow?

207
00:09:08,827 --> 00:09:11,996
Do you sell them, or just cook for yourself?

208
00:09:13,332 --> 00:09:16,034
Not to sell, just to eat!

209
00:09:16,635 --> 00:09:18,904
Wait, he doesn't sell them? Just eats them?

210
00:09:18,904 --> 00:09:20,472
- He's done it his whole life...
- His whole life, and...

211
00:09:20,472 --> 00:09:22,040
- His whole life...
- And he doesn't sell them?

212
00:09:22,040 --> 00:09:24,643
That makes no sense. He's basically unemployed.

213
00:09:24,643 --> 00:09:27,012
- The story doesn't add up.
- He's a bum.

214
00:09:27,012 --> 00:09:28,814
The story doesn't add up.

215
00:09:28,814 --> 00:09:29,915
I mean, his whole life...

216
00:09:29,915 --> 00:09:31,450
- He studied farming...
- And on top of that...

217
00:09:31,450 --> 00:09:33,652
- Guess his family's loaded.
- He went to ag school in LA...

218
00:09:33,652 --> 00:09:35,821
- I mean, what's he even...
- There was no fixing it

219
00:09:35,821 --> 00:09:37,022
- at that point.
- Watching it now...

220
00:09:37,022 --> 00:09:38,757
He was done. Game over.

221
00:09:38,757 --> 00:09:40,926
So how have you been making a living, then?

222
00:09:40,926 --> 00:09:44,129
Of course that question was coming.
That was inevitable.

223
00:09:44,129 --> 00:09:45,897
He's just living off his own crops.

224
00:09:45,897 --> 00:09:48,767
[The question that hit the nail on the head]

225
00:09:48,767 --> 00:09:50,469
Oh, man.

226
00:09:50,469 --> 00:09:52,504
[Synchronized despair]

227
00:09:52,504 --> 00:09:54,306
[The laugh of surrender]

228
00:09:54,306 --> 00:09:56,441
I'll never forget that look on his face!

229
00:09:56,441 --> 00:09:58,010
Oh, man, that face...

230
00:09:58,010 --> 00:10:01,279
The DJ was blasting behind the boss,

231
00:10:01,279 --> 00:10:03,115
and the questions kept coming at me.

232
00:10:03,115 --> 00:10:05,484
That was so funny.
He looked so serious and intense.

233
00:10:05,484 --> 00:10:08,420
[The boss keeps firing questions...]
He was basically going, "I don't get you."

234
00:10:08,420 --> 00:10:11,456
[So how do you even make a living?]

235
00:10:11,456 --> 00:10:15,159
Please tell him I'm barely surviving.

236
00:10:16,128 --> 00:10:18,196
What does that even mean?

237
00:10:18,196 --> 00:10:21,333
- He gave up.
- What is he even saying?

238
00:10:21,333 --> 00:10:23,769
- He's not thinking straight right now!
- No, that's not it.

239
00:10:23,769 --> 00:10:26,505
- Look at him. He was barely functioning.
- He really was.

240
00:10:26,505 --> 00:10:28,206
He's so tired, he can't think straight.

241
00:10:28,206 --> 00:10:30,942
He's completely overwhelmed right now.

242
00:10:30,942 --> 00:10:33,145
[Just laugh it off]

243
00:10:33,145 --> 00:10:34,713
See? I knew it.

244
00:10:34,713 --> 00:10:37,816
[He never should've come here...]
He's too nice to lie.

245
00:10:37,816 --> 00:10:39,584
His face was saying he really didn't get me.

246
00:10:39,584 --> 00:10:42,220
[Undercover identity at risk]
How did you pay for 12 years of school?

247
00:10:42,220 --> 00:10:43,955
You went there to study farming,

248
00:10:43,955 --> 00:10:47,225
so why don't you have a business or a job?

249
00:10:47,225 --> 00:10:50,128
He was basically telling me,
"You make no sense."

250
00:10:50,128 --> 00:10:53,398
I looked unemployed,

251
00:10:53,398 --> 00:10:55,867
with years of study in the US,

252
00:10:55,867 --> 00:10:58,303
so they probably thought
I was some rich slacker.

253
00:10:58,303 --> 00:10:59,371
A total slacker.

254
00:10:59,371 --> 00:11:01,339
[This is painful]
I studied but didn't do anything...

255
00:11:01,339 --> 00:11:02,774
- Now everyone thinks he's weird.
- No one believes him anymore.

256
00:11:02,774 --> 00:11:03,842
It is weird.

257
00:11:03,842 --> 00:11:07,512
Let's open a restaurant in Korea!

258
00:11:07,512 --> 00:11:10,682
Hee Tae can handle the vegetables,
and I'll cook!

259
00:11:10,682 --> 00:11:12,284
Oh, Sorem just...

260
00:11:12,284 --> 00:11:15,153
[Still working under you?]
showed his true colors.

261
00:11:15,787 --> 00:11:17,189
Take me with you, man.

262
00:11:17,189 --> 00:11:18,957
I'm dying here.

263
00:11:18,957 --> 00:11:20,792
[Just come to Korea first!]

264
00:11:21,460 --> 00:11:24,963
[We work tomorrow. Let's get up!]

265
00:11:24,963 --> 00:11:28,667
[After 90 minutes of questioning, 1:30 AM]

266
00:11:28,667 --> 00:11:30,368
His head must've been spinning.

267
00:11:30,368 --> 00:11:32,471
[Nothing feels settled...]

268
00:11:32,471 --> 00:11:34,272
I do think they're a little suspicious.

269
00:11:34,272 --> 00:11:36,708
Not necessarily about who I really am,

270
00:11:36,708 --> 00:11:39,010
but more like something about me feels off.

271
00:11:39,678 --> 00:11:43,515
They just can't quite put their finger on it.

272
00:11:43,515 --> 00:11:45,350
[He heads back, still uneasy...]

273
00:11:45,350 --> 00:11:49,353
He needs to plan his cover story for tomorrow.

274
00:11:50,555 --> 00:11:54,526
If it's 2 AM there, it's 9 AM in Korea.

275
00:11:54,526 --> 00:11:57,129
[Right after his promotion, too...]
He must be completely drained.

276
00:11:57,129 --> 00:11:59,497
He starts on the grill tomorrow.

277
00:12:02,234 --> 00:12:04,436
This is starting to go in a weird direction.

278
00:12:04,436 --> 00:12:08,739
[Promotion aside, will his cover be blown?]

279
00:12:11,042 --> 00:12:14,880
[Morning commute, 8:50 AM]

280
00:12:14,880 --> 00:12:17,282
[Undercover Day 3, and...]

281
00:12:17,282 --> 00:12:18,984
What a view.

282
00:12:18,984 --> 00:12:20,385
[His first day after the promotion]

283
00:12:20,385 --> 00:12:22,253
This is nice.

284
00:12:25,191 --> 00:12:27,025
At least he cleaned up well.

285
00:12:27,025 --> 00:12:29,660
[No longer stuck on rookie duty]

286
00:12:30,860 --> 00:12:32,030
I felt good.

287
00:12:32,030 --> 00:12:34,226
[But after last night's close call...]

288
00:12:34,226 --> 00:12:37,493
Today, I'll be working
farther inside the kitchen.

289
00:12:37,493 --> 00:12:39,804
So he probably won't be able to ask me much.

290
00:12:39,804 --> 00:12:42,941
Before, I was right by the doorway,

291
00:12:42,941 --> 00:12:45,143
so he'd see me working whenever he passed by,

292
00:12:45,143 --> 00:12:47,179
[The fresh pasta station was his usual route]
and he'd talk to me as he went by.

293
00:12:47,179 --> 00:12:49,860
- Right.
- Since I'll be farther inside,

294
00:12:49,860 --> 00:12:52,693
- maybe he won't ask as many questions.
- Right. You'll be tucked in the middle.

295
00:12:52,693 --> 00:12:55,794
[But the real problem is the No.1 chef...]
But I was worried the chef might ask me things.

296
00:12:55,794 --> 00:12:57,522
His questions were sharp.

297
00:12:57,522 --> 00:13:00,193
[Gianpietro, the No.1 chef suspicious of Hee Tae]
Good morning.

298
00:13:00,193 --> 00:13:02,360
Good morning.

299
00:13:02,360 --> 00:13:04,026
[An awkward handshake attempt!]

300
00:13:04,026 --> 00:13:05,660
How are you feeling? You okay?

301
00:13:05,660 --> 00:13:07,093
I'm good.

302
00:13:07,093 --> 00:13:08,033
You, too?

303
00:13:08,033 --> 00:13:09,193
Did you get some rest last night?

304
00:13:09,193 --> 00:13:11,427
Yes, I did!

305
00:13:11,427 --> 00:13:13,805
- Did you have a good night's rest?
- I did, yes.

306
00:13:13,805 --> 00:13:16,007
[Nervous about what the head chef might say...]

307
00:13:16,007 --> 00:13:19,510
[He carefully reads the room...]

308
00:13:20,579 --> 00:13:22,214
[Turns out... he's just sleepy!]

309
00:13:22,214 --> 00:13:24,059
Everyone's tired.

310
00:13:24,059 --> 00:13:27,134
People working in Italy
can't really go anywhere in the morning.

311
00:13:27,134 --> 00:13:28,219
They're just too exhausted.

312
00:13:28,219 --> 00:13:29,860
The more I watch,
the more I see Italy and Korea

313
00:13:29,860 --> 00:13:32,691
- have a lot in common.
- They do, in a way.

314
00:13:32,691 --> 00:13:35,026
[For now, he makes it in without suspicion]

315
00:13:35,026 --> 00:13:36,760
At the sound of the bell,

316
00:13:36,760 --> 00:13:39,063
[Will his first day at No.2 go smoothly?]
everyone heads in.

317
00:13:39,931 --> 00:13:42,033
[Peek]

318
00:13:43,501 --> 00:13:47,573
[Spots Senior Simone at No.2]

319
00:13:47,573 --> 00:13:49,207
He must have a ton of questions.

320
00:13:49,207 --> 00:13:51,910
- Right? He has to move up now.
- Exactly.

321
00:13:51,910 --> 00:13:54,059
[Just hovering around]
Walking over to that spot still felt weird.

322
00:13:54,059 --> 00:13:55,947
- Yeah.
- Right.

323
00:13:55,947 --> 00:13:57,449
[Waiting for Simone to call him over]

324
00:13:57,449 --> 00:13:58,517
- Come over here.
- Yes.

325
00:13:58,517 --> 00:13:59,251
There it is.

326
00:13:59,251 --> 00:14:00,552
- Come over here.
- Yes.

327
00:14:00,552 --> 00:14:03,188
[The call he had been waiting for]

328
00:14:03,188 --> 00:14:06,658
[Past the rookie station]

329
00:14:06,658 --> 00:14:09,561
[Jealous]
[Walks right into the No.2 station]

330
00:14:09,561 --> 00:14:11,062
[Saying bye to his old mentor Lucrezia.
For now.]

331
00:14:11,062 --> 00:14:13,565
[Glance back]

332
00:14:13,565 --> 00:14:14,926
[Now Simone's his mentor!]

333
00:14:14,926 --> 00:14:16,560
Finally made it up here.

334
00:14:16,560 --> 00:14:17,560
Promotion complete.

335
00:14:17,560 --> 00:14:20,493
[Hee Tae's first task after the promotion?]
It took forever to get here.

336
00:14:20,493 --> 00:14:22,827
Let's make the potato mille-feuille.

337
00:14:22,827 --> 00:14:25,326
- Mille-feuille?
- Potato mille-feuille.

338
00:14:25,326 --> 00:14:26,678
I didn't know
you could make that with potatoes.

339
00:14:26,678 --> 00:14:29,226
[Simone's potato mille-feuille masterclass]
One and a half.

340
00:14:29,226 --> 00:14:31,182
Keep this pressed down.

341
00:14:31,182 --> 00:14:33,818
[Slice]

342
00:14:33,818 --> 00:14:36,721
[These paper-thin potato slices...]

343
00:14:37,323 --> 00:14:39,491
It comes with the roasted rabbit.

344
00:14:39,491 --> 00:14:40,625
[Potato mille-feuille served with rabbit]

345
00:14:40,625 --> 00:14:43,662
- So it's the main garnish?
- Yeah, the main garnish.

346
00:14:43,662 --> 00:14:46,331
It means "a thousand leaves."

347
00:14:46,331 --> 00:14:48,299
"A thousand leaves."

348
00:14:48,967 --> 00:14:49,993
[First task: slicing potatoes]
Try it out.

349
00:14:49,993 --> 00:14:52,637
You layer all those thin slices together.

350
00:14:52,637 --> 00:14:55,427
[Watching closely]

351
00:14:55,427 --> 00:14:59,577
[Gets right to work]

352
00:15:00,211 --> 00:15:02,827
[Slice]

353
00:15:02,827 --> 00:15:06,493
The vibe over there was totally different.

354
00:15:06,493 --> 00:15:08,920
- Much calmer.
- It felt like there was a little more time.

355
00:15:08,920 --> 00:15:11,423
It wasn't as hectic over there.

356
00:15:11,423 --> 00:15:15,727
[Even taking it easy, the pile grows fast]

357
00:15:15,727 --> 00:15:19,593
[He's already done?]

358
00:15:19,593 --> 00:15:22,032
Good. Now...

359
00:15:22,032 --> 00:15:24,527
[Hee Tae's thin potato slices]

360
00:15:24,527 --> 00:15:27,760
Stack them up like this.

361
00:15:27,760 --> 00:15:31,576
[Layering the potato slices]
You just keep stacking them.

362
00:15:31,576 --> 00:15:34,045
[Next comes the salt]

363
00:15:35,080 --> 00:15:37,427
[Two grinds of pepper!]
Sprinkle pepper twice.

364
00:15:37,427 --> 00:15:38,683
So they stick together?

365
00:15:38,683 --> 00:15:40,785
[Pour on the cream, bake it, then cut to size]
Yeah. As it cooks, it gets nice and rich.

366
00:15:40,785 --> 00:15:42,926
The cheese melts into it too.

367
00:15:42,926 --> 00:15:45,423
[Got it]

368
00:15:46,424 --> 00:15:50,595
[Speeding up]

369
00:15:50,595 --> 00:15:55,900
[Stacking them quickly and precisely]

370
00:15:56,901 --> 00:15:59,738
[Seasoning by feel]

371
00:15:59,738 --> 00:16:02,341
[Not bad...]

372
00:16:02,341 --> 00:16:03,778
He's really good at this.

373
00:16:03,778 --> 00:16:05,627
[Surprisingly generous with the pepper]

374
00:16:05,627 --> 00:16:06,945
[He's good]

375
00:16:06,945 --> 00:16:08,113
[Simone's version vs. Hee Tae's]

376
00:16:08,113 --> 00:16:10,627
[Pouring the cream just as boldly]

377
00:16:10,627 --> 00:16:11,926
Okay.

378
00:16:11,926 --> 00:16:13,260
[A little caught off guard]

379
00:16:13,260 --> 00:16:14,343
Okay.

380
00:16:14,343 --> 00:16:18,527
[Hee Tae's potato mille-feuille is ready]

381
00:16:18,527 --> 00:16:20,058
Now it goes into the oven.

382
00:16:20,058 --> 00:16:21,427
[Covering it before it goes in]

383
00:16:21,427 --> 00:16:24,562
Now for the most important part!

384
00:16:24,562 --> 00:16:26,931
[What's left?]

385
00:16:26,931 --> 00:16:29,167
[Tap tap tap tap tap]

386
00:16:29,167 --> 00:16:31,035
With love!

387
00:16:31,035 --> 00:16:33,260
[With love?]

388
00:16:33,260 --> 00:16:35,073
Okay.

389
00:16:35,073 --> 00:16:36,794
[Following Simone's lead]

390
00:16:36,794 --> 00:16:38,742
[What's he stamping on it?]
With love!

391
00:16:39,427 --> 00:16:41,078
[Great job, Hee Tae]
It's a heart.

392
00:16:41,078 --> 00:16:42,873
He made a heart?

393
00:16:44,149 --> 00:16:45,593
- Italy really is all about love.
- Always.

394
00:16:45,593 --> 00:16:49,254
- It's all about love.
- Everything here just feels so charming.

395
00:16:49,254 --> 00:16:51,923
Italy is all about love.

396
00:16:51,923 --> 00:16:54,058
Yes.

397
00:16:54,993 --> 00:16:56,060
Italy is love.

398
00:16:56,060 --> 00:16:59,030
[Hee Tae's love-filled potato mille-feuille]

399
00:16:59,030 --> 00:17:00,593
[It'll be golden and crispy soon!]

400
00:17:00,593 --> 00:17:02,567
That looks good.

401
00:17:02,567 --> 00:17:05,837
[Next task as No.2]

402
00:17:05,837 --> 00:17:09,174
[Flour goes into the mashed potatoes?]

403
00:17:09,174 --> 00:17:11,042
[One of the restaurant's signature dishes]

404
00:17:11,042 --> 00:17:12,610
[What's this?]

405
00:17:12,610 --> 00:17:14,479
- Gnocchi.
- Gnocchi.

406
00:17:14,479 --> 00:17:16,514
[Potato gnocchi]

407
00:17:16,514 --> 00:17:21,973
[A dough made with mashed potatoes and flour]

408
00:17:22,627 --> 00:17:24,585
The biggest difference from Korean gnocchi...

409
00:17:24,585 --> 00:17:27,726
[Cut into bite-sized pieces]
- is they don't pan-fry it here. - Right.

410
00:17:27,726 --> 00:17:29,059
So they boil it?

411
00:17:29,059 --> 00:17:30,428
They just boil it like pasta.

412
00:17:30,428 --> 00:17:31,460
[Cooked just like pasta]

413
00:17:31,460 --> 00:17:33,430
It's really good.

414
00:17:35,366 --> 00:17:39,603
[Gnocchi is actually...]

415
00:17:41,239 --> 00:17:42,674
[One of Sam Kim's restaurant's bestsellers]

416
00:17:42,674 --> 00:17:44,142
- You make a lot of gnocchi, right?
- We do.

417
00:17:44,142 --> 00:17:46,959
- We make it all the time.
- Chef, you're known for your gnocchi.

418
00:17:46,959 --> 00:17:49,380
You're really good at making gnocchi.

419
00:17:49,380 --> 00:17:50,682
[He's made it hundreds of times.
Can he stay undercover?]

420
00:17:50,682 --> 00:17:52,417
[Pretending it's his first time]

421
00:17:52,417 --> 00:17:55,987
[Pretending he's impressed]

422
00:17:55,987 --> 00:17:59,190
- Don't press the dough.
- Okay.

423
00:17:59,190 --> 00:18:01,125
Stretch it out instead.

424
00:18:02,427 --> 00:18:03,962
[You can do this, right?]

425
00:18:03,962 --> 00:18:07,065
[Acting mode: ON]

426
00:18:07,065 --> 00:18:09,660
[That dough isn't easy to work with...]
[Glances over]

427
00:18:09,660 --> 00:18:11,827
Here we go. Let's see how good he is.

428
00:18:11,827 --> 00:18:13,470
Gnocchi master.

429
00:18:14,305 --> 00:18:17,242
[Sneaks a look at Simone's dough]

430
00:18:17,242 --> 00:18:21,093
[Gets the thickness just right...]

431
00:18:21,093 --> 00:18:23,794
[Then cuts three ropes without being told]

432
00:18:23,794 --> 00:18:25,649
He's good.

433
00:18:26,484 --> 00:18:28,219
[Huh?]
Simone's surprised.

434
00:18:28,219 --> 00:18:30,654
He keeps watching him from the side.

435
00:18:32,660 --> 00:18:34,492
- Four at a time.
- Gosh, that's not easy.

436
00:18:34,492 --> 00:18:35,994
[Four pieces at once this time!]

437
00:18:35,994 --> 00:18:39,727
[Cutting even faster than Simone!]

438
00:18:39,727 --> 00:18:41,232
[What is this?]
He's surprised.

439
00:18:41,232 --> 00:18:42,560
Simone's going to be so shocked.

440
00:18:42,560 --> 00:18:43,827
Simone, get ready to be surprised!

441
00:18:43,827 --> 00:18:45,837
- He's surprised now.
- Get ready for it.

442
00:18:45,837 --> 00:18:47,293
- Here we go.
- This is an instant promotion.

443
00:18:47,293 --> 00:18:49,940
- You didn't care about the undercover part?
- No.

444
00:18:51,560 --> 00:18:53,744
[He's actually good?]
He's even better.

445
00:18:54,794 --> 00:19:00,560
He understood how to do it
by the second or third try.

446
00:19:00,560 --> 00:19:04,059
I could tell he had great hand skills.

447
00:19:04,059 --> 00:19:08,226
[Back in his element at the gnocchi dough]

448
00:19:08,226 --> 00:19:09,527
He's going straight for it now.

449
00:19:09,527 --> 00:19:11,129
He figured he had already proven himself once.

450
00:19:11,129 --> 00:19:13,326
[Only two days left! Time to show off!]

451
00:19:13,326 --> 00:19:16,433
- He's making a lot.
- I made a whole lot.

452
00:19:17,569 --> 00:19:20,972
[Pouring flour]

453
00:19:20,972 --> 00:19:22,941
[With a large amount of flour]

454
00:19:22,941 --> 00:19:25,643
[He starts mixing something up]

455
00:19:25,643 --> 00:19:27,011
[What is this?]

456
00:19:27,011 --> 00:19:29,326
[Stretching]

457
00:19:29,326 --> 00:19:32,293
[Showing interest]

458
00:19:32,293 --> 00:19:33,952
- Bread?
- It's focaccia dough.

459
00:19:33,952 --> 00:19:35,860
- Focaccia.
- Yes.

460
00:19:35,860 --> 00:19:37,088
Natural sourdough starter?

461
00:19:37,088 --> 00:19:38,456
Yeah, it's a sourdough starter.

462
00:19:38,456 --> 00:19:39,691
So it's a sourdough starter.

463
00:19:39,691 --> 00:19:40,858
Yeah, it's a sourdough starter.

464
00:19:40,858 --> 00:19:42,527
[A professional conversation]
So it's a sourdough starter.

465
00:19:42,527 --> 00:19:44,762
Isn't he a little too skilled at this?

466
00:19:45,363 --> 00:19:48,326
[Actually, Hee Tae...]

467
00:19:48,326 --> 00:19:50,460
[He bakes all the bread at his place]
I tend to...

468
00:19:50,460 --> 00:19:53,038
bake it myself.

469
00:19:53,038 --> 00:19:55,139
[A bread expert!]
Baking bread's his hobby.

470
00:19:55,139 --> 00:19:57,260
He was baking bread until 3 AM yesterday.

471
00:19:57,260 --> 00:19:58,543
You know he bakes when he's stressed.

472
00:19:58,543 --> 00:19:59,593
- Right.
- To relieve stress.

473
00:19:59,593 --> 00:20:00,660
- It relieves stress.
- It really does.

474
00:20:00,660 --> 00:20:03,326
It relieves his stress.

475
00:20:03,326 --> 00:20:07,520
He doesn't use dry
or fresh yeast for the dough.

476
00:20:07,520 --> 00:20:09,926
He actually has his own sourdough starter.

477
00:20:09,926 --> 00:20:11,656
He just scoops that right in.

478
00:20:11,656 --> 00:20:13,827
[Since his favorite topic came up]

479
00:20:13,827 --> 00:20:14,959
Can I do this?

480
00:20:14,959 --> 00:20:16,660
- Can I do this?
- Yes.

481
00:20:18,396 --> 00:20:19,693
[Starting to make focaccia]

482
00:20:19,693 --> 00:20:22,166
[Rosemary]
Is that going on top of the focaccia?

483
00:20:22,993 --> 00:20:25,493
[So intrigued]
I like baking bread,

484
00:20:25,493 --> 00:20:27,205
so I watched him making it very closely.

485
00:20:27,205 --> 00:20:29,440
He's interested since he bakes too.

486
00:20:29,440 --> 00:20:30,675
[What else goes in here?]
Baking's fun too.

487
00:20:30,675 --> 00:20:32,860
[Sneak a peek]

488
00:20:32,860 --> 00:20:33,852
Olives?

489
00:20:33,852 --> 00:20:35,580
- Olive oil.
- Olive oil.

490
00:20:35,580 --> 00:20:39,383
They add the olive oil at the very end here.

491
00:20:40,084 --> 00:20:43,320
[Grinding rosemary and olive oil]

492
00:20:45,056 --> 00:20:46,891
Rosemary focaccia.

493
00:20:46,891 --> 00:20:50,194
[Mixing it in the machine]

494
00:20:50,194 --> 00:20:55,126
[Parma restaurant's focaccia dough]

495
00:20:55,126 --> 00:20:56,293
That part's also very important.

496
00:20:56,293 --> 00:20:57,235
- The folding.
- Folding.

497
00:20:57,235 --> 00:21:01,072
They call it folding when you fold the dough.

498
00:21:01,072 --> 00:21:03,174
When you put your hands in the dough,

499
00:21:03,174 --> 00:21:04,742
you can feel how elastic it is.

500
00:21:04,742 --> 00:21:06,844
[Having so much fun]
And you'll know if it's tight enough...

501
00:21:06,844 --> 00:21:07,845
He's unstoppable.

502
00:21:07,845 --> 00:21:09,741
to bake well.

503
00:21:09,741 --> 00:21:12,477
[While Simone steps away for a bit]

504
00:21:13,251 --> 00:21:18,063
[The dough left all alone]

505
00:21:18,063 --> 00:21:20,158
[Poking]

506
00:21:20,158 --> 00:21:22,226
[Stroking]

507
00:21:22,226 --> 00:21:24,228
[How's the dough at this place?]
He's curious.

508
00:21:24,228 --> 00:21:26,364
I got curious, so I touched it.

509
00:21:26,364 --> 00:21:28,599
[Forgets undercover, excited for bread]
It was puffy.

510
00:21:29,301 --> 00:21:31,794
- Do you want to try?
- Yes.

511
00:21:31,794 --> 00:21:33,538
[A chance to show off his folding!]
Why do you fold it?

512
00:21:33,538 --> 00:21:35,406
You have to fold it to create layers.

513
00:21:35,406 --> 00:21:36,708
- It makes air pockets.
- Exactly.

514
00:21:36,708 --> 00:21:37,794
- So the bread gets soft.
- Right.

515
00:21:37,794 --> 00:21:39,393
[Crucial step for the bread's softness]
Same here.

516
00:21:39,393 --> 00:21:41,645
[Excited]
Fold it and close it.

517
00:21:44,315 --> 00:21:45,460
[Flip]

518
00:21:45,460 --> 00:21:47,318
Good.

519
00:21:47,318 --> 00:21:49,787
[That's a very advanced skill!]
You can't do that at first.

520
00:21:49,787 --> 00:21:51,722
[Hmm, what?]
They can't do it at first.

521
00:21:53,460 --> 00:21:54,425
Yes.

522
00:21:54,425 --> 00:21:56,593
[What farmer folds dough this well?]

523
00:21:56,593 --> 00:21:58,196
Yes.

524
00:21:58,196 --> 00:21:59,827
Now fold it well.

525
00:21:59,827 --> 00:22:01,065
Lift it up.

526
00:22:01,065 --> 00:22:03,067
[Hee Tae's active time post-pasta zone]

527
00:22:03,067 --> 00:22:04,802
Exactly. Now like this.

528
00:22:04,802 --> 00:22:09,006
[Service Starts at 12:00 PM]

529
00:22:09,006 --> 00:22:11,008
- The weather's great.
- Yeah, it's so nice out.

530
00:22:11,008 --> 00:22:13,311
[Customers start trickling in]

531
00:22:13,311 --> 00:22:16,660
[The Parma restaurant quickly gets busy]

532
00:22:16,660 --> 00:22:19,059
First service since his promotion.

533
00:22:19,059 --> 00:22:20,284
- Hee Tae.
- Yes.

534
00:22:20,284 --> 00:22:22,653
Come over here!

535
00:22:22,653 --> 00:22:25,289
Sorem, keep working here from now on!

536
00:22:26,190 --> 00:22:27,859
Sorem's back.

537
00:22:27,859 --> 00:22:30,862
- He got his old spot back.
- He's returned.

538
00:22:30,862 --> 00:22:32,396
[Hee Tae]

539
00:22:32,396 --> 00:22:36,059
[Promoted!]

540
00:22:36,059 --> 00:22:38,770
[Looking good, Hee Tae]

541
00:22:38,770 --> 00:22:40,504
[He can't hide his smile]
He got promoted already.

542
00:22:41,427 --> 00:22:43,274
[What orders will Hee Tae get post-promotion?]

543
00:22:43,274 --> 00:22:46,356
Assorted salumi, fried torta bread,

544
00:22:46,356 --> 00:22:50,414
veal sweetbreads, tagliatelle, potato gnocchi.

545
00:22:50,414 --> 00:22:52,727
[Hee Tae's task in Zone 2 is...]
Two portions of cooked shoulder.

546
00:22:52,727 --> 00:22:54,627
It's the salumi platter!

547
00:22:54,627 --> 00:22:56,487
- Salumi platter?
- Salumi platter.

548
00:22:56,487 --> 00:22:58,356
Coppa, pancetta.

549
00:22:58,356 --> 00:23:00,093
Prosciutto, salame.

550
00:23:00,093 --> 00:23:02,126
So...

551
00:23:02,126 --> 00:23:04,629
Is this the home of salumi?

552
00:23:04,629 --> 00:23:07,765
You could say this region's the main hub.

553
00:23:07,765 --> 00:23:13,303
[Northern Italy's classic sliced cured meat]

554
00:23:13,303 --> 00:23:15,840
[A customer favorite on every single table]
The base flavor's pretty salty, right?

555
00:23:15,840 --> 00:23:18,543
Naturally, since it's cured.

556
00:23:18,543 --> 00:23:22,188
[Salty, perfect with a glass of wine]

557
00:23:22,188 --> 00:23:24,627
[Zone 2 first task: Serving salumi]

558
00:23:24,627 --> 00:23:25,783
Okay?

559
00:23:25,783 --> 00:23:29,059
[Simone's demonstration first]

560
00:23:29,059 --> 00:23:33,959
Slicing salumi's not a simple task.

561
00:23:33,959 --> 00:23:37,062
Controlling the thickness is crucial.

562
00:23:37,062 --> 00:23:40,031
- It takes a feel for it.
- It's all about feel.

563
00:23:40,031 --> 00:23:42,867
Depending on whether a slice
is thicker or thinner,

564
00:23:42,867 --> 00:23:47,672
the taste and texture change completely.

565
00:23:47,672 --> 00:23:51,075
That's coppa, which is from the pork collar.

566
00:23:51,075 --> 00:23:52,143
- This one.
- Pancetta.

567
00:23:52,143 --> 00:23:53,360
- The pork belly.
- Okay.

568
00:23:53,360 --> 00:23:54,346
It's like pork belly.

569
00:23:54,346 --> 00:23:57,615
[Looking closely]

570
00:23:57,615 --> 00:24:00,751
[Looking at the thickness of the pancetta...]

571
00:24:00,751 --> 00:24:02,119
[Coppa, Pancetta]

572
00:24:02,119 --> 00:24:06,624
[Even softer and thinner than the coppa!]

573
00:24:06,624 --> 00:24:09,126
[Figuring out the thickness for each meat]

574
00:24:09,126 --> 00:24:12,496
- Crudo.
- You can think of crudo as prosciutto.

575
00:24:12,496 --> 00:24:15,632
- Prosciutto, the leg.
- With the fat on top!

576
00:24:16,367 --> 00:24:20,504
[Coppa, pancetta]
[More fat for Prosciutto!]

577
00:24:20,504 --> 00:24:22,041
[Cutting methods vary by part]

578
00:24:22,041 --> 00:24:23,193
- Depending on the part?
- Yes.

579
00:24:23,193 --> 00:24:25,009
Made from pork belly...

580
00:24:25,009 --> 00:24:28,045
[Fourth meat: Salame]
Salame's made like sausage.

581
00:24:30,848 --> 00:24:32,660
They plate it like that
because each one tastes different, right?

582
00:24:32,660 --> 00:24:34,318
- By part.
- Each part tastes different.

583
00:24:34,318 --> 00:24:35,653
The fat has a different flavor.

584
00:24:35,653 --> 00:24:39,993
[Thin salumi slices melt fast in your mouth]

585
00:24:39,993 --> 00:24:41,525
[Boasting an ultimate soft texture]
Honestly, you really need

586
00:24:41,525 --> 00:24:43,360
a lot of practice for this.

587
00:24:43,360 --> 00:24:45,696
- I don't think it's easy to do well at first.
- It's really hard.

588
00:24:45,696 --> 00:24:47,565
Now...

589
00:24:47,565 --> 00:24:49,000
Give it a try, Hee Tae!

590
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:50,901
- Me?
- Yes.

591
00:24:51,993 --> 00:24:53,971
That's harder than it looks.

592
00:24:53,971 --> 00:24:56,326
- The meats all have different shapes.
- The meats?

593
00:24:56,326 --> 00:24:59,176
- So you have to adjust the thickness.
- Right.

594
00:24:59,176 --> 00:25:01,512
[Worried if he can slice it properly]

595
00:25:01,512 --> 00:25:05,959
[Forgot about him]
[Chestnut hair]

596
00:25:05,959 --> 00:25:06,951
Sorem.

597
00:25:06,951 --> 00:25:08,819
[Sorem stuck in pasta zone after Hee Tae left]

598
00:25:08,819 --> 00:25:10,288
[Glance]
[Is he mindful of Hee Tae at Zone two?]

599
00:25:10,288 --> 00:25:12,956
[Curious]

600
00:25:14,026 --> 00:25:15,559
It didn't bother me.

601
00:25:15,559 --> 00:25:17,328
I just thought that through this experience,

602
00:25:17,328 --> 00:25:20,998
he should try as many things as possible.

603
00:25:20,998 --> 00:25:23,200
That's all!

604
00:25:23,200 --> 00:25:24,568
[Completely indifferent]

605
00:25:24,568 --> 00:25:26,794
He really doesn't care, right?

606
00:25:26,794 --> 00:25:28,239
Does Sorem have no ambition?

607
00:25:28,239 --> 00:25:29,907
- His face already said it all.
- Right.

608
00:25:29,907 --> 00:25:31,609
[The youngest, happy with his own spot]

609
00:25:31,609 --> 00:25:34,779
[Likewise, he has no time to worry about him]
Pork?

610
00:25:34,779 --> 00:25:37,615
[Hee Tae's first real task: Slicing meat]

611
00:25:37,615 --> 00:25:41,018
[The key is to slice it thin and wide]

612
00:25:41,018 --> 00:25:42,553
[Anticipation]
Let's see.

613
00:25:42,553 --> 00:25:44,622
He'll probably nail it on the first try, right?

614
00:25:44,622 --> 00:25:48,325
[Slicing slowly with everyone watching]

615
00:25:50,663 --> 00:25:52,763
What's wrong?

616
00:25:52,763 --> 00:25:56,267
[Pushing it slowly again]

617
00:25:56,267 --> 00:25:58,093
- Why?
- What's wrong?

618
00:25:58,093 --> 00:26:02,072
[Is something wrong?]

619
00:26:03,059 --> 00:26:04,175
[What?]

620
00:26:04,175 --> 00:26:06,076
What's that?

621
00:26:06,711 --> 00:26:08,660
[Wrinkled]

622
00:26:08,660 --> 00:26:10,427
- Huh?
- What?

623
00:26:10,427 --> 00:26:11,481
[Awkward]
What's that?

624
00:26:11,481 --> 00:26:13,385
[What happened to the meat?]

625
00:26:13,385 --> 00:26:14,618
- Wait.
- Huh?

626
00:26:14,618 --> 00:26:16,660
Gosh.

627
00:26:16,660 --> 00:26:18,922
[Hahaha]

628
00:26:20,527 --> 00:26:21,760
[Tries a few more times, still looks messy]

629
00:26:21,760 --> 00:26:23,894
- Huh?
- What?

630
00:26:23,894 --> 00:26:26,897
- He has to throw all of that away.
- What's going on? What's he going to do?

631
00:26:26,897 --> 00:26:28,799
[Eyes shaking]

632
00:26:28,799 --> 00:26:32,026
Try to catch it as it's coming out.

633
00:26:32,026 --> 00:26:34,005
Look here.

634
00:26:34,005 --> 00:26:35,339
[Hahaha]

635
00:26:35,339 --> 00:26:38,126
- Wait.
- Why is he laughing at him?

636
00:26:38,126 --> 00:26:39,593
[Sorem, really?]
I didn't know that.

637
00:26:39,593 --> 00:26:41,926
- Gosh, seriously.
- I had no idea.

638
00:26:41,926 --> 00:26:45,182
[While Sorem secretly laughs]

639
00:26:45,182 --> 00:26:46,593
[Hee Tae's slicing isn't going as planned]

640
00:26:46,593 --> 00:26:48,319
This is actually not that easy.

641
00:26:48,319 --> 00:26:50,354
When it gets close to the machine,

642
00:26:50,354 --> 00:26:53,224
you have to push it slowly!

643
00:26:53,224 --> 00:26:55,293
- Ah, slowly!
- Slowly.

644
00:26:55,293 --> 00:26:57,959
[Requires perfect strength and speed control]

645
00:26:57,959 --> 00:26:59,059
- Ah, slowly!
- Yeah.

646
00:26:59,059 --> 00:27:00,260
So you can grab it well.

647
00:27:00,260 --> 00:27:03,200
- It's not easy for a beginner.
- It's really tough.

648
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:05,627
The whole slice needs to come out evenly.

649
00:27:05,627 --> 00:27:07,527
- Right.
- Cleanly.

650
00:27:07,527 --> 00:27:11,074
[Focuses and pushes it again]

651
00:27:12,326 --> 00:27:14,427
[Controlling the strength is tough]
When you're near...

652
00:27:14,427 --> 00:27:15,860
Near.

653
00:27:15,860 --> 00:27:18,315
[Hee Tae eventually gets pushed back]
Near.

654
00:27:18,315 --> 00:27:20,260
[Embarrassed]
[Whimper]

655
00:27:20,260 --> 00:27:21,552
Near the slice.

656
00:27:21,552 --> 00:27:22,653
Do it like this.

657
00:27:22,653 --> 00:27:24,660
[Try cutting it to the thickness of prosciutto]

658
00:27:24,660 --> 00:27:26,430
[Another chance]
Okay.

659
00:27:26,430 --> 00:27:28,025
This is his chance.

660
00:27:28,025 --> 00:27:32,029
[Pushing it slowly as he learned]

661
00:27:32,029 --> 00:27:35,398
[Focusing]

662
00:27:37,101 --> 00:27:39,236
[A perfectly clean cut]

663
00:27:39,236 --> 00:27:41,438
He got the hang of it now!

664
00:27:43,541 --> 00:27:48,179
[Catches it perfectly onto the plate]

665
00:27:48,179 --> 00:27:49,380
[Mastered the strength and speed]

666
00:27:49,380 --> 00:27:52,383
[Nods]

667
00:27:52,383 --> 00:27:53,517
Very quickly.

668
00:27:53,517 --> 00:27:56,120
[Successfully got the hang of it]

669
00:27:56,120 --> 00:27:59,089
[No. 1 joins in]
Good, one more!

670
00:27:59,790 --> 00:28:02,460
[Watching closely]
That must be so much pressure!

671
00:28:02,460 --> 00:28:03,727
That's really a lot of pressure.

672
00:28:03,727 --> 00:28:07,531
[Perfect cut and size]

673
00:28:07,531 --> 00:28:08,827
[Good job, Hee Tae]

674
00:28:08,827 --> 00:28:11,026
Let's try the salame now.

675
00:28:11,026 --> 00:28:12,803
Let's try the salame now.

676
00:28:12,803 --> 00:28:14,838
[Slicing the salame thickly with a knife]
Three slices.

677
00:28:16,093 --> 00:28:17,274
He's gotten so good at it.

678
00:28:17,274 --> 00:28:18,909
[Knife skills are my specialty]

679
00:28:18,909 --> 00:28:20,277
[Glance]

680
00:28:20,277 --> 00:28:22,026
He watches everything so closely.

681
00:28:22,026 --> 00:28:23,614
[Shy]
Pretending to do something else.

682
00:28:23,614 --> 00:28:26,250
[Perfect thickness]

683
00:28:26,250 --> 00:28:30,020
[Satisfied]

684
00:28:30,020 --> 00:28:32,889
[Adding the nicely cut salame]

685
00:28:34,091 --> 00:28:36,827
[Hee Tae's first salumi platter is done]
Oh, that looks delicious.

686
00:28:36,827 --> 00:28:39,797
- The fat renders out after a bit.
- Right.

687
00:28:39,797 --> 00:28:41,193
[Glossy and salty salumi platter]
It looks so glossy.

688
00:28:41,193 --> 00:28:43,134
When left at room temperature.

689
00:28:43,134 --> 00:28:44,502
[Must serve with fried torta bread]

690
00:28:44,502 --> 00:28:47,137
- Ah, like that.
- That looks delicious.

691
00:28:48,405 --> 00:28:50,274
- Fried torta bread.
- Okay.

692
00:28:50,274 --> 00:28:53,010
[Second task is fried torta bread]

693
00:28:53,010 --> 00:28:54,211
One and two.

694
00:28:54,211 --> 00:28:56,646
[Wait a minute]

695
00:28:57,427 --> 00:28:59,293
[He used to just make and pass them]
Exactly. You only...

696
00:28:59,293 --> 00:29:01,818
- handed them over.
- Right.

697
00:29:02,488 --> 00:29:04,888
[That fried torta bread]
The fried bread.

698
00:29:05,523 --> 00:29:09,293
[Now with Sorem's torta dough]

699
00:29:09,293 --> 00:29:11,529
- Fried torta bread.
- He's frying it himself now.

700
00:29:11,529 --> 00:29:12,763
[Hee Tae gets it and fries it]
He moved up to that spot.

701
00:29:12,763 --> 00:29:14,598
One and two.

702
00:29:15,794 --> 00:29:18,469
Watch it, you could get burned with oil.

703
00:29:18,469 --> 00:29:20,971
[Watching closely]

704
00:29:20,971 --> 00:29:25,009
[The dough puffs up in the oil]
Do you see how it puffed up like this?

705
00:29:25,009 --> 00:29:27,926
[Plump]

706
00:29:27,926 --> 00:29:30,527
[When it starts turning golden]
Colored.

707
00:29:30,527 --> 00:29:32,393
[Tap]
Now...

708
00:29:32,393 --> 00:29:35,019
He taps it right here, and it flips over.

709
00:29:35,019 --> 00:29:37,568
[Oh!]

710
00:29:39,316 --> 00:29:44,395
[Flipping it at once with a wrist snap]

711
00:29:44,395 --> 00:29:47,126
[This is the skill of No. 2]

712
00:29:47,126 --> 00:29:49,633
[Understood]

713
00:29:49,633 --> 00:29:51,293
Two portions of fried bread.

714
00:29:51,293 --> 00:29:52,836
Eight pieces!

715
00:29:52,836 --> 00:29:55,360
One portion equals four pieces.

716
00:29:55,360 --> 00:29:57,808
Okay? Fried bread.

717
00:29:57,808 --> 00:30:01,579
[Slowly putting the dough into the oil]

718
00:30:01,579 --> 00:30:06,517
Don't put your hands in too deep,
you'll get hurt.

719
00:30:06,517 --> 00:30:09,553
I saw him practically toss it in earlier.
Like this, from above.

720
00:30:09,553 --> 00:30:12,223
[Flipping it at the perfect time]

721
00:30:12,223 --> 00:30:15,492
[Focusing so it doesn't overcook]

722
00:30:15,492 --> 00:30:18,028
[Perfectly golden timing]

723
00:30:18,028 --> 00:30:20,463
[Excited with satisfaction]

724
00:30:21,732 --> 00:30:23,035
[Plating it beautifully]

725
00:30:23,035 --> 00:30:24,335
- I'm curious.
- I think it'll be delicious.

726
00:30:24,335 --> 00:30:26,069
- Yeah.
- It's delicious.

727
00:30:27,271 --> 00:30:30,374
[Hee Tae's first salumi and torta]

728
00:30:30,374 --> 00:30:32,109
[Finally, Hee Tae's first dish]

729
00:30:32,109 --> 00:30:33,727
[Arrives at the customer's table]

730
00:30:33,727 --> 00:30:35,114
Salame platter.

731
00:30:35,114 --> 00:30:38,560
