Salame, coppa, pancetta, prosciutto.

732
00:30:38,560 --> 00:30:40,517
How will they react? I'm so curious.

733
00:30:40,517 --> 00:30:42,319
[Will they enjoy it?]

734
00:30:42,319 --> 00:30:44,989
- It's good.
- It's delicious.

735
00:30:44,989 --> 00:30:46,089
[What a relief]

736
00:30:46,089 --> 00:30:49,359
[Nodding in satisfaction]

737
00:30:50,327 --> 00:30:53,631
[This is nice]

738
00:30:53,631 --> 00:30:56,634
[Everyone loves Hee Tae's salumi]
I want to join them and eat too.

739
00:30:56,634 --> 00:30:58,669
- That looks good.
- Just relaxing like that,

740
00:30:58,669 --> 00:31:00,804
having a glass of wine.

741
00:31:01,599 --> 00:31:03,393
[Orders keep coming in]
Two salumi platters, two fried breads,

742
00:31:03,393 --> 00:31:04,675
Two of each salumi and fried torta,

743
00:31:04,675 --> 00:31:05,643
- one culaccia, extra pickled onions.
- Seriously.

744
00:31:05,643 --> 00:31:06,760
- Two erbetta.
- It's busy.

745
00:31:06,760 --> 00:31:08,946
- Two green tagliatelle.
- It's really busy.

746
00:31:08,946 --> 00:31:11,115
[Setting up the meats right away]

747
00:31:11,115 --> 00:31:13,893
[Hee Tae takes over the meat slicer]

748
00:31:15,286 --> 00:31:17,954
[Zero mistakes with every slice now]

749
00:31:18,555 --> 00:31:21,659
[Already a salumi master]

750
00:31:21,659 --> 00:31:23,160
[Watching Hee Tae fill up the plates]

751
00:31:23,160 --> 00:31:25,894
[Satisfied nod]

752
00:31:25,894 --> 00:31:27,898
[Frying the torta bread perfectly]
He works really hard.

753
00:31:27,898 --> 00:31:30,768
[Perfectly handled four orders]

754
00:31:30,768 --> 00:31:33,560
[Hee Tae moving busily at his new spot]

755
00:31:33,560 --> 00:31:35,973
[Simone watched him all service long]
He keeps watching him.

756
00:31:35,973 --> 00:31:39,427
[And the main chef No. 1]
[Good!]

757
00:31:39,427 --> 00:31:40,446
Got it.

758
00:31:40,446 --> 00:31:42,278
Perfect!

759
00:31:43,026 --> 00:31:45,493
He did well.

760
00:31:45,493 --> 00:31:47,518
I've seen people do much worse
when they first come to that spot.

761
00:31:47,518 --> 00:31:49,427
[Right]

762
00:31:49,427 --> 00:31:52,056
Hee Tae's adapting well

763
00:31:52,056 --> 00:31:55,293
to the way we work here.

764
00:31:55,293 --> 00:31:58,293
That's definitely worthy of praise.

765
00:31:58,293 --> 00:32:03,226
Hee Tae's already doing things on his own
before I even say anything.

766
00:32:03,226 --> 00:32:05,102
He's already doing it himself.

767
00:32:05,102 --> 00:32:09,173
He's only worked here for three days,
but he adapted perfectly.

768
00:32:09,173 --> 00:32:12,869
[Successfully finished his first service
after the promotion]

769
00:32:12,869 --> 00:32:13,993
[And the staff gathered around No. 1...]
All of a sudden...

770
00:32:13,993 --> 00:32:15,813
What is he doing? What are they up to?

771
00:32:15,813 --> 00:32:17,815
[Reading the room...]

772
00:32:17,815 --> 00:32:19,983
[What is this? What is this vibe?]
What's going on?

773
00:32:21,393 --> 00:32:22,693
Hee Tae! Tomorrow...

774
00:32:22,693 --> 00:32:24,655
Yes.

775
00:32:24,655 --> 00:32:26,427
Make the staff meal for us!

776
00:32:26,427 --> 00:32:28,859
- What?
- What?

777
00:32:28,859 --> 00:32:30,296
What does that mean?

778
00:32:30,296 --> 00:32:32,260
Staff meal!

779
00:32:32,260 --> 00:32:34,264
[Staff meal duty right after promotion?]
- Really? - What?

780
00:32:34,264 --> 00:32:35,699
- They just let you do everything here.
- Here...

781
00:32:35,699 --> 00:32:37,360
- He didn't even ask to do it.
- Here, you have to ask.

782
00:32:37,360 --> 00:32:39,828
- They just tell him to do it?
- They're making him do it.

783
00:32:39,828 --> 00:32:40,995
They just let him do everything.

784
00:32:40,995 --> 00:32:42,372
[The life of an ace newbie]

785
00:32:42,372 --> 00:32:44,093
- I'm so jealous...
- I know.

786
00:32:44,093 --> 00:32:45,609
- The system is completely different.
- Right.

787
00:32:45,609 --> 00:32:46,794
We tried so hard to do it.

788
00:32:46,794 --> 00:32:48,848
[Thought you had to earn the staff meal?]
That place is nice.

789
00:32:48,848 --> 00:32:51,181
[Hee Tae gets a new chance after promotion]

790
00:32:51,181 --> 00:32:53,650
Okay, I'll give it a try!

791
00:32:53,650 --> 00:32:55,460
[Nervous]

792
00:32:55,460 --> 00:32:57,054
I understand.

793
00:32:57,054 --> 00:32:59,794
When they told me to make the staff meal...

794
00:32:59,794 --> 00:33:01,660
I started to see what the chef was going for.

795
00:33:01,660 --> 00:33:03,761
I mean... I thought it might be a test

796
00:33:03,761 --> 00:33:05,226
- for another promotion.
- Exactly.

797
00:33:05,226 --> 00:33:07,531
- Let's just see how he does.
- Yeah.

798
00:33:07,531 --> 00:33:11,301
We're testing his skills with the staff meal.

799
00:33:11,301 --> 00:33:14,605
We want to see how good he is
and how he handles the heat.

800
00:33:14,605 --> 00:33:18,187
Depending on how the staff meal turns out,

801
00:33:18,187 --> 00:33:20,978
I might put him next to me
for tomorrow's lunch service.

802
00:33:20,978 --> 00:33:24,782
[This is a test for the next level!]
Exactly, you read the room perfectly.

803
00:33:24,782 --> 00:33:25,918
- Okay.
- Yes.

804
00:33:25,918 --> 00:33:28,018
[Maximum pressure]
Oh, yes. Good!

805
00:33:28,018 --> 00:33:30,888
[Smiling on the outside but...]

806
00:33:30,888 --> 00:33:32,956
[The tension starts to build up]
[Lips drying up]

807
00:33:32,956 --> 00:33:35,191
What should you do?

808
00:33:36,026 --> 00:33:40,230
[Hee Tae returned to work after the break]

809
00:33:40,230 --> 00:33:42,766
[While prepping for dinner service]
My biggest worry right now is...

810
00:33:42,766 --> 00:33:46,036
Making the staff meal has always been
a bit stressful for me.

811
00:33:46,036 --> 00:33:48,772
[Oh man, Hee Tae!]

812
00:33:48,772 --> 00:33:50,808
[Only thinking about tomorrow's staff meal]

813
00:33:50,808 --> 00:33:52,476
[Deep worries, how will his staff meal be?]

814
00:33:52,476 --> 00:33:54,344
What's he going to make?

815
00:33:56,680 --> 00:33:58,215
[Sam Kwon, not Sung Jun, in Naples, Italy]
Our Chef Kwon Sung Jun...

816
00:33:58,215 --> 00:33:59,783
[Day 3 undercover]
The three days he promised...

817
00:33:59,783 --> 00:34:03,387
are down to just half a day.

818
00:34:03,387 --> 00:34:05,622
The biggest opportunity for chefs is...

819
00:34:05,622 --> 00:34:06,857
He looks so determined.

820
00:34:06,857 --> 00:34:11,962
Laura. Do you mind if I make lunch today?

821
00:34:11,962 --> 00:34:13,130
Of course.

822
00:34:13,130 --> 00:34:14,798
[Kwon volunteers to make lunch staff meal]

823
00:34:14,798 --> 00:34:19,303
[Secret weapon: authentic Naples risotto]

824
00:34:19,303 --> 00:34:22,773
[The first taster is Boss Laura]

825
00:34:22,773 --> 00:34:24,308
[Nervous]

826
00:34:24,308 --> 00:34:26,977
I feel like he served this to us...

827
00:34:26,977 --> 00:34:30,581
with a lot of respect.

828
00:34:30,581 --> 00:34:34,051
I like Kwon's idea, and it tastes good too.

829
00:34:34,051 --> 00:34:35,986
- She read him perfectly. His intention.
- She caught on right away.

830
00:34:35,986 --> 00:34:37,820
As expected of the boss.

831
00:34:38,522 --> 00:34:40,324
[But...]
Why does she look doubtful?

832
00:34:40,324 --> 00:34:46,930
As a menu item, it's too simple.

833
00:34:46,930 --> 00:34:51,301
[Disappointing because it's too simple]
They need to be menu-worthy.

834
00:34:51,301 --> 00:34:52,402
[Admit]

835
00:34:52,402 --> 00:34:54,805
[Senior Paolo, Senior Antonio]
[The remaining two seniors]

836
00:34:54,805 --> 00:34:58,075
[What will his closest seniors say?]

837
00:34:58,075 --> 00:35:00,744
[Senior Paolo takes a bite first]

838
00:35:00,744 --> 00:35:02,880
[Curious]
I wonder what he'll say.

839
00:35:02,880 --> 00:35:04,681
Paolo, it's good, right?

840
00:35:04,681 --> 00:35:07,184
Kwon's risotto has everything I like.

841
00:35:07,184 --> 00:35:08,493
It's cooked perfectly too.

842
00:35:08,493 --> 00:35:09,987
The most important thing for risotto
is how it's cooked.

843
00:35:09,987 --> 00:35:11,154
[Shrugs proudly]

844
00:35:11,154 --> 00:35:13,991
[Following the boss,
Paolo also gives it high praise]

845
00:35:13,991 --> 00:35:15,058
[Finally, Senior Antonio takes a bite]

846
00:35:15,058 --> 00:35:17,327
[Full of anticipation]
Senior Antonio.

847
00:35:17,327 --> 00:35:20,930
[What will Senior Antonio's review be?]

848
00:35:23,033 --> 00:35:25,702
[Sigh?]
What's wrong? What's with his face?

849
00:35:25,702 --> 00:35:27,371
Hold on.

850
00:35:27,371 --> 00:35:29,706
I'll say it's fifty-fifty.

851
00:35:29,706 --> 00:35:32,593
- I'll say it's fifty-fifty.
- Fifty-fifty?

852
00:35:32,593 --> 00:35:34,585
- Because he did half of the work himself.
- Senior Antonio...

853
00:35:34,585 --> 00:35:37,814
- He's not acknowledging it?
- What's with him all of a sudden?

854
00:35:37,814 --> 00:35:39,261
I think it tasted good.

855
00:35:39,261 --> 00:35:42,188
Right, the taste was excellent.

856
00:35:42,188 --> 00:35:45,322
But to be honest...
there are parts that are Naples-style

857
00:35:45,322 --> 00:35:47,758
- and parts that aren't.
- So there were parts that weren't. Right.

858
00:35:47,758 --> 00:35:49,560
Didn't you say it was authentic?

859
00:35:49,560 --> 00:35:52,162
What part isn't authentic?

860
00:35:52,162 --> 00:35:53,727
For example, we don't use white wine.

861
00:35:53,727 --> 00:35:55,432
No, we don't like it.

862
00:35:55,432 --> 00:35:59,303
- We don't add white wine when we cook.
- We don't do it like that.

863
00:35:59,303 --> 00:36:01,605
I want to add white wine.

864
00:36:01,605 --> 00:36:02,874
- White wine?
- Yes.

865
00:36:02,874 --> 00:36:05,576
[Kwon added white wine to his tomato risotto]

866
00:36:05,576 --> 00:36:08,111
[That's not our style]

867
00:36:08,111 --> 00:36:09,713
White wine! They don't use things like that!

868
00:36:09,713 --> 00:36:11,827
[Wait...]
I told you! I said it was weird!

869
00:36:11,827 --> 00:36:14,918
- I said it'd taste like grapes.
- White wine is my preference.

870
00:36:14,918 --> 00:36:17,654
Come on. If you were going to do that,
you should've gone a different route.

871
00:36:17,654 --> 00:36:19,056
[I love Chef Kwon's vibe]
The reason I added this is...

872
00:36:19,056 --> 00:36:21,625
I don't know what's in that tomato sauce.

873
00:36:21,625 --> 00:36:25,329
It's not just puree.
It's a sauce they made beforehand.

874
00:36:25,329 --> 00:36:28,198
Since it was boiled down,
it lacked some acidity when I tasted it.

875
00:36:28,198 --> 00:36:29,900
So that's why I added white wine.

876
00:36:29,900 --> 00:36:31,568
[Anyway, in conclusion]

877
00:36:31,568 --> 00:36:33,637
It was closer to Milan style.

878
00:36:33,637 --> 00:36:35,772
- Risotto is originally from Milan.
- It's Milan style?

879
00:36:35,772 --> 00:36:37,708
[Playing dumb]
Milan...

880
00:36:37,708 --> 00:36:39,042
[What does that even mean...]
Milan...

881
00:36:39,042 --> 00:36:41,712
[Q. So you are saying it's not Naples style?]

882
00:36:41,712 --> 00:36:44,731
No, the overall vibe is right.

883
00:36:46,316 --> 00:36:48,964
- Because things like tomatoes, provola cheese,
- Tomato, provola...

884
00:36:48,964 --> 00:36:50,627
and basil...

885
00:36:50,627 --> 00:36:53,724
are the most commonly used ingredients
here in Naples.

886
00:36:53,724 --> 00:36:56,727
It's like a harmony
between the South and the North.

887
00:36:56,727 --> 00:36:59,763
[Overall review: Good but a bit ambiguous]

888
00:36:59,763 --> 00:37:01,264
Ten minutes.

889
00:37:01,264 --> 00:37:03,508
[Glance]

890
00:37:03,508 --> 00:37:05,966
[Glances again]
What?

891
00:37:06,703 --> 00:37:08,639
[Leftover tomato risotto]

892
00:37:08,639 --> 00:37:10,674
I'll have another bowl.

893
00:37:10,674 --> 00:37:12,275
[Proud]
I need more.

894
00:37:12,275 --> 00:37:14,645
She must've liked it. It suits her taste.

895
00:37:14,645 --> 00:37:16,313
Who wants some more?

896
00:37:16,313 --> 00:37:18,551
[Scraping every last bit onto the plate]
I would like it.

897
00:37:18,551 --> 00:37:19,690
I knew it.

898
00:37:19,690 --> 00:37:21,985
[Oh, so good]

899
00:37:21,985 --> 00:37:23,932
They still scraped their plates clean.

900
00:37:23,932 --> 00:37:25,956
It was seriously good.

901
00:37:25,956 --> 00:37:28,759
[Empty plates before they knew it]

902
00:37:28,759 --> 00:37:31,595
[As the meal wraps up]

903
00:37:31,595 --> 00:37:34,230
What are some good traditional Korean dishes?

904
00:37:35,565 --> 00:37:37,401
[Thinking about what to say about Korean food]

905
00:37:37,401 --> 00:37:40,727
Among the really famous ones...
there's meat braised in soy sauce.

906
00:37:40,727 --> 00:37:41,538
Galbi.

907
00:37:41,538 --> 00:37:43,807
- For example, braised in soy sauce.
- Like braised short ribs.

908
00:37:43,807 --> 00:37:45,876
[Beef bulgogi, braised pork ribs]
Braised short ribs are delicious.

909
00:37:45,876 --> 00:37:47,794
- Fried chicken is good too.
- Fried chicken is delicious.

910
00:37:47,794 --> 00:37:50,280
- It's very famous.
- Yes.

911
00:37:50,280 --> 00:37:54,593
Then how about a Korean chicken dish
for lunch tomorrow?

912
00:37:54,593 --> 00:37:56,331
- Sure.
- I'm in trouble.

913
00:37:56,331 --> 00:37:58,388
I have to do this every day now.

914
00:37:58,388 --> 00:37:59,623
If you make a staff meal this good,

915
00:37:59,623 --> 00:38:01,291
- you're stuck doing it every day.
- Right.

916
00:38:01,291 --> 00:38:04,995
- That means you got acknowledged again.
- I just got more work.

917
00:38:04,995 --> 00:38:07,731
[A Korean fried chicken dish...]
Korean food... Understood.

918
00:38:07,731 --> 00:38:10,500
[Looking forward to it, Kwon]

919
00:38:10,500 --> 00:38:12,202
Sung Jun has to fry chicken tomorrow.

920
00:38:12,202 --> 00:38:13,503
Or make Andong jjimdak.

921
00:38:13,503 --> 00:38:16,673
[Receiving a second staff meal proposal
that feels like a mission]

922
00:38:16,673 --> 00:38:20,010
[Staff lunch ends in great success!]

923
00:38:20,010 --> 00:38:23,080
How were your second and third days?

924
00:38:23,080 --> 00:38:25,816
[Small talk before service]
How many days now?

925
00:38:25,816 --> 00:38:27,918
How has it been so far?

926
00:38:27,918 --> 00:38:30,387
Tell us the truth, be honest.

927
00:38:30,387 --> 00:38:33,223
- Tell us the truth, be honest.
- It's been good.

928
00:38:33,223 --> 00:38:35,525
Is it going the way you wanted?

929
00:38:35,525 --> 00:38:38,393
Or is there something else you want to try?

930
00:38:38,393 --> 00:38:39,796
Well...

931
00:38:39,796 --> 00:38:41,932
So...

932
00:38:41,932 --> 00:38:44,334
I want to learn the pasta and main dishes too.

933
00:38:44,334 --> 00:38:46,837
I want to learn the pasta and main dishes too.

934
00:38:46,837 --> 00:38:47,838
- Yeah.
- Yes.

935
00:38:47,838 --> 00:38:50,040
- There will be chances.
- Yes.

936
00:38:50,040 --> 00:38:51,808
Okay.

937
00:38:51,808 --> 00:38:53,243
He actually speaks up
about what he wants to do.

938
00:38:53,243 --> 00:38:55,545
[Burning with motivation]
I always speak up.

939
00:38:55,545 --> 00:38:57,180
[The Gen Z junior sure is different...]
Trying to stand out.

940
00:38:57,180 --> 00:38:58,448
- Let's work.
- Yes.

941
00:38:58,448 --> 00:38:59,895
Let's start.

942
00:38:59,895 --> 00:39:01,485
[Making a clear appeal for a promotion]

943
00:39:01,485 --> 00:39:03,987
[Day 3 lunch service begins]

944
00:39:03,987 --> 00:39:07,157
Kwon. We got orders for six bean soups,
so you need to make eight in total.

945
00:39:07,157 --> 00:39:08,792
[A rush of orders right from the start]
Total eight starters.

946
00:39:08,792 --> 00:39:10,093
Okay.

947
00:39:10,093 --> 00:39:12,996
It's starting right up again.

948
00:39:12,996 --> 00:39:14,231
[Glance]

949
00:39:14,231 --> 00:39:16,333
- Did you taste it? How is it?
- It's perfect.

950
00:39:16,333 --> 00:39:18,635
- Which table is this for?
- Table 5.

951
00:39:18,635 --> 00:39:20,070
[Glance]

952
00:39:20,070 --> 00:39:24,441
[Moving on to prepare the antipasto platter]

953
00:39:24,441 --> 00:39:27,778
[Can make the antipasto platter
with his eyes closed now]

954
00:39:27,778 --> 00:39:29,193
- These two.
- Yes.

955
00:39:29,193 --> 00:39:30,680
[Satisfied]

956
00:39:30,680 --> 00:39:32,015
He's doing great.

957
00:39:32,015 --> 00:39:34,184
- Kwon.
- Yes.

958
00:39:34,184 --> 00:39:35,360
- Is it going well?
- Yes.

959
00:39:35,360 --> 00:39:37,053
Do you need any help?

960
00:39:37,053 --> 00:39:38,221
[Completely relaxed on his own]
Alright.

961
00:39:38,221 --> 00:39:39,723
- Really?
- Yes.

962
00:39:39,723 --> 00:39:40,993
- Good.
- Okay.

963
00:39:40,993 --> 00:39:42,425
[The compliments keep rolling in]

964
00:39:42,425 --> 00:39:44,461
[He easily did his part
throughout today's lunch service]

965
00:39:44,461 --> 00:39:46,596
His skills are finally showing.

966
00:39:48,598 --> 00:39:50,133
- Kwon.
- Yes.

967
00:39:50,133 --> 00:39:52,936
- Let's clean up now.
- Okay.

968
00:39:52,936 --> 00:39:54,104
It's working.

969
00:39:54,104 --> 00:39:56,673
[While Kwon briefly steps away]
The waiters are not, though.

970
00:39:56,673 --> 00:39:58,942
[Boss and the seniors huddled up]
What?

971
00:39:58,942 --> 00:40:00,010
What's the problem?

972
00:40:00,010 --> 00:40:03,380
[After talking for a while...]

973
00:40:03,380 --> 00:40:07,250
[They scatter back to what they were doing...]

974
00:40:07,250 --> 00:40:10,120
[Meanwhile, Kwon returns to the kitchen]

975
00:40:10,120 --> 00:40:11,621
- Kwon.
- Yes.

976
00:40:11,621 --> 00:40:14,324
- Tonight for dinner service,
- Yes.

977
00:40:14,324 --> 00:40:17,861
you're next to Paolo.

978
00:40:17,861 --> 00:40:18,862
- Huh? What?
- What?

979
00:40:18,862 --> 00:40:19,930
- The main line?
- Out of nowhere?

980
00:40:19,930 --> 00:40:21,331
- What?
- Seriously?

981
00:40:21,331 --> 00:40:22,999
- Tonight for dinner service,
- Yes.

982
00:40:22,999 --> 00:40:25,068
you're next to Paolo.

983
00:40:25,068 --> 00:40:25,936
- Okay.
- Okay.

984
00:40:25,936 --> 00:40:27,070
[I got promoted!]
Yes.

985
00:40:27,070 --> 00:40:28,905
[Okay]
Good.

986
00:40:28,905 --> 00:40:30,140
[So proud]
That's huge.

987
00:40:30,140 --> 00:40:32,309
[Congrats! Kwon is promoted to the main line]
But...

988
00:40:32,309 --> 00:40:34,077
They recognized him.

989
00:40:34,077 --> 00:40:37,180
[Day 3 of service. Kwon finally levels up]

990
00:40:37,180 --> 00:40:40,417
[Main line debut coming up after a short break]
Have a good night, rest well.

991
00:40:40,417 --> 00:40:43,720
[Clocking out with a light heart]

992
00:40:43,720 --> 00:40:45,922
[Humming]
He can't hide how happy he is.

993
00:40:46,523 --> 00:40:50,360
[Rustle]

994
00:40:50,360 --> 00:40:52,028
[Something's different today, isn't it?]

995
00:40:52,028 --> 00:40:53,728
What's going on?

996
00:40:59,415 --> 00:41:00,497
[Day 1, Day 2]

997
00:41:00,497 --> 00:41:02,399
He was basically lying down
all through Day 1 and Day 2.

998
00:41:02,399 --> 00:41:04,088
[Unlike the past days
when he was flat on his back with no energy]

999
00:41:05,970 --> 00:41:07,171
[Today, he's a whole new Kwon?]
And now, on Day 3...

1000
00:41:07,171 --> 00:41:10,040
- What am I doing? What is that?
- What's he doing?

1001
00:41:10,040 --> 00:41:12,367
- He got real busy all of a sudden.
- I don't know either. What is that?

1002
00:41:12,367 --> 00:41:14,445
[Carrying something,
taking the stairs two at a time]

1003
00:41:14,445 --> 00:41:15,412
[The reason Kwon's rushing like this?]

1004
00:41:15,412 --> 00:41:17,580
What is that? What's the...

1005
00:41:19,582 --> 00:41:22,753
[Basking in the glory of Napoli Pizza]
Pizza.

1006
00:41:22,753 --> 00:41:24,255
- Pizza?
- But...

1007
00:41:24,255 --> 00:41:26,557
He's on his own celebrating.

1008
00:41:26,557 --> 00:41:28,387
So he's having a solo pizza party?

1009
00:41:28,387 --> 00:41:30,666
[Folding it up nicely, big bite]
Why am I eating pizza like that?

1010
00:41:32,018 --> 00:41:33,521
[He's loving this]
I mean, come on.

1011
00:41:33,521 --> 00:41:34,832
[Content little foot tap]

1012
00:41:34,832 --> 00:41:35,899
[Chomp]

1013
00:41:35,899 --> 00:41:37,234
- What?
- What?

1014
00:41:37,234 --> 00:41:40,170
- Man, I was really enjoying that.
- He finished all of that?

1015
00:41:40,170 --> 00:41:41,872
I left some. I've got a conscience.

1016
00:41:41,872 --> 00:41:43,741
- One slice.
- Saving it for dinner.

1017
00:41:43,741 --> 00:41:45,375
[Saving the rest of the pizza]

1018
00:41:45,976 --> 00:41:49,621
[Fixing his hair, something he never does]

1019
00:41:49,621 --> 00:41:50,948
He is so hyped right now.

1020
00:41:50,948 --> 00:41:53,631
[Time to go make some main dishes]

1021
00:41:53,631 --> 00:41:55,024
[Current Time: 6:55 PM]
- Hi. - Hi.

1022
00:41:55,024 --> 00:41:57,588
[Dopamine MAX, back at work]

1023
00:41:57,588 --> 00:41:59,423
- Kwon.
- Yes.

1024
00:41:59,423 --> 00:42:00,424
Kwon.

1025
00:42:00,424 --> 00:42:01,725
[Come here]
Sam Kwon.

1026
00:42:01,725 --> 00:42:02,893
Shall we go?

1027
00:42:02,893 --> 00:42:04,461
- Let's go get ready for service.
- He looks light on his feet.

1028
00:42:04,461 --> 00:42:05,796
Right?

1029
00:42:05,796 --> 00:42:07,164
[Crumpled]
Yes.

1030
00:42:07,164 --> 00:42:08,766
[Cozy little elevator ride]

1031
00:42:08,766 --> 00:42:10,767
Let's start.

1032
00:42:13,003 --> 00:42:14,171
[Kwon promoted today, and he's over the moon]

1033
00:42:14,171 --> 00:42:16,206
[Cute]
Look at that face.

1034
00:42:16,206 --> 00:42:17,508
I mean, seriously.

1035
00:42:17,508 --> 00:42:20,644
[Eye contact]

1036
00:42:20,644 --> 00:42:22,513
[The awkward, suffocating elevator ride
from day one]

1037
00:42:22,513 --> 00:42:24,748
Everyone's gotten used to me being around.

1038
00:42:24,748 --> 00:42:27,192
[Blank stares]

1039
00:42:28,185 --> 00:42:29,720
[Warming up with some small talk]
Is there a match on tonight?

1040
00:42:29,720 --> 00:42:31,588
- Yeah, Napoli is playing.
- Wanna watch it?

1041
00:42:31,588 --> 00:42:33,490
[Mood lifting]
I think the senior chefs really like him.

1042
00:42:33,490 --> 00:42:36,493
Well, he pulls his weight in the kitchen.

1043
00:42:36,493 --> 00:42:37,661
- I told you.
- Water, flour, and salt.

1044
00:42:37,661 --> 00:42:41,632
[Arriving on the 2nd floor in good spirits]
I told you to go there.

1045
00:42:41,632 --> 00:42:43,767
[What's Kwon's first task on the main line?]
Water, flour and salt.

1046
00:42:43,767 --> 00:42:46,491
- I haven't seen this kitchen yet.
- They moved to a different prep area.

1047
00:42:50,705 --> 00:42:53,208
[Paolo pulling something out of the fridge]

1048
00:42:54,673 --> 00:42:57,443
This is the mille-feuille dough
I prepped this morning.

1049
00:42:57,443 --> 00:42:58,611
Got it.

1050
00:42:58,611 --> 00:43:01,780
So this upstairs kitchen is
exclusively for desserts.

1051
00:43:02,748 --> 00:43:05,817
[Paolo, the No. 2 on the main line,]

1052
00:43:06,785 --> 00:43:09,855
[is also the pastry chef!]

1053
00:43:09,855 --> 00:43:11,090
That's impressive.

1054
00:43:11,090 --> 00:43:12,558
Looks delicious.

1055
00:43:12,558 --> 00:43:14,059
[Making all the desserts from scratch here]

1056
00:43:14,059 --> 00:43:15,127
This here.

1057
00:43:15,127 --> 00:43:19,464
[What dessert are they prepping today?]

1058
00:43:20,082 --> 00:43:22,401
- So they do mille-feuille here too.
- But a sweet version.

1059
00:43:22,401 --> 00:43:25,437
[A crowd favorite at the restaurant]

1060
00:43:25,437 --> 00:43:27,239
Dessert mille-feuille is notoriously
hard to pull off.

1061
00:43:27,239 --> 00:43:28,741
[Mille-feuille means "a thousand leaves,"
the secret is in the endless layers]

1062
00:43:28,741 --> 00:43:32,945
[Starting the dough prep with Paolo]
A bit of flour.

1063
00:43:32,945 --> 00:43:35,548
[Press]

1064
00:43:35,548 --> 00:43:37,950
We need to shape this into a square.

1065
00:43:37,950 --> 00:43:39,985
- A square big enough...
- Okay.

1066
00:43:39,985 --> 00:43:44,857
to wrap the butter. By hand. Got it?

1067
00:43:44,857 --> 00:43:46,692
That's puff pastry dough.

1068
00:43:46,692 --> 00:43:48,460
Usually, you run that through a machine.

1069
00:43:48,460 --> 00:43:50,129
- Right.
- But they're doing it all by hand here.

1070
00:43:50,129 --> 00:43:51,330
Stacking a thousand layers by hand?

1071
00:43:51,330 --> 00:43:53,065
- They're doing the lamination manually.
- Seriously?

1072
00:43:53,065 --> 00:43:55,834
Because you have to fold the butter in
over and over.

1073
00:43:55,834 --> 00:43:57,369
- You just repeat the process.
- By hand?

1074
00:43:57,369 --> 00:43:59,564
That takes a crazy amount of elbow grease.

1075
00:44:00,739 --> 00:44:04,476
If you're ready, let's get to it.

1076
00:44:04,476 --> 00:44:07,016
[Trying to roll it out gently...]

1077
00:44:07,016 --> 00:44:10,148
[Struggle]
That's so tough... I'm already dying.

1078
00:44:10,783 --> 00:44:12,318
[Panicking slightly]
That's enough.

1079
00:44:12,318 --> 00:44:15,754
[Paolo squares up the edges]

1080
00:44:15,754 --> 00:44:17,890
[While Kwon does the heavy rolling]

1081
00:44:17,890 --> 00:44:19,758
- Gosh.
- That is an insane workout.

1082
00:44:19,758 --> 00:44:22,127
- It's seriously exhausting.
- Right.

1083
00:44:23,796 --> 00:44:26,498
[Adding the main ingredient: butter]
That's the butter.

1084
00:44:26,498 --> 00:44:28,545
- Folding that butter in.
- Yeah.

1085
00:44:28,545 --> 00:44:31,003
[Folding it into a neat square]

1086
00:44:31,003 --> 00:44:32,571
Roll it.

1087
00:44:32,571 --> 00:44:34,773
[Now roll it, Kwon]
Okay.

1088
00:44:34,773 --> 00:44:38,010
[Now it's just rinse and repeat]

1089
00:44:38,010 --> 00:44:41,480
[Rolling the dough flat]

1090
00:44:41,480 --> 00:44:42,815
[Ugh]

1091
00:44:42,815 --> 00:44:45,283
That definitely calls for a machine,
but they're doing it by hand.

1092
00:44:46,685 --> 00:44:48,254
Everything is so organic.

1093
00:44:48,254 --> 00:44:49,622
Italy really is on another level.

1094
00:44:49,622 --> 00:44:51,557
[Classic analog Naples]

1095
00:44:51,557 --> 00:44:54,627
[Paolo stacks the folded layers]
Look what I do.

1096
00:44:54,627 --> 00:44:56,095
Ready? Okay.

1097
00:44:56,095 --> 00:44:58,063
Kwon, let's roll it again.

1098
00:44:59,131 --> 00:45:01,000
[Round two begins]

1099
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:03,836
[Biting his lip]

1100
00:45:03,836 --> 00:45:07,473
[Rolling it out until the layers are perfect]
I'm drained before service even started.

1101
00:45:07,473 --> 00:45:09,141
- Okay.
- Okay.

1102
00:45:09,141 --> 00:45:10,376
[Today's mille-feuille prep is done]

1103
00:45:10,376 --> 00:45:12,344
Okay. Perfect.

1104
00:45:12,344 --> 00:45:13,612
[Tight layers]

1105
00:45:13,612 --> 00:45:15,414
Good.

1106
00:45:15,414 --> 00:45:18,050
Chilling it.
They have to do this again tomorrow.

1107
00:45:18,050 --> 00:45:19,518
- It's a continuous cycle.
- Roll it out, add butter, repeat.

1108
00:45:19,518 --> 00:45:21,353
Tomorrow again,
because if you do it all at once...

1109
00:45:21,353 --> 00:45:24,290
- The butter will just melt.
- It melts.

1110
00:45:24,290 --> 00:45:28,163
[Moving right on to the next task]

1111
00:45:28,163 --> 00:45:31,382
[Prepping more dough?]
Try to make it clear.

1112
00:45:31,382 --> 00:45:34,433
[These little round dough balls...]

1113
00:45:34,433 --> 00:45:36,168
[Are the complimentary cheese bread rolls]

1114
00:45:36,168 --> 00:45:37,936
- Cheese bread.
- That bread was so good.

1115
00:45:37,936 --> 00:45:40,172
They make their own bread, too.

1116
00:45:40,172 --> 00:45:42,574
- Put it in the dough.
- Okay.

1117
00:45:42,574 --> 00:45:44,009
[Expert demonstration by Paolo]

1118
00:45:44,009 --> 00:45:45,477
Use your hand...

1119
00:45:45,477 --> 00:45:47,146
Just gently roll it around like that?

1120
00:45:47,146 --> 00:45:48,980
Okay.

1121
00:45:49,981 --> 00:45:55,954
I don't know how convenient that is.

1122
00:45:55,954 --> 00:45:58,023
Wait, Paolo rolled it against the table, right?

1123
00:45:58,023 --> 00:45:59,783
But Kwon's just rolling it between his hands.

1124
00:45:59,783 --> 00:46:01,060
[Kwon going rogue again]

1125
00:46:01,060 --> 00:46:02,994
I'll do it my way.

1126
00:46:07,232 --> 00:46:08,133
[How's this?]

1127
00:46:08,133 --> 00:46:09,268
[Still getting his work checked
like a good rookie]

1128
00:46:09,268 --> 00:46:11,437
Not bad.

1129
00:46:11,437 --> 00:46:14,340
Everyone has their own technique, I guess.

1130
00:46:14,340 --> 00:46:16,175
- So this is your style.
- Exactly.

1131
00:46:16,175 --> 00:46:17,976
- He just...
- This works too.

1132
00:46:17,976 --> 00:46:20,279
- It doesn't matter.
- He's got fast hands, though.

1133
00:46:20,279 --> 00:46:21,680
I've baked a lot of bread myself.

1134
00:46:21,680 --> 00:46:23,115
I usually roll two at a time.

1135
00:46:23,115 --> 00:46:25,351
- To speed things up.
- Right, two at a time.

1136
00:46:25,351 --> 00:46:28,520
[Round and puffy cheese rolls, just like Kwon]

1137
00:46:28,520 --> 00:46:30,220
What is this?

1138
00:46:31,623 --> 00:46:33,192
- The resemblance is uncanny.
- You guys are so mean.

1139
00:46:33,192 --> 00:46:34,727
- His face turned into a cheese roll.
- It suits him.

1140
00:46:34,727 --> 00:46:36,561
You guys are too much.

1141
00:46:37,899 --> 00:46:38,916
[The Kwon look-alike rolls
head straight to the oven]

1142
00:46:38,916 --> 00:46:42,033
Fire, fire! Let's cook them.

1143
00:46:43,082 --> 00:46:45,453
[Pretty]
They look a bit like brioche.

1144
00:46:46,207 --> 00:46:48,774
Oh, they came out great.

1145
00:46:48,774 --> 00:46:51,249
- They're hot right now.
- I know.

1146
00:46:53,846 --> 00:46:54,813
- Did you get a shock?
- Yes.

1147
00:46:54,813 --> 00:46:56,149
We've gotten close.

1148
00:46:56,149 --> 00:46:57,216
Yeah, you can really tell.

1149
00:46:57,216 --> 00:46:58,250
Yeah, we're super tight now.

1150
00:46:58,250 --> 00:47:01,587
[Can't resist the bread he baked,
even if it's scorching hot]

1151
00:47:01,587 --> 00:47:03,125
[Ouch, hot]

1152
00:47:03,125 --> 00:47:04,390
[Glancing over]

1153
00:47:04,390 --> 00:47:05,724
- Is it hot?
- Yes.

1154
00:47:05,724 --> 00:47:08,193
- Does it taste good?
- It's delicious.

1155
00:47:09,461 --> 00:47:11,796
[Confident]
It's good because I made it.

1156
00:47:12,564 --> 00:47:13,832
He actually said that over there?

1157
00:47:13,832 --> 00:47:16,034
[There it is, his signature smugness]
Because you did it?

1158
00:47:16,034 --> 00:47:18,027
- People love it.
- Of course they do.

1159
00:47:18,027 --> 00:47:20,038
[Kitchen flipped by the rookie's new side]

1160
00:47:20,038 --> 00:47:21,072
Of course.

1161
00:47:21,072 --> 00:47:23,983
- They've probably never heard that one before.
- He's really saying that?

1162
00:47:23,983 --> 00:47:25,277
[Smug Kwon, Naples Truther]
That's just how Naples is.

1163
00:47:25,277 --> 00:47:26,879
People are naturally cocky there.

1164
00:47:26,879 --> 00:47:29,248
[Did you actually ask Naples?]
He says that's just how Naples is.

1165
00:47:29,248 --> 00:47:30,649
Naples is a cocky city, I'm telling you.

1166
00:47:30,649 --> 00:47:32,390
- What are you talking about?
- I learned it all from there.

1167
00:47:32,390 --> 00:47:33,852
Don't talk nonsense just because we don't know.

1168
00:47:33,852 --> 00:47:36,288
I learned every bit of it over there.

1169
00:47:36,288 --> 00:47:37,589
[While the guy himself stays chill]
Bravo!

1170
00:47:37,589 --> 00:47:39,224
[Nom nom]

1171
00:47:39,224 --> 00:47:40,862
[The boss, shocked by the rookie's smugness]
Bravo!

1172
00:47:40,862 --> 00:47:43,695
- Shocked?
- She's laughing so genuinely.

1173
00:47:44,696 --> 00:47:47,599
[To. Kwon]
Let's stay humble...

1174
00:47:47,599 --> 00:47:50,905
[Nod]
Humility is priority number one.

1175
00:47:50,905 --> 00:47:53,672
[Explain yourself, Naples Truther]
Right. Stay humble, she said.

1176
00:47:53,672 --> 00:47:54,985
[No...]
Hey! Now you get it?

1177
00:47:54,985 --> 00:47:56,475
- You get what she meant?
- Humility comes first.

1178
00:47:56,475 --> 00:47:59,811
[Shakes head]
Anyone can see you're being ridiculous.

1179
00:48:02,414 --> 00:48:03,482
Paolo.

1180
00:48:03,482 --> 00:48:05,517
[Enter Giacomo, the head of the house]

1181
00:48:05,517 --> 00:48:11,657
My friend showed me
the dough sheeter you asked for.

1182
00:48:11,657 --> 00:48:12,624
[Interested]
The dough sheeter.

1183
00:48:12,624 --> 00:48:17,198
- Yeah, buy the machine already.
- To make millefoglie.

1184
00:48:17,198 --> 00:48:18,215
[A dough-rolling machine,
Paolo's wishlist item]

1185
00:48:18,215 --> 00:48:20,098
- The dough roller.
- He needs the machine.

1186
00:48:20,098 --> 00:48:22,100
- That thing's super expensive.
- It's so expensive.

1187
00:48:22,100 --> 00:48:24,102
[But...]
Expensive.

1188
00:48:24,102 --> 00:48:26,671
Five million won?

1189
00:48:28,540 --> 00:48:29,675
Five million won?

1190
00:48:29,675 --> 00:48:31,510
[About 5 million won, pricier than expected]

1191
00:48:31,510 --> 00:48:34,313
- With arms like yours, you don't need it.
- True, but...

1192
00:48:34,313 --> 00:48:38,016
Don't leave! I have a witness!

1193
00:48:38,016 --> 00:48:39,651
[A witness?]

1194
00:48:39,651 --> 00:48:43,322
[Me!]
Don't leave! I have a witness!

1195
00:48:43,322 --> 00:48:45,557
[Hand naturally goes up to his arm]
It's heavy.

1196
00:48:45,557 --> 00:48:46,959
[Puppy dog eyes activated]
He's playing it up.

1197
00:48:46,959 --> 00:48:48,126
He's begging for one.

1198
00:48:48,126 --> 00:48:50,095
- You think I should buy the dough sheeter?
- Yes.

1199
00:48:50,095 --> 00:48:52,030
Seriously?

1200
00:48:52,030 --> 00:48:53,765
[The audience is loving it]
Stuff like this is great.

1201
00:48:53,765 --> 00:48:57,202
- He's begging for one.
- Backing him up like this.

1202
00:48:57,202 --> 00:48:58,804
[A chance to win Senior Pa over]
It was so hard.

1203
00:48:58,804 --> 00:49:00,208
My arm hurts.

1204
00:49:00,208 --> 00:49:01,840
It hurts.

1205
00:49:01,840 --> 00:49:03,742
- You sure I should buy it?
- Yes.

1206
00:49:03,742 --> 00:49:05,043
[Playing it cool]

1207
00:49:05,043 --> 00:49:07,416
[Senior Pa's double thumbs up]
Is he really going to buy it?

1208
00:49:07,416 --> 00:49:09,515
[Scoring major points with Senior Pa]
That's how you win them over.

1209
00:49:09,515 --> 00:49:12,050
- Right.
- He backed him up.

1210
00:49:12,050 --> 00:49:15,320
Kwon seems brighter today.

1211
00:49:15,320 --> 00:49:19,658
He's starting to get our jokes,

1212
00:49:19,658 --> 00:49:21,609
and it feels like he's really...

1213
00:49:21,609 --> 00:49:24,988
- Becoming one of the team.
- becoming one of the team.

1214
00:49:24,988 --> 00:49:27,366
- I'm fitting in.
- Yeah, I can see it.

1215
00:49:27,366 --> 00:49:28,467
It's all jokes.

1216
00:49:28,467 --> 00:49:31,670
[The rookie's blended
right into the sister restaurant]

1217
00:49:31,670 --> 00:49:35,707
[First dinner service after his promotion
to the main station]

1218
00:49:35,707 --> 00:49:38,377
[First order of the night]

1219
00:49:38,377 --> 00:49:40,712
[Main: One sirloin steak]
- Table six. - Steak.

1220
00:49:40,712 --> 00:49:44,116
[Straight to the main course, no appetizers]
They asked for the sirloin steak.

1221
00:49:44,116 --> 00:49:45,817
- Kwon, come here.
- Yes.

1222
00:49:45,817 --> 00:49:47,686
We already have a main course order.

1223
00:49:47,686 --> 00:49:50,122
There's a sirloin steak order right now.

1224
00:49:50,122 --> 00:49:51,583
- Let's get it.
- Yes.

1225
00:49:51,583 --> 00:49:54,500
[Kwon's first main course dish?]

1226
00:49:55,241 --> 00:49:59,398
[Kwon's first main station dish: sirloin steak]
His first dish at the main station.

1227
00:49:59,398 --> 00:50:03,268
[Normally the steak comes with sauce
and tomato garnish]

1228
00:50:03,268 --> 00:50:04,803
[Main: Two sirloin steaks,
standard, cooked to preference]

1229
00:50:04,803 --> 00:50:06,505
[Main: One sirloin steak, no sauce, no garnish]

1230
00:50:06,505 --> 00:50:08,273
[Main: One sirloin steak, uncut,
no sauce or garnish]

1231
00:50:08,273 --> 00:50:10,883
[Most customizable dish in the restaurant]
Right. With steak,

1232
00:50:10,883 --> 00:50:13,845
[Must memorize special requests]
there's the doneness.

1233
00:50:13,845 --> 00:50:18,016
[Learning the technique from scratch]
Now you need it without...

1234
00:50:18,016 --> 00:50:19,451
- without sides.
- Yes.

1235
00:50:19,451 --> 00:50:20,552
[Main: One sirloin, thick,
uncut, no sauce and garnish]

1236
00:50:20,552 --> 00:50:23,255
- No sauce.
- Yes.

1237
00:50:23,255 --> 00:50:24,590
[Finally, his first main course]

1238
00:50:24,590 --> 00:50:26,458
Look at that focus.

1239
00:50:26,458 --> 00:50:28,260
- I'm going to cut it thick.
- Okay.

1240
00:50:28,260 --> 00:50:29,695
- Okay.
- Okay.

1241
00:50:29,695 --> 00:50:31,296
Go ahead and cut it.

1242
00:50:31,296 --> 00:50:33,065
[Quickly grabs the knife]

1243
00:50:33,065 --> 00:50:36,635
[Hands fumbling from the rush]

1244
00:50:36,635 --> 00:50:38,604
[No wonder, though...]

1245
00:50:38,604 --> 00:50:40,639
[It's been a while since real knife work]

1246
00:50:40,639 --> 00:50:43,875
[Even the one-hand hold technique]

1247
00:50:44,509 --> 00:50:47,045
[Perfect knife work]

1248
00:50:47,045 --> 00:50:49,214
Good, perfect.

1249
00:50:49,214 --> 00:50:51,917
- Just a little bit of olive oil.
- Okay.

1250
00:50:51,917 --> 00:50:53,285
[Olive oil]

1251
00:50:53,285 --> 00:50:55,153
[Focus]

1252
00:50:56,832 --> 00:50:58,156
[Kwon, you put it on]
Okay.

1253
00:50:58,156 --> 00:50:59,291
[Cooking it solo]

1254
00:50:59,291 --> 00:51:03,195
[Carefully onto the grill]

1255
00:51:03,195 --> 00:51:05,330
[Full focus since it's his first main]

1256
00:51:05,330 --> 00:51:07,612
You have to get the grill marks right.

1257
00:51:08,967 --> 00:51:11,235
[Cooking up nicely]
Looks delicious.

1258
00:51:13,305 --> 00:51:15,607
They don't do the butter basting
or anything like that on the steak.

1259
00:51:15,607 --> 00:51:16,975
Sauce isn't really a thing here either.

1260
00:51:16,975 --> 00:51:18,477
- Just salt.
- Just the meat.

1261
00:51:18,477 --> 00:51:19,611
- Just salt.
- And that's it.

1262
00:51:19,611 --> 00:51:21,213
[Simple grilling style]

1263
00:51:21,213 --> 00:51:23,328
[Main: One sirloin, thick, uncut,
no sauce and garnish]

1264
00:51:23,328 --> 00:51:25,050
[Kwon's steak, seasoned with just salt]

1265
00:51:25,050 --> 00:51:26,084
Where are we going?

1266
00:51:26,084 --> 00:51:26,918
- Potatoes.
- Okay!

1267
00:51:26,918 --> 00:51:29,021
[Sent out as is!]
Super simple.

1268
00:51:29,021 --> 00:51:32,791
[Kwon's sirloin steak heads to the guests]

1269
00:51:32,791 --> 00:51:33,992
[How will the guests rate it?]

1270
00:51:33,992 --> 00:51:36,627
- I'm curious.
- Looks delicious.

1271
00:51:37,596 --> 00:51:40,399
[Cutting it into tender pieces]

1272
00:51:40,399 --> 00:51:42,968
[One bite in]

1273
00:51:42,968 --> 00:51:44,636
How is it?

1274
00:51:44,636 --> 00:51:46,336
Delicious.

1275
00:51:47,572 --> 00:51:49,875
- There's a timer for it.
- Paolo.

1276
00:51:49,875 --> 00:51:50,942
- Yes.
- Excuse me.

1277
00:51:50,942 --> 00:51:53,679
Order for cod steak and scarola salad.

1278
00:51:53,679 --> 00:51:55,380
Okay.

1279
00:51:55,380 --> 00:51:58,150
[New main course order: cod steak]
- Baccalà. - Baccalà.

1280
00:51:58,150 --> 00:51:59,449
[Diving right in]
Baccalà.

1281
00:51:59,449 --> 00:52:01,720
On the cutting board.

1282
00:52:01,720 --> 00:52:04,456
Baccalà is salt-cured cod.

1283
00:52:04,456 --> 00:52:05,569
Popular in the Mediterranean,

1284
00:52:05,569 --> 00:52:07,693
[Cutting the cod into grill-friendly pieces]
Spain, Italy.

1285
00:52:07,693 --> 00:52:08,860
[Olive oil, drizzle]

1286
00:52:08,860 --> 00:52:11,863
That's enough.

1287
00:52:11,863 --> 00:52:13,865
- Let's do it.
- Okay.

1288
00:52:13,865 --> 00:52:16,134
[Unlike the sirloin, this one's pan-seared]
As a steak.

1289
00:52:16,134 --> 00:52:17,834
[Easy does it]
Gently.

1290
00:52:19,771 --> 00:52:21,573
Careful.

1291
00:52:21,573 --> 00:52:25,777
[Starts searing with a practiced hand]

1292
00:52:25,777 --> 00:52:30,315
[Standing it up to cook evenly all around]

1293
00:52:30,315 --> 00:52:32,150
You gave it to Monica.

1294
00:52:32,150 --> 00:52:34,819
[Once cooked, moves the cod to a tray]

1295
00:52:36,883 --> 00:52:37,889
Okay.

1296
00:52:37,889 --> 00:52:40,549
[Kwon handles it all the way through]

1297
00:52:40,549 --> 00:52:42,293
Okay.

1298
00:52:44,629 --> 00:52:46,631
- Now?
- Table 3.

1299
00:52:46,631 --> 00:52:48,433
He's really got the hang of this.

1300
00:52:48,433 --> 00:52:52,904
[Kwon's second main course heads out]

1301
00:52:52,904 --> 00:52:56,708
[All dishes out,
brief peace at the main station]

1302
00:52:56,708 --> 00:53:00,145
[Even Kwon catches his breath]

1303
00:53:00,145 --> 00:53:03,026
Usually at the main station,

1304
00:53:03,026 --> 00:53:05,050
- we start prepping later.
- Yes.

1305
00:53:05,050 --> 00:53:07,282
So you can prep

1306
00:53:07,282 --> 00:53:10,422
[Senior Pa kindly explains things to Kwon]
ingredients ahead,

1307
00:53:10,422 --> 00:53:13,792
- or if the pasta station looks busy,
- Yeah.

1308
00:53:13,792 --> 00:53:16,127
you can go help out.

1309
00:53:16,962 --> 00:53:18,396
No one ever helps me.

1310
00:53:18,396 --> 00:53:20,096
Yes?

1311
00:53:21,066 --> 00:53:22,637
No one ever helps me.

1312
00:53:22,637 --> 00:53:24,236
- Yes?
- No one ever helps me.

1313
00:53:24,236 --> 00:53:25,470
He's strong.

1314
00:53:25,470 --> 00:53:27,873
[Senior An's love call to Kwon]

1315
00:53:27,873 --> 00:53:29,583
[Wink]

1316
00:53:31,343 --> 00:53:32,749
[Tonight's dinner service feels extra warm]

1317
00:53:32,749 --> 00:53:34,879
Feels peaceful.

1318
00:53:36,065 --> 00:53:39,417
[The dining room's calm too, until...]

1319
00:53:39,417 --> 00:53:43,187
[The guest who got Kwon's cod steak]

1320
00:53:43,891 --> 00:53:45,190
- What?
- What?

1321
00:53:45,190 --> 00:53:46,291
What? That look?

1322
00:53:46,291 --> 00:53:47,759
[Guest making a sour face?]
That look...

1323
00:53:47,759 --> 00:53:50,829
I can't finish this cod steak.

1324
00:53:50,829 --> 00:53:52,731
It's too salty.

1325
00:53:52,731 --> 00:53:54,866
Too salty?

1326
00:53:54,866 --> 00:53:56,700
[First complaint of the night]
- Hold on. - No way.

1327
00:53:57,469 --> 00:53:58,570
[And then...]

1328
00:53:58,570 --> 00:54:01,539
The cod steak is a bit salty.

1329
00:54:01,539 --> 00:54:03,541
- A bit salty?
- More than a bit.

1330
00:54:03,541 --> 00:54:06,044
I'm going to leave the cod steak.

1331
00:54:06,044 --> 00:54:08,046
- What are they going to do now?
- I'll go check with the kitchen.

1332
00:54:08,046 --> 00:54:11,282
[Uh-oh]

1333
00:54:11,282 --> 00:54:12,582
Okay.

1334
00:54:12,582 --> 00:54:15,520
[Server heads to the kitchen for the main]
The one you did today.

1335
00:54:15,520 --> 00:54:17,355
- Emergency.
- No.

1336
00:54:17,355 --> 00:54:19,157
- This is a full-blown emergency.
- Total emergency.

1337
00:54:19,157 --> 00:54:22,520
[The mood shifts in an instant]

1338
00:54:23,761 --> 00:54:25,683
The cod steak is too salty?

1339
00:54:28,199 --> 00:54:30,135
The cod steak is too salty?

1340
00:54:30,135 --> 00:54:33,104
And it had to be the day Sung Jun started.

1341
00:54:33,104 --> 00:54:35,874
[Complaint the second he got promoted?]
Right, the second I moved up.

1342
00:54:35,874 --> 00:54:38,276
- Sung Jun is such bad luck.
- Right.

1343
00:54:38,276 --> 00:54:39,477
Sorry about that.

1344
00:54:39,477 --> 00:54:41,012
- I mean, that kind of bad luck.
- Bad luck.

1345
00:54:41,012 --> 00:54:42,046
Unlucky.

1346
00:54:42,046 --> 00:54:44,415
- Unlucky.
- Unfortunate.

1347
00:54:44,415 --> 00:54:47,118
[Working hard to smooth it over]

1348
00:54:47,118 --> 00:54:49,254
The first main course dish
and you already have a mistake.

1349
00:54:49,254 --> 00:54:51,389
Amazing.

1350
00:54:51,389 --> 00:54:53,158
You're learning from the best.

1351
00:54:53,158 --> 00:54:55,360
- Senior An is loving this.
- He's thrilled.

1352
00:54:55,360 --> 00:54:57,495
Back at the appetizer station,
how many mistakes did you make?

1353
00:54:57,495 --> 00:54:59,663
Zero! Because I'm just that good.

1354
00:55:01,499 --> 00:55:03,434
He's loving it.

1355
00:55:03,434 --> 00:55:04,669
People from Naples,

1356
00:55:04,669 --> 00:55:06,437
- they've got the same vibe.
- Cockiness is

1357
00:55:06,437 --> 00:55:08,173
- the default setting.
- Yeah, they've got a bit of that.

1358
00:55:08,173 --> 00:55:10,275
A complaint just came in, why is he so happy?

1359
00:55:10,275 --> 00:55:12,110
- He's rubbing it in.
- This should be serious.

1360
00:55:12,110 --> 00:55:14,678
- The whole team's doing it.
- Right.

1361
00:55:17,081 --> 00:55:19,117
Paolo.

1362
00:55:19,117 --> 00:55:22,787
Let me try the cod steak that went out too.

1363
00:55:22,787 --> 00:55:25,089
- Curious what the boss will say.
- Right.

1364
00:55:25,089 --> 00:55:27,158
[The vibe read]

1365
00:55:27,158 --> 00:55:30,128
[Smile completely gone]
Did you catch that face? That fast?

1366
00:55:30,128 --> 00:55:33,264
[Slicing the cod that went to the guest]
Meat isn't so...

1367
00:55:33,264 --> 00:55:36,534
[The boss tries the salt-cured cod]

1368
00:55:36,534 --> 00:55:38,816
- This is a full-blown emergency.
- Right.

1369
00:55:38,816 --> 00:55:40,805
What do you do? I mean, it's already cured...

1370
00:55:40,805 --> 00:55:43,141
- Right.
- It came in already salted.

1371
00:55:43,141 --> 00:55:45,876
This is way too salty. Can't send this out.

1372
00:55:46,578 --> 00:55:48,880
Laura, the salt-cured cod is a bit salty.

1373
00:55:48,880 --> 00:55:51,419
Can't send it out like this.

1374
00:55:51,419 --> 00:55:52,988
It's too salty.

1375
00:55:52,988 --> 00:55:55,320
[Kitchen mood gets even more serious]

1376
00:55:55,320 --> 00:55:57,822
I don't know when it came in.

1377
00:55:57,822 --> 00:55:59,290
- Isn't it always this salty?
- Right.

1378
00:55:59,290 --> 00:56:01,693
- If it came in pre-cured.
- The curing was off.

1379
00:56:01,693 --> 00:56:04,395
- We get it from the fish supplier.
- Right.

1380
00:56:04,395 --> 00:56:05,930
- They cured it too heavily.
- Right.

1381
00:56:05,930 --> 00:56:07,232
But either way, what matters is

1382
00:56:07,232 --> 00:56:09,300
- that the guests don't need to know all that.
- No, they don't need to.

1383
00:56:09,300 --> 00:56:10,602
- The guests don't care.
- Right.

1384
00:56:10,602 --> 00:56:12,036
- "It tastes salty to me."
- The point is,

1385
00:56:12,036 --> 00:56:14,048
- you have to sear it before it goes out.
- Test it.

1386
00:56:14,048 --> 00:56:16,474
- You should've tested it.
- Should've tried it.

1387
00:56:17,645 --> 00:56:21,713
The product itself came in way saltier
than usual.

1388
00:56:21,713 --> 00:56:25,049
[Q. Why did the cod steak complaint happen?]
[Serious]

1389
00:56:25,049 --> 00:56:29,754
The salt level of the cured cod
isn't always consistent.

1390
00:56:29,754 --> 00:56:32,957
So I always taste it first.

1391
00:56:32,957 --> 00:56:35,293
- You have to taste it every time.
- Always tasting it.

1392
00:56:35,293 --> 00:56:39,197
- But a mistake still slipped through?
- I check how salty the cod is.

1393
00:56:39,197 --> 00:56:41,566
But that day, I didn't get to taste it!

1394
00:56:41,566 --> 00:56:43,968
And we were out

1395
00:56:43,968 --> 00:56:45,870
- He didn't taste it?
- of any other cod too.

1396
00:56:45,870 --> 00:56:48,840
Jenna, can I get some salt-cured cod?

1397
00:56:48,840 --> 00:56:50,308
[This is bad...]

1398
00:56:50,308 --> 00:56:54,012
[Scrambling to track down new salt-cured cod]
That's working hour, that's why I called.

1399
00:56:54,012 --> 00:56:56,213
Are you at the restaurant?

1400
00:56:56,814 --> 00:56:59,083
[Laura rushes out to save the situation]

1401
00:56:59,083 --> 00:57:01,219
- Really? Right now?
- Because there's none left.

1402
00:57:01,219 --> 00:57:03,354
And we've got to serve dinner.

1403
00:57:04,022 --> 00:57:05,089
[Deflated...]

1404
00:57:05,089 --> 00:57:07,358
Deflated.

1405
00:57:07,358 --> 00:57:10,361
Because in a situation like that,
things could go south.

1406
00:57:10,361 --> 00:57:11,696
- Right.
- Right.

1407
00:57:11,696 --> 00:57:13,631
[Discouraged]

1408
00:57:13,631 --> 00:57:16,601
[While the kitchen scrambles,
Giacomo goes to the guests]

1409
00:57:16,601 --> 00:57:19,370
I'm sorry, was the cod steak a bit salty?

1410
00:57:19,370 --> 00:57:21,664
It's fine, don't worry about it.

1411
00:57:21,664 --> 00:57:25,977
- You should have told me.
- No worries.

1412
00:57:25,977 --> 00:57:27,745
- Can I bring you extra dessert?
- No, no.

1413
00:57:27,745 --> 00:57:29,447
- This is enough, don't worry.
- A zeppole?

1414
00:57:29,447 --> 00:57:31,649
- You sure?
- Don't you worry.

1415
00:57:31,649 --> 00:57:32,650
Thank you.

1416
00:57:32,650 --> 00:57:35,286
[Guests kindly understand, situation defused]

1417
00:57:35,286 --> 00:57:36,821
- Is she back?
- Paolo.

1418
00:57:36,821 --> 00:57:39,390
[Laura's back]
[With fresh salt-cured cod]

1419
00:57:39,390 --> 00:57:42,626
- Shouldn't they taste those ones too?
- Right, we have to taste it.

1420
00:57:43,294 --> 00:57:45,262
Everyone, let's try it.

1421
00:57:46,197 --> 00:57:48,932
[Three of them checking the new cured cod]

1422
00:57:49,867 --> 00:57:54,439
[Tasting it more seriously than ever]

1423
00:57:54,439 --> 00:57:56,273
[What if this one's salty too?]
Salty again?

1424
00:57:57,449 --> 00:57:59,677
[Worried]

1425
00:57:59,677 --> 00:58:01,145
Not bad!

1426
00:58:01,145 --> 00:58:02,380
Not bad.

1427
00:58:02,380 --> 00:58:04,248
[Looks like the salt level's fine this time]
Turn it around.

1428
00:58:04,248 --> 00:58:06,584
[Huge relief]
It looks different.

1429
00:58:06,584 --> 00:58:09,220
[Peek]

1430
00:58:09,220 --> 00:58:10,555
[Behind the seniors dealing with the cod]

1431
00:58:10,555 --> 00:58:12,490
Everyone's so tied up with that...

1432
00:58:12,490 --> 00:58:14,826
The pots are all still boiling.

1433
00:58:14,826 --> 00:58:15,860
The risotto and everything.

1434
00:58:15,860 --> 00:58:18,162
Oh no.

1435
00:58:18,162 --> 00:58:21,632
[Kwon can't stop noticing that pot]

1436
00:58:21,632 --> 00:58:22,633
[Focuses back on the cod]

1437
00:58:22,633 --> 00:58:24,582
It's not bad, though.

1438
00:58:24,582 --> 00:58:25,436
[Then heads to the stove?]

1439
00:58:25,436 --> 00:58:27,205
- The boss saw him!
- Guess I'm stepping up.

1440
00:58:27,205 --> 00:58:30,808
[Kwon boldly starts stirring the risotto]
He's about to save the day.

1441
00:58:30,808 --> 00:58:33,911
Well... I've done main courses before.

1442
00:58:33,911 --> 00:58:35,913
But anyway.

1443
00:58:35,913 --> 00:58:37,515
[Oops]

1444
00:58:37,515 --> 00:58:39,183
[There it is, my laugh trigger]
No way.

1445
00:58:39,183 --> 00:58:41,152
Man, this is such a cool shot.

1446
00:58:41,152 --> 00:58:44,616
[Interview cam, always the biggest hurdle]
And then suddenly, in the interview...

1447
00:58:44,616 --> 00:58:45,490
[Rustic charm]
Sung Jun...

1448
00:58:45,490 --> 00:58:47,258
- Why do I look like that?
- It totally distracted me.

1449
00:58:47,258 --> 00:58:48,501
It broke my focus.

1450
00:58:48,501 --> 00:58:49,994
Sung Jun... your neck disappeared.

1451
00:58:49,994 --> 00:58:51,262
- Seriously, what happened?
- His neck's just gone.

1452
00:58:51,262 --> 00:58:52,663
Sorry, can we just get the audio only?

1453
00:58:52,663 --> 00:58:55,066
Are you sure that's you on screen?

1454
00:58:55,066 --> 00:58:57,001
But anyway.

1455
00:58:57,001 --> 00:58:59,404
When you think of Italy,
the most important thing is

1456
00:58:59,404 --> 00:59:01,339
pasta and risotto.

1457
00:59:01,339 --> 00:59:02,707
Right, I've got to nail the pasta.

1458
00:59:02,707 --> 00:59:05,109
Honestly, that side is
where I'd want to prove myself.

1459
00:59:05,109 --> 00:59:06,319
[Yeah, you'd want a shot at it]

1460
00:59:07,716 --> 00:59:10,148
[Day 3 promise. 1 hour 40 min left]
1 hour, 40 minutes.

1461
00:59:10,148 --> 00:59:13,151
The main section was slammed
and everyone was in chaos.

1462
00:59:13,151 --> 00:59:14,519
So that opens up a window.

1463
00:59:14,519 --> 00:59:16,054
The risotto would burn if nobody touched it.

1464
00:59:16,054 --> 00:59:18,056
[The risotto pot boiling away all alone]
Right.

1465
00:59:18,056 --> 00:59:19,956
With a chance like that opening up...

1466
00:59:19,956 --> 00:59:21,959
He could feel it too, this is his shot!

1467
00:59:21,959 --> 00:59:24,128
[Leaving the busy seniors behind]
Exactly.

1468
00:59:24,128 --> 00:59:27,298
[Charging to the burners]

1469
00:59:27,298 --> 00:59:28,566
Now's the time to go for it.

1470
00:59:28,566 --> 00:59:31,436
[And just like that,
Kwon slips up to the stove]

1471
00:59:31,436 --> 00:59:34,739
[Boss Luisa was watching Kwon]

1472
00:59:34,739 --> 00:59:38,576
[Is she just letting it happen?]

1473
00:59:38,576 --> 00:59:41,279
[Glance]
I had no idea she was watching me like that.

1474
00:59:41,279 --> 00:59:42,713
I really didn't know.

1475
00:59:42,713 --> 00:59:44,482
- Weren't you trying to get her attention?
- No, I wasn't.

1476
00:59:44,482 --> 00:59:47,452
[Boss Laura just helps out, no words...]
I had no idea she was watching me like that.

1477
00:59:47,452 --> 00:59:51,855
[An unexpected shot
at the burner falls into his lap]

1478
00:59:52,723 --> 00:59:55,693
Pasta and risotto, honestly,
they're a huge deal to Italians.

1479
00:59:55,693 --> 00:59:58,463
- That's right.
- So they don't hand it over easily.

1480
00:59:58,463 --> 00:59:59,997
[First, stirring the Salsiccia and rice]

1481
00:59:59,997 --> 01:00:01,466
This is a golden opportunity.

1482
01:00:01,466 --> 01:00:03,901
If he makes a good impression here...

1483
01:00:03,901 --> 01:00:06,920
- Keep stirring so the moisture evaporates.
- Yes.

1484
01:00:07,672 --> 01:00:10,694
[Stirring patiently]

1485
01:00:12,383 --> 01:00:14,795
[The vegetable stock was shallow at first]

1486
01:00:14,795 --> 01:00:18,525
[Stir it until it simmers down like porridge]

1487
01:00:18,525 --> 01:00:21,545
[Keep going]
Keep going, keep going.

1488
01:00:21,545 --> 01:00:23,465
But I'd also just made risotto for lunch.

1489
01:00:23,465 --> 01:00:24,585
Since he'd already made it at lunch.

1490
01:00:24,585 --> 01:00:26,105
If I hadn't done that.

1491
01:00:26,105 --> 01:00:27,805
- Right.
- They might not have trusted me with it.

1492
01:00:27,805 --> 01:00:29,055
- Right.
- Wow...

1493
01:00:29,055 --> 01:00:30,185
[What a build-up]
It all connects, doesn't it?

1494
01:00:30,185 --> 01:00:31,335
- Exactly.
- It's amazing.

1495
01:00:31,335 --> 01:00:34,514
Seeing this, it feels like good luck too.

1496
01:00:34,514 --> 01:00:36,425
Because I made an impression.

1497
01:00:36,425 --> 01:00:38,895
It all lines up perfectly.

1498
01:00:38,895 --> 01:00:41,295
I'm about to add the sauce.

1499
01:00:41,295 --> 01:00:43,055
- Friarielli sauce.
- These would be...

1500
01:00:43,055 --> 01:00:45,835
Friarielli.

1501
01:00:45,835 --> 01:00:47,625
[Friarielli, the Naples specialty he
prepped with the owner on day one]

1502
01:00:47,625 --> 01:00:49,575
It's kind of like turnip greens?

1503
01:00:49,575 --> 01:00:52,935
[Made with fresh friarielli sauce]
Yeah, it does taste like turnip greens.

1504
01:00:53,770 --> 01:00:56,104
Oh, that looks delicious.

1505
01:00:58,135 --> 01:01:01,158
[Loaded with friarielli sauce]

1506
01:01:01,158 --> 01:01:02,895
You need to make the color
really vivid, like this.

1507
01:01:02,895 --> 01:01:04,185
[Such a pretty color]

1508
01:01:04,185 --> 01:01:05,535
It's pretty.

1509
01:01:05,535 --> 01:01:07,385
Yeah, it really is such a vivid color.

1510
01:01:07,385 --> 01:01:09,015
And with a sauce this fine,
you have to be careful

1511
01:01:09,015 --> 01:01:12,505
because it sticks to the pot easily.

1512
01:01:12,505 --> 01:01:13,885
[Got it]
Okay.

1513
01:01:13,885 --> 01:01:16,585
[An old aluminum pot]
It's because this aluminum pot is a bit old.

1514
01:01:16,585 --> 01:01:18,715
- Right.
- The bottom's dented like this.

1515
01:01:18,715 --> 01:01:20,985
- Right.
- Stuff gets stuck in the gaps.

1516
01:01:20,985 --> 01:01:23,325
[Showing off some skill,
lifting the pot slightly while stirring]

1517
01:01:23,325 --> 01:01:25,055
[Huh?]

1518
01:01:25,055 --> 01:01:26,155
[Right...]

1519
01:01:26,155 --> 01:01:27,375
So you have to control the heat well.

1520
01:01:27,375 --> 01:01:28,935
[Beep beep]

1521
01:01:28,935 --> 01:01:31,435
[Suddenly a timer goes off]

1522
01:01:31,435 --> 01:01:33,595
[OFF]
That's the risotto timer.

1523
01:01:33,595 --> 01:01:36,825
- What?
- The risotto timer.

1524
01:01:36,825 --> 01:01:41,895
- Okay, shall we taste it now?
- Okay.

1525
01:01:41,895 --> 01:01:43,735
Thank you.

1526
01:01:43,735 --> 01:01:45,535
Okay.

1527
01:01:45,535 --> 01:01:47,885
The most important thing with risotto and pasta

1528
01:01:47,885 --> 01:01:49,375
is how well it's cooked.

1529
01:01:49,375 --> 01:01:51,255
So essentially this means

1530
01:01:51,255 --> 01:01:54,615
what Kwon Sung Jun made is
actually going out to a customer.

1531
01:01:54,615 --> 01:01:55,785
- Coincidentally, right now.
- Yeah, exactly.

1532
01:01:55,785 --> 01:01:56,855
[Getting promoted to the
burner station just like this?]

1533
01:01:56,855 --> 01:01:58,735
[Tense]

1534
01:01:58,735 --> 01:02:00,982
[Owner Luisa takes a taste first]

1535
01:02:04,095 --> 01:02:05,545
It's not cooked yet.

1536
01:02:05,545 --> 01:02:09,195
[The risotto is undercooked]

1537
01:02:09,195 --> 01:02:12,055
- Should I add more broth then?
- Yes!

1538
01:02:13,565 --> 01:02:18,463
[Without panicking,
he decides to pour in broth and cook it more]

1539
01:02:18,463 --> 01:02:20,095
[But]

1540
01:02:20,095 --> 01:02:23,255
[He's not flustered at all for a junior]

1541
01:02:23,255 --> 01:02:25,165
[Handling it this smoothly
right from the start?]

1542
01:02:25,165 --> 01:02:27,305
He's so good it's suspicious.

1543
01:02:27,305 --> 01:02:28,665
[What if he gets caught...]

1544
01:02:28,665 --> 01:02:31,965
[A seed of suspicion sprouting?]

1545
01:02:31,965 --> 01:02:33,385
You really love making risotto, don't you!

1546
01:02:33,385 --> 01:02:34,535
Yes, yes, yes!

1547
01:02:34,535 --> 01:02:37,095
[0% suspicion]
I knew it.

1548
01:02:37,095 --> 01:02:39,095
[Wait, this actually works?]

1549
01:02:39,095 --> 01:02:41,575
- So he's just a guy who really loves risotto?
- Someone who loves it.

1550
01:02:41,575 --> 01:02:44,615
A young man with an unusual love for risotto.

1551
01:02:45,335 --> 01:02:47,925
[How good is he, exactly?]

1552
01:02:49,695 --> 01:02:50,895
[Double-checking how well it's cooked]
Thank you.

1553
01:02:50,895 --> 01:02:52,505
[Calm as if he'd always worked here]
Okay.

1554
01:02:52,505 --> 01:02:55,865
[This whole situation is hilarious lol]

1555
01:02:57,975 --> 01:03:00,955
[Why's he so good?]
It's a little suspicious, isn't it?

1556
01:03:01,945 --> 01:03:04,155
[Kwon does his own quality check too]

1557
01:03:04,155 --> 01:03:08,675
[Satisfied with how well it's cooked]

1558
01:03:09,415 --> 01:03:11,175
- Ready, right?
- Yes.

1559
01:03:11,175 --> 01:03:16,155
Just add a bit of butter and cheese
and it's done.

1560
01:03:16,155 --> 01:03:18,655
Mix it well with the spatula
so it all blends together!

1561
01:03:18,655 --> 01:03:20,995
[Time for his specialty]

1562
01:03:22,535 --> 01:03:23,975
[A true mantecare genius after all!]

1563
01:03:23,975 --> 01:03:25,695
[Dazzling skill]

1564
01:03:25,695 --> 01:03:27,085
This is actually a real skill, this.

1565
01:03:27,085 --> 01:03:28,775
[What is going on...]

1566
01:03:28,775 --> 01:03:30,345
[That level of skill...]

1567
01:03:30,345 --> 01:03:32,184
He's way, way too skilled.

1568
01:03:32,184 --> 01:03:35,482
To say this is just something
he did as a hobby...

1569
01:03:36,905 --> 01:03:39,335
[The friarielli risotto,
finished in no time with practiced hands]

1570
01:03:39,335 --> 01:03:41,215
Bravo.

1571
01:03:41,215 --> 01:03:42,495
[Plating time]

1572
01:03:42,495 --> 01:03:43,945
Even the plating.

1573
01:03:43,945 --> 01:03:45,655
[When Kwon plates it]

1574
01:03:45,655 --> 01:03:48,375
[Owner Luisa spreads it out wide]

1575
01:03:48,375 --> 01:03:51,705
[Now all that's left is the
sauce and toppings on top]

1576
01:03:51,705 --> 01:03:52,955
- Is this oil?
- It's cheese sauce!

1577
01:03:52,955 --> 01:03:54,875
This is for the cheese.

1578
01:03:54,875 --> 01:03:57,125
[Please drizzle it in a pretty swirl]
Make a nice swirl.

1579
01:03:58,105 --> 01:04:00,285
In a swirl shape.

1580
01:04:00,285 --> 01:04:03,195
[Drizzled the cheese sauce in a pretty swirl]
In a swirl shape.

1581
01:04:03,195 --> 01:04:05,565
[Thin sausage slices laid on top like flowers]
This is actually, in a way,

1582
01:04:05,565 --> 01:04:06,715
- kind of a modern style dish.
- Right.

1583
01:04:06,715 --> 01:04:09,725
[It looks pretty complicated]

1584
01:04:09,725 --> 01:04:11,785
- Right, Kwon's good at this too.
- Where'd he even get that from?

1585
01:04:11,785 --> 01:04:13,675
[Flowers]
Flowers again, and they suit it too.

1586
01:04:13,675 --> 01:04:15,455
- He likes flowers.
- He does, likes putting them on.

1587
01:04:15,455 --> 01:04:17,755
[Let me show off a little something]
That's for the cheese.

1588
01:04:18,985 --> 01:04:22,265
[Curious]

1589
01:04:23,225 --> 01:04:25,005
- No.
- Like this?

1590
01:04:25,005 --> 01:04:26,975
Huh?

1591
01:04:26,975 --> 01:04:29,325
- This just... The consistency was way off.
- It was too thin.

1592
01:04:29,325 --> 01:04:30,425
- Yeah, that was really thin.
- Way too thin.

1593
01:04:30,425 --> 01:04:32,185
Looks like it drew a butterfly shape,
was that on purpose?

1594
01:04:32,185 --> 01:04:33,915
No, that sauce was just too thin.

1595
01:04:33,915 --> 01:04:37,225
It's either too thin,
or the temperature's too high.

1596
01:04:37,225 --> 01:04:38,535
- Like this?
- Wait, stop...

1597
01:04:38,535 --> 01:04:40,605
- Stop, stop!
- Okay.

1598
01:04:40,605 --> 01:04:42,765
[What's "okay" about this?]
Oh no, oh no.

1599
01:04:42,765 --> 01:04:44,175
What do we do about that?

1600
01:04:44,175 --> 01:04:45,755
[The second one will be better, right?]

1601
01:04:45,755 --> 01:04:47,735
[Beep]

1602
01:04:49,085 --> 01:04:51,165
[Startled]
[What on earth is that?]

1603
01:04:51,165 --> 01:04:53,675
If it's too hot, it comes out like that.

1604
01:04:53,675 --> 01:04:54,935
It was too hot.

1605
01:04:54,935 --> 01:04:56,095
[Title of the piece: Freedom]

1606
01:04:56,095 --> 01:04:58,215
Freedom.

1607
01:04:58,215 --> 01:05:00,045
- Freedom, nice.
- Okay.

1608
01:05:00,045 --> 01:05:01,995
Let's go. Use this.

1609
01:05:01,995 --> 01:05:04,155
[Let's cover it up with sausage topping!]

1610
01:05:04,155 --> 01:05:05,839
"Let's cover it," really.

1611
01:05:05,839 --> 01:05:08,025
[Doing his best to salvage it]

1612
01:05:09,305 --> 01:05:11,975
[Topped with sausage and fried friarielli]
Top it with fried friarielli.

1613
01:05:11,975 --> 01:05:13,295
But since the owner

1614
01:05:13,295 --> 01:05:16,445
[Successfully dressed up the risotto]
didn't say anything special about it.

1615
01:05:16,445 --> 01:05:18,936
- She's chill about it.
- It looks pretty.

1616
01:05:19,645 --> 01:05:20,985
Self-assessment.

1617
01:05:20,985 --> 01:05:25,065
[Kwon's first risotto finally gets served]
Table 5, two risottos. We started with table 7.

1618
01:05:25,065 --> 01:05:27,415
[Will it...]

1619
01:05:27,415 --> 01:05:28,555
Will it, though?

1620
01:05:28,555 --> 01:05:30,075
[Curious about the reaction]
[How will they rate Kwon's first risotto?]

1621
01:05:30,075 --> 01:05:33,335
[Overwhelmed with emotion]
Wow, my risotto is actually going out.

1622
01:05:35,415 --> 01:05:37,275
[Hmm...]

1623
01:05:37,275 --> 01:05:39,575
Their expression...

1624
01:05:40,815 --> 01:05:42,575
[Is something wrong with the risotto?]
Why?

1625
01:05:42,575 --> 01:05:43,625
- Huh, why?
- Why?

1626
01:05:43,625 --> 01:05:45,375
Why, why?

1627
01:05:45,375 --> 01:05:47,535
A smile's supposed to
come out right away, isn't it?

1628
01:05:47,535 --> 01:05:51,583
[First risotto] [He's never seen a reaction]
Emergency.

1629
01:05:51,583 --> 01:05:53,645
[Carefully taking another bite]

1630
01:05:53,645 --> 01:05:54,935
How does it taste?

1631
01:05:54,935 --> 01:05:56,855
It's fantastic.

1632
01:05:56,855 --> 01:05:58,215
She said it's delicious.

1633
01:05:58,215 --> 01:05:59,435
She said it's delicious.

1634
01:05:59,435 --> 01:06:04,135
This seems like a pretty fancy restaurant!

1635
01:06:04,135 --> 01:06:07,115
[Tastes classy]

1636
01:06:07,115 --> 01:06:08,215
[That good?]
Really?

1637
01:06:08,215 --> 01:06:11,145
[A cocky little foot tap]
Well, who made it, though...

1638
01:06:11,145 --> 01:06:13,545
- He was anxious just a moment ago.
- Exactly.

1639
01:06:13,545 --> 01:06:15,035
- Because their expression looked a bit off.
- Really.

1640
01:06:15,035 --> 01:06:16,525
Really, how should I put it, the way I see it.

1641
01:06:16,525 --> 01:06:18,665
You're kind of like that pot over there.

1642
01:06:18,665 --> 01:06:21,225
- That's just like an aluminum pot.
- Aluminum pot.

1643
01:06:21,225 --> 01:06:23,035
Didn't you say you were changing your image?

1644
01:06:23,035 --> 01:06:26,285
[Gotta hold back the cockiness]
Oh right, I should be careful from now on.

1645
01:06:26,285 --> 01:06:31,015
[While the customers at table 7
enjoy Kwon's first risotto]

1646
01:06:31,015 --> 01:06:35,355
[Meanwhile, the other customers are
also nearly done with their appetizers]

1647
01:06:35,355 --> 01:06:39,135
- Table 1's appetizers are all out too.
- Oh, then it's about to get busy again.

1648
01:06:39,135 --> 01:06:40,525
Oh, now.

1649
01:06:40,525 --> 01:06:42,335
What needs to go out from
the pasta station, Antonio?

1650
01:06:42,335 --> 01:06:45,325
[Order slip: 3 lard pasta,
2 friarielli risotto]

1651
01:06:45,325 --> 01:06:47,375
[1 cod pasta, 1 veal cheek, 2 fried pork rib]
Wow, that's a lot.

1652
01:06:47,375 --> 01:06:49,015
Wow, way too much.

1653
01:06:49,015 --> 01:06:50,735
[An overwhelming number of orders]
Wow, how many is this?

1654
01:06:50,735 --> 01:06:52,055
[2 genovese pasta,
2 friarielli risotto, 1 cod steak]

1655
01:06:52,055 --> 01:06:53,965
[Conclusion: extremely busy]

1656
01:06:53,965 --> 01:06:57,375
[So much pasta]
Two genovese pastas are cooking.

1657
01:06:57,375 --> 01:06:58,505
[Starts boiling]

1658
01:06:58,505 --> 01:07:00,765
[Let's move fast]
Fast!

1659
01:07:00,765 --> 01:07:03,275
[With pasta orders piling up, Owner Laura,
who'd been prepping cod, comes back too]

1660
01:07:03,275 --> 01:07:07,325
Should I keep prepping cod,
or come help over here?

1661
01:07:07,325 --> 01:07:08,575
No, we're fine!

1662
01:07:08,575 --> 01:07:10,825
There's three of us, so don't worry.

1663
01:07:11,575 --> 01:07:14,075
[The chefs pick up the pace]
The three of us.

1664
01:07:14,075 --> 01:07:15,655
[Emphasis]
Three, including me!

1665
01:07:15,655 --> 01:07:18,015
[Quietly claiming a spot among them]

1666
01:07:18,015 --> 01:07:19,465
- Sneakily.
- Sneakily.

1667
01:07:19,465 --> 01:07:21,145
[Voluntarily cooking extra risotto]
Naturally.

1668
01:07:21,145 --> 01:07:24,757
- If a risotto order comes in, it's mine now.
- He's basically the risotto station now.

1669
01:07:24,757 --> 01:07:26,345
Want to go over there?

1670
01:07:26,345 --> 01:07:27,465
Or do you want to stay here?

1671
01:07:27,465 --> 01:07:29,145
[Doesn't quite catch it]
I'll keep doing risotto.

1672
01:07:29,145 --> 01:07:31,195
Or do you want to go over to Antonio's side?

1673
01:07:31,195 --> 01:07:33,482
I want to do this!

1674
01:07:33,482 --> 01:07:36,122
[Ta-da, my little bro]

1675
01:07:36,122 --> 01:07:38,012
Why would I go there?

1676
01:07:38,012 --> 01:07:40,412
[After coming this far]
Why would I go there? I've gotta do risotto.

1677
01:07:40,412 --> 01:07:43,642
[Declaring himself an old tree]
I need to put down roots here.

1678
01:07:43,642 --> 01:07:45,882
I want to do risotto!

1679
01:07:45,882 --> 01:07:49,122
[Oh yeah? Just leave it to me!]

1680
01:07:49,122 --> 01:07:50,912
[Having secured his spot]
I can't ever give up this spot.

1681
01:07:50,912 --> 01:07:53,182
That's skill, real skill.

1682
01:07:54,522 --> 01:07:55,612
[You can do this, right?]
Okay?

1683
01:07:55,612 --> 01:07:57,582
[I can do!]
Okay.

1684
01:07:57,582 --> 01:08:00,732
[With a determined? Dimpled smile]

1685
01:08:00,732 --> 01:08:02,332
[Risotto round two begins]

1686
01:08:02,332 --> 01:08:03,902
You've gotta look out for
your own meal ticket too.

1687
01:08:03,902 --> 01:08:06,062
- Right, you gotta show initiative.
- Of course.

1688
01:08:06,062 --> 01:08:09,322
- You can't just wait for someone to tell you.
- Right, right.

1689
01:08:09,322 --> 01:08:10,622
[A glance]

1690
01:08:10,622 --> 01:08:14,802
[Also keeping an eye on Senior Pa's menu
while he's away]

1691
01:08:14,802 --> 01:08:17,502
[Good job]

1692
01:08:17,502 --> 01:08:18,992
[Standing shoulder to shoulder
with the burner-station seniors]

1693
01:08:18,992 --> 01:08:20,172
Feels natural now.

1694
01:08:20,172 --> 01:08:23,442
[Kwon, fully absorbed in risotto, is moving up?]
Whoa, Sung Jun, that's amazing.

1695
01:08:23,442 --> 01:08:25,362
[Beep beep]

1696
01:08:25,362 --> 01:08:27,932
[The risotto timer goes off]

1697
01:08:27,932 --> 01:08:29,452
[Tasting spoon]

1698
01:08:29,452 --> 01:08:33,082
[Midway risotto check]

1699
01:08:33,082 --> 01:08:35,772
[Owner Luisa tastes it carefully]

1700
01:08:35,772 --> 01:08:37,802
[Nods...]

1701
01:08:37,802 --> 01:08:40,842
This time, you try it.

1702
01:08:40,842 --> 01:08:42,582
[Nom]

1703
01:08:45,402 --> 01:08:47,292
I think... it needs a bit more salt.

1704
01:08:47,292 --> 01:08:49,422
[Correct answer!]

1705
01:08:49,422 --> 01:08:50,802
Well, my seasoning's right on point.

1706
01:08:50,802 --> 01:08:51,922
- Right on point.
- Is it good now?

1707
01:08:51,922 --> 01:08:53,392
- Let's go!
- Yes.

1708
01:08:53,392 --> 01:08:56,682
[Moving to the plating station]

1709
01:08:56,682 --> 01:08:58,602
[Butter]

1710
01:08:59,202 --> 01:09:01,112
[Cheese]

1711
01:09:01,792 --> 01:09:02,832
Mix it up!

1712
01:09:02,832 --> 01:09:05,312
[Mix, mix]

1713
01:09:05,312 --> 01:09:10,492
[Beginning the mantecare]

1714
01:09:10,492 --> 01:09:12,572
You know to mix it until
the butter's fully melted, right?

1715
01:09:12,572 --> 01:09:14,218
Yes!

1716
01:09:15,132 --> 01:09:19,242
[With skilled mantecare technique]

1717
01:09:19,242 --> 01:09:20,832
[Achieving that creamy risotto texture]
Quickly.

1718
01:09:20,832 --> 01:09:22,482
Until it emulsifies.

1719
01:09:22,482 --> 01:09:25,582
So the oil and water blend together well.

1720
01:09:25,582 --> 01:09:28,402
[Quickly dividing it into bowls]

1721
01:09:28,402 --> 01:09:29,842
- Yes, right?
- Yes.

1722
01:09:29,842 --> 01:09:30,992
[Plop plop]

1723
01:09:30,992 --> 01:09:34,222
You always have to spread the risotto out nice
and flat like that.

1724
01:09:34,222 --> 01:09:36,740
[That's it, well done!]

1725
01:09:36,740 --> 01:09:38,252
But why do you have to spread it out?

1726
01:09:38,252 --> 01:09:40,802
Hmm... To show that it turned out well?

1727
01:09:40,802 --> 01:09:42,522
Really?

1728
01:09:42,522 --> 01:09:44,302
[Pung's guess]
Or is it to cool it down faster?

1729
01:09:44,302 --> 01:09:46,242
[Rice piled up high]
No, it's because if the rice piles up like that,

1730
01:09:46,242 --> 01:09:48,032
the rice in the middle keeps cooking more.

1731
01:09:48,032 --> 01:09:49,872
[Needs flattening has to be spread out flat!]
You spread it out.

1732
01:09:49,872 --> 01:09:51,582
Oh, that's right.

1733
01:09:51,582 --> 01:09:53,632
[MC Kim Pung, thrilled Kwon doesn't know yet]
Huh, you didn't know?

1734
01:09:53,632 --> 01:09:54,832
You didn't know!

1735
01:09:54,832 --> 01:09:56,972
- You learned that here.
- Learned it, learned it.

1736
01:09:56,972 --> 01:09:58,887
You're learning a lot on "Undercover!"

1737
01:09:58,887 --> 01:10:00,017
Learned another thing.

1738
01:10:00,017 --> 01:10:01,868
I see.

1739
01:10:03,102 --> 01:10:08,542
[Fun fact: wide spreading prevents overcooking]

1740
01:10:08,542 --> 01:10:12,122
[Now it's just a matter
of drizzling the sauce well]

1741
01:10:16,092 --> 01:10:17,262
[Title of the piece: Swirl of Freedom]
Again!

1742
01:10:17,262 --> 01:10:20,272
- It's round from the middle out.
- The consistency itself is off.

1743
01:10:20,272 --> 01:10:21,642
It's fine, right?

1744
01:10:21,642 --> 01:10:23,372
[Fully focused]

1745
01:10:23,372 --> 01:10:25,352
Yes, it's fine!

1746
01:10:26,732 --> 01:10:28,122
[Riding on An's approval, finishes the plating]
Now I just plate it on my own.

1747
01:10:28,122 --> 01:10:29,902
[Covering it up?]

1748
01:10:29,902 --> 01:10:31,842
- Why does he keep covering it up?
- Covering it.

1749
01:10:31,842 --> 01:10:33,482
[Wraps it up neatly]
Can't help that one.

1750
01:10:33,482 --> 01:10:36,032
Couldn't be helped.

1751
01:10:36,032 --> 01:10:37,532
Good job.

1752
01:10:37,532 --> 01:10:39,162
But the shape's really pretty.

1753
01:10:39,162 --> 01:10:42,092
- It's pretty.
- The color, the color combo is so good.

1754
01:10:42,092 --> 01:10:45,102
Shape aside,
the color combination is really nice.

1755
01:10:45,102 --> 01:10:48,992
Alright, there are
two more risotto orders, Kwon!

1756
01:10:48,992 --> 01:10:52,412
At this point, just keep handling it yourself!

1757
01:10:53,712 --> 01:10:55,072
[Senior Pa, who'd already been making risotto]

1758
01:10:55,072 --> 01:10:57,722
[Tossing risotto duty over to
the NEW guy, Kwon grabs it]

1759
01:10:57,722 --> 01:10:59,852
Wow, this has basically
become the risotto station now.

1760
01:10:59,852 --> 01:11:01,792
[Is risotto a piece of cake now?]
- Naturally. - Just naturally.

1761
01:11:01,792 --> 01:11:04,812
Risotto's just naturally mine now.

1762
01:11:05,962 --> 01:11:09,447
[He's good at this...]

1763
01:11:09,447 --> 01:11:12,962
[While he was distracted by the cod]
[The one who got his risotto duty stolen by a junior]

1764
01:11:12,962 --> 01:11:16,012
- Got it stolen by a junior.
- Wow, this is...

1765
01:11:16,812 --> 01:11:21,772
I think Kwon actually prefers
being on the risotto station.

1766
01:11:21,772 --> 01:11:23,552
[He's totally sulking]
He's sulking.

1767
01:11:23,552 --> 01:11:24,812
- He's sulking.
- Oh, Paolo.

1768
01:11:24,812 --> 01:11:26,892
[Inner pout]
- He's not happy. - He's sulking.

1769
01:11:26,892 --> 01:11:30,462
- He said he'd do mains.
- That always-smiling Paolo.

1770
01:11:31,242 --> 01:11:32,642
[Kwon... are you happy?]

1771
01:11:32,642 --> 01:11:34,112
- Geez.
- Sung Jun, what do we do about this...

1772
01:11:34,112 --> 01:11:35,650
No, this is what happens when I get serious.

1773
01:11:35,650 --> 01:11:37,642
Watching Kwon make risotto...

1774
01:11:37,642 --> 01:11:41,532
He's already doing really well.

1775
01:11:41,532 --> 01:11:44,302
I feel almost betrayed by Kwon.

1776
01:11:44,302 --> 01:11:46,242
Oh, really?

1777
01:11:46,242 --> 01:11:49,042
I'm joking, I'm happy about it.

1778
01:11:49,042 --> 01:11:53,342
If someone moves stations
to learn something new,

1779
01:11:53,342 --> 01:11:54,972
- I'm happy for them.
- Of course.

1780
01:11:54,972 --> 01:11:56,432
I was joking earlier...

1781
01:11:56,432 --> 01:11:59,532
[Moved Really?]

1782
01:11:59,532 --> 01:12:03,562
[While Kwon chases his dream
at the burner station...]

1783
01:12:03,562 --> 01:12:05,442
[Lonely, An handles the appetizers alone...]
How should I put it?

1784
01:12:05,442 --> 01:12:08,732
- Like men who've lost their girlfriends.
- Right.

1785
01:12:09,372 --> 01:12:11,742
[A glance]

1786
01:12:11,742 --> 01:12:14,442
[A glance]

1787
01:12:14,442 --> 01:12:16,912
[Whoosh]

1788
01:12:16,912 --> 01:12:21,122
[Keeps glancing over at Senior An...]

1789
01:12:21,122 --> 01:12:25,022
[The ex-junior pulls fried food out for An!]
I realized what Senior An needed.

1790
01:12:26,702 --> 01:12:29,712
[Kwon hasn't forgotten me...]
Thanks, Kwon.

1791
01:12:29,712 --> 01:12:31,022
[It's nothing]
Yeah.

1792
01:12:31,022 --> 01:12:32,842
Since I've done appetizers too.

1793
01:12:32,842 --> 01:12:34,202
[Then, without a word,
starts helping with the appetizer platter]

1794
01:12:34,202 --> 01:12:36,682
Right at the moment it's needed!

1795
01:12:36,682 --> 01:12:39,262
[Senior and junior working in sync
side by side, for the first time in a while?]

1796
01:12:39,262 --> 01:12:42,262
But that's actually how
Antonio normally works too.

1797
01:12:42,992 --> 01:12:44,302
He starts on the appetizer station,

1798
01:12:44,302 --> 01:12:45,522
and once he has a bit of breathing room,

1799
01:12:45,522 --> 01:12:47,532
he helps with pasta, then goes to mains.

1800
01:12:47,532 --> 01:12:50,382
That's how it works in a kitchen this small.

1801
01:12:50,382 --> 01:12:53,666
Everyone takes turns
doing everything for each other.

1802
01:12:53,666 --> 01:12:56,992
I worked hard thinking,
"I should help out as much as I can too".

1803
01:12:56,992 --> 01:12:58,802
[If Senior Pa on the mains station looks busy]

1804
01:12:58,802 --> 01:13:02,182
[Waiting on the oven]
While doing this, I'd also go help with mains.

1805
01:13:02,922 --> 01:13:04,912
[Grilling cod steak in place of Senior Pa too]
He's skilled now.

1806
01:13:04,912 --> 01:13:06,352
Oh my gosh, thank you.

1807
01:13:06,352 --> 01:13:08,802
- Thanks.
- Because now I can see everything.

1808
01:13:08,802 --> 01:13:11,952
[You're doing great, Kwon!]
Okay.

1809
01:13:11,952 --> 01:13:13,392
[Infiltrated the burner, instincts remain!]
It's good!

1810
01:13:13,392 --> 01:13:16,832
So now he's developed an eye
for reading this whole kitchen.

1811
01:13:16,832 --> 01:13:21,692
Whether I'm working on
appetizers, pasta, or dessert,

1812
01:13:21,692 --> 01:13:23,342
whenever I turn around,
Kwon's always already right there

1813
01:13:23,342 --> 01:13:25,882
either helping out or watching me.

1814
01:13:25,882 --> 01:13:29,472
Not everyone has that kind of attitude.

1815
01:13:29,472 --> 01:13:31,552
- That's Senior An for you.
- Kwon's really a good person.

1816
01:13:31,552 --> 01:13:34,912
[Sung Jun, good person]
That's Senior Pa for you.

1817
01:13:37,102 --> 01:13:40,312
[Kwon is finishing the last risotto tonight]

1818
01:13:43,722 --> 01:13:46,302
[Perfect temp and consistency, nails the swirl]
Oh, it's cooled down.

1819
01:13:46,302 --> 01:13:48,722
The consistency's finally about right.

1820
01:13:48,722 --> 01:13:49,902
Two risottos going out.

1821
01:13:49,902 --> 01:13:52,332
[Focused to the very end]
Yes, yes.

1822
01:13:54,066 --> 01:13:57,872
Thank you.

1823
01:13:57,872 --> 01:14:02,380
[Kwon's risotto is delivered to the customers]

1824
01:14:02,380 --> 01:14:05,008
The risotto is so pretty!

1825
01:14:05,008 --> 01:14:07,782
Just as expected... You've got a good eye.

1826
01:14:08,962 --> 01:14:10,952
Self-praise.

1827
01:14:14,892 --> 01:14:17,482
[Fully satisfied]

1828
01:14:17,482 --> 01:14:21,082
[Scrape, scrape]
- It must be delicious. - Exactly.

1829
01:14:21,082 --> 01:14:24,861
But that color alone gives off
such an appetizing feel.

1830
01:14:25,742 --> 01:14:27,422
Hey, but today,

1831
01:14:27,422 --> 01:14:29,692
[Thanks to the salty cod]
we should really thank that salty cod.

1832
01:14:29,692 --> 01:14:31,582
[MVP in my heart]
Because the cod turned out salty,

1833
01:14:31,582 --> 01:14:33,422
- that's how we ended up here.
- You got lucky.

1834
01:14:33,422 --> 01:14:35,282
- No, this is...
- Real lucky, huh.

1835
01:14:35,282 --> 01:14:38,362
Because I made risotto at lunch!
That's how this opportunity came my way.

1836
01:14:38,362 --> 01:14:40,382
But you have to be prepared to seize
an opportunity like this, don't you think?

1837
01:14:40,382 --> 01:14:42,642
- That's actually a fair point too.
- Right, right, exactly.

1838
01:14:42,642 --> 01:14:44,402
Honestly, you need that eagerness.

1839
01:14:44,402 --> 01:14:46,762
- People look kindly on that too.
- Right.

1840
01:14:46,762 --> 01:14:49,872
That's really the kind of behavior
that sets an example.

1841
01:14:49,872 --> 01:14:51,842
I'll turn off the pasta cooker now.

1842
01:14:51,842 --> 01:14:53,372
Oh, it's over now.

1843
01:14:53,372 --> 01:14:55,807
What a busy day.

1844
01:14:57,552 --> 01:15:00,012
[Wasn't it the "3-day promise?"]
Yeah.

1845
01:15:00,012 --> 01:15:02,412
That's right.

1846
01:15:02,412 --> 01:15:04,222
- The promised three days.
- Yeah.

1847
01:15:04,222 --> 01:15:05,452
Haven't I achieved it?

1848
01:15:05,452 --> 01:15:09,112
I thought I'd already hit my goal by day three?

1849
01:15:10,722 --> 01:15:12,522
[Final mission still incomplete?]
Not quite to the final menu yet...

1850
01:15:12,522 --> 01:15:13,602
Oh, the menu?

1851
01:15:13,602 --> 01:15:15,102
- You have to get a menu item listed.
- Right, anyway.

1852
01:15:15,102 --> 01:15:17,152
My goal was, first of all,

1853
01:15:17,152 --> 01:15:19,232
to do everything in the kitchen.

1854
01:15:19,232 --> 01:15:22,332
[Huh? Making up his own mission?]
Since that was my goal.

1855
01:15:22,332 --> 01:15:25,802
Are you just going ahead
and revising the whole show concept yourself?

1856
01:15:25,802 --> 01:15:27,292
Are you the production team now?

1857
01:15:27,292 --> 01:15:29,362
[Sam Kwon breaks the day-3 promise]
Well, the original plan was that, but...

1858
01:15:29,362 --> 01:15:31,042
That's what I wanted to do.

1859
01:15:31,042 --> 01:15:32,252
What are you talking about?

1860
01:15:32,252 --> 01:15:34,332
Oh, you had your own personal
mission on top of it?

1861
01:15:34,332 --> 01:15:35,452
[Noble]
A fight against myself.

1862
01:15:35,452 --> 01:15:37,562
Oh, "completed my fight against myself."

1863
01:15:37,562 --> 01:15:38,972
It was a mission against myself.

1864
01:15:38,972 --> 01:15:40,782
Oh, you didn't mention that at first.

1865
01:15:40,782 --> 01:15:42,752
You didn't tell us about your
"fight against myself" mission.

1866
01:15:42,752 --> 01:15:44,412
That was my mission, and...

1867
01:15:44,412 --> 01:15:45,792
There are still two days left, right?

1868
01:15:45,792 --> 01:15:46,862
Oh, the production team's mission...

1869
01:15:46,862 --> 01:15:48,242
- Just starting now.
- Just starting, huh?

1870
01:15:48,242 --> 01:15:49,852
- The menu thing is just getting started.
- Wow, really...

1871
01:15:49,852 --> 01:15:51,442
Guess that part got edited out.

1872
01:15:51,442 --> 01:15:53,102
- That part.
- Right, this got edited out.

1873
01:15:53,102 --> 01:15:54,592
You did say that too, right?

1874
01:15:54,592 --> 01:15:56,842
[Shameless]
I'm not really sure.

1875
01:15:56,842 --> 01:15:58,442
Well, first I need to actually be helpful,

1876
01:15:58,442 --> 01:16:00,652
But the restaurant's way busier
than I expected.

1877
01:16:00,652 --> 01:16:02,142
A kitchen is...

1878
01:16:02,142 --> 01:16:04,942
You didn't know this when planning it,
but you must've felt it by now watching us.

1879
01:16:04,942 --> 01:16:06,222
In a place where you work like this,

1880
01:16:06,222 --> 01:16:07,842
there's honestly no time to do anything extra.

1881
01:16:07,842 --> 01:16:10,352
- You'd die if you tried that.
- Wow. That's for sure.

1882
01:16:10,352 --> 01:16:12,032
[Ruling: the promised day 3 is a fail]
Wait, what, is it a fail?

1883
01:16:12,032 --> 01:16:13,772
- Basically a fail.
- I thought it was a success.

1884
01:16:13,772 --> 01:16:15,162
It's basically a fail.

1885
01:16:15,162 --> 01:16:18,592
[Did his best either way, tired...]
[Yawn]

1886
01:16:18,592 --> 01:16:21,022
- Oh, that was tough.
- Must've been really tough.

1887
01:16:21,022 --> 01:16:22,842
You're tired, right?

1888
01:16:22,842 --> 01:16:25,292
[This is nothing!]
A little tired, but...

1889
01:16:25,292 --> 01:16:27,912
Come in, come in!

1890
01:16:29,342 --> 01:16:30,682
[Follow me]
[Who's this?]

1891
01:16:30,682 --> 01:16:31,792
Who is it?

1892
01:16:31,792 --> 01:16:33,882
[People heading to the kitchen
following the owner?]

1893
01:16:33,882 --> 01:16:36,412
More customers?

1894
01:16:36,412 --> 01:16:39,842
[Rumble]

1895
01:16:39,842 --> 01:16:43,312
[These people ambushed the kitchen?]
Good evening.

1896
01:16:43,312 --> 01:16:48,282
[Flustered]
[Who are these people looking for Kwon?]

1897
01:16:50,162 --> 01:16:53,202
In Chengdu, China, here's our Chef Jung Ji Sun.

1898
01:16:53,202 --> 01:16:55,482
[Day 3 undercover]
What will happen today, I wonder?

1899
01:16:55,482 --> 01:16:56,842
- Let's...
- Is she going to the burner station?

1900
01:16:56,842 --> 01:16:58,512
Let's watch together.

1901
01:16:58,512 --> 01:17:01,682
Could I make the staff meal?

1902
01:17:01,682 --> 01:17:03,292
Of course, of course!

1903
01:17:03,292 --> 01:17:05,472
What are you making?

1904
01:17:05,472 --> 01:17:06,862
Beef bulgogi.

1905
01:17:06,862 --> 01:17:08,642
- It's Korean bulgogi.
- Now for the staff meal.

1906
01:17:08,642 --> 01:17:10,322
Korean-style beef bulgogi.

1907
01:17:10,322 --> 01:17:12,445
[Tak tak]
- She's making the dish. - Right.

1908
01:17:12,445 --> 01:17:13,446
Huh?

1909
01:17:13,446 --> 01:17:15,532
[Cutting through even the
earpiece tak tak tak tak tak tak tak]

1910
01:17:15,532 --> 01:17:16,912
[With a 50-person batch, completely
forgetting she's undercover] [Knife skill]

1911
01:17:16,912 --> 01:17:18,812
Her old habits are starting to show through.

1912
01:17:18,812 --> 01:17:20,492
[Startled]
- She's a real pro after all! - It's startling.

1913
01:17:20,492 --> 01:17:22,492
- Number two.
- She's chopping so fast, rat-tat-tat!

1914
01:17:22,492 --> 01:17:23,982
You really bought a ton?

1915
01:17:23,982 --> 01:17:26,202
[50 servings of meat alone]
[Floored]

1916
01:17:26,202 --> 01:17:28,192
- They love it so much.
- In case there's not enough.

1917
01:17:28,192 --> 01:17:30,682
We can't even finish it all.

1918
01:17:30,682 --> 01:17:32,812
[Crowned the big-spender junior]

1919
01:17:32,812 --> 01:17:36,332
[An enormous amount of bulgogi]

1920
01:17:36,332 --> 01:17:40,402
[How the 50-serving bulgogi tastes]
[Coming up shortly at the staff meal!]

1921
01:17:40,402 --> 01:17:43,612
[11:00 AM, day 3 lunch service]
- Day 3. - Is that rice?

1922
01:17:43,612 --> 01:17:48,402
[Service begins with the sound of rice cooking]

1923
01:17:48,402 --> 01:17:53,402
[Packed with family customers,
from kids to adults]

1924
01:17:53,402 --> 01:17:55,842
One of these, please.

1925
01:17:55,842 --> 01:17:58,572
My teeth aren't great, so one mapo tofu please.

1926
01:17:58,572 --> 01:18:00,142
You ordered the stir-fried kidney beans, right?

1927
01:18:00,142 --> 01:18:02,442
[Here it comes!]
It's sweet and sour, right?

1928
01:18:02,442 --> 01:18:04,352
It's here!

1929
01:18:04,352 --> 01:18:05,452
[Order's in!]

1930
01:18:05,452 --> 01:18:07,182
Whoa, what is that?

1931
01:18:07,182 --> 01:18:10,202
Prep one whole sea bass!

1932
01:18:10,202 --> 01:18:11,932
[When an order comes in?]

1933
01:18:11,932 --> 01:18:14,542
One sea bass.

1934
01:18:14,542 --> 01:18:16,412
What else is there?

1935
01:18:16,412 --> 01:18:21,512
[Wok station cooking begins]

1936
01:18:23,182 --> 01:18:26,002
[Flavor created by the chef's
wok skills and fire control]

1937
01:18:26,002 --> 01:18:27,632
That looks delicious.

1938
01:18:27,632 --> 01:18:29,692
Looks delicious.

1939
01:18:29,692 --> 01:18:31,482
[This is what Sunny has to overcome]
Really looks delicious.

1940
01:18:31,482 --> 01:18:33,692
One soup, please.

1941
01:18:33,692 --> 01:18:36,622
[The Wok station in Chengdu]

1942
01:18:36,622 --> 01:18:38,082
Chef Yang!

1943
01:18:38,082 --> 01:18:40,112
Here are the swamp eel ingredients.

1944
01:18:40,112 --> 01:18:43,052
Stir-fried swamp eel with chili peppers.

1945
01:18:45,322 --> 01:18:49,392
[Sunny quickly grabs a bowl
the moment she hears the dish name]

1946
01:18:49,392 --> 01:18:53,442
[Ace Sunny's unshakable instincts]
Now she just picks up on things right away.

1947
01:18:53,442 --> 01:18:56,572
[What about the prepped swamp eel?]
Curious about that swamp eel.

1948
01:18:56,572 --> 01:19:02,302
[Fries it to drive off the moisture]

1949
01:19:03,765 --> 01:19:06,302
Wow, that looks delicious.

1950
01:19:06,302 --> 01:19:08,172
I'd love to try that.

1951
01:19:09,742 --> 01:19:12,492
[Stacking it up neatly]

1952
01:19:12,492 --> 01:19:15,672
[Plating on pure reflex]

1953
01:19:17,722 --> 01:19:21,072
[The hands of a 24-year pro
slipping out without thinking]

1954
01:19:21,072 --> 01:19:23,772
[Sunny even handles the order slip herself,
without missing a beat]

1955
01:19:23,772 --> 01:19:25,552
[Sunny, coming through]
You can just put it beside there.

1956
01:19:25,552 --> 01:19:26,992
Beside?

1957
01:19:26,992 --> 01:19:29,902
[Delivery complete]

1958
01:19:30,602 --> 01:19:31,662
[Cleanup, spot-less]

1959
01:19:31,662 --> 01:19:33,932
[Pleased]

1960
01:19:33,932 --> 01:19:35,182
[Slide]

1961
01:19:35,182 --> 01:19:37,082
I want to see this, but it's too low down.

1962
01:19:37,082 --> 01:19:40,802
[After scanning the burner senior's dish]
Go quickly, since you have to head over there.

1963
01:19:40,802 --> 01:19:42,962
[Prepping the matching ingredients]

1964
01:19:42,962 --> 01:19:45,322
[At the sight of Sunny
handling everything on her own]

1965
01:19:45,322 --> 01:19:47,482
[Thumbs up]

1966
01:19:47,482 --> 01:19:51,052
[Heh. This is nothing]
That's real instinct, honestly.

1967
01:19:51,052 --> 01:19:53,482
You don't need this bowl anymore, right?

1968
01:19:53,482 --> 01:19:55,952
I'll take it.

1969
01:19:55,952 --> 01:19:58,467
[Reliable Sunny]

1970
01:19:58,467 --> 01:20:01,987
[With the staff meal coming up,
Sunny handles her own job crisply]

1971
01:20:03,082 --> 01:20:06,362
[A tool makes an appearance this time?]

1972
01:20:06,362 --> 01:20:07,962
[The most senior burner cook,
prepping chili peppers]

1973
01:20:07,962 --> 01:20:10,632
[Sunny joins in with scissors too]

1974
01:20:11,312 --> 01:20:14,562
[Checking the prep size]

1975
01:20:14,562 --> 01:20:17,322
[Handles it with instinct, without being told]

1976
01:20:17,322 --> 01:20:19,482
[Impressive]

1977
01:20:19,482 --> 01:20:22,962
[Most senior burner cook]
We're going to turn it into chili powder.

1978
01:20:22,962 --> 01:20:25,562
Being in Sichuan,
I know they use really good chili peppers.

1979
01:20:25,562 --> 01:20:29,442
Right, the chilies really
look great at a glance.

1980
01:20:29,442 --> 01:20:31,532
Which chili is spicier?

1981
01:20:31,532 --> 01:20:34,442
This one's Chaotian chili.

1982
01:20:34,442 --> 01:20:35,902
The other one is Xiaomi chili.

1983
01:20:35,902 --> 01:20:38,402
[Chaotian, Xiaomi, Qixing chili blend]
- This one's Qixing chili. - Qixing chili.

1984
01:20:38,402 --> 01:20:40,012
- They blend the chilies.
- We stir-fry all three kinds together.

1985
01:20:40,012 --> 01:20:41,022
I see.

1986
01:20:41,022 --> 01:20:42,432
The special chili powder
goes into the Spicy Pork Slices.

1987
01:20:42,432 --> 01:20:44,192
Spicy Pork Slices!

1988
01:20:44,192 --> 01:20:46,142
Oh, it's Spicy Pork Slices!

1989
01:20:46,142 --> 01:20:48,522
[With ginger, minced garlic,
and spicy doubanjiang added in]

1990
01:20:48,522 --> 01:20:49,932
Doubanjiang with Sichuan peppercorns.

1991
01:20:49,932 --> 01:20:53,082
That's the foundation of Sichuan cooking.

1992
01:20:53,082 --> 01:20:55,822
[Right into the thickly sliced pork]
Like blanching the meat a little.

1993
01:20:55,822 --> 01:20:56,922
[Sichuan's spicy flavor soaking in deep]

1994
01:20:56,922 --> 01:20:58,172
Ooh, that looks delicious.

1995
01:20:58,172 --> 01:20:59,452
It's delicious.

1996
01:20:59,452 --> 01:21:00,732
Oh, looks delicious.

1997
01:21:00,732 --> 01:21:03,692
Drizzle the oil all over to
really bring out the aroma.

1998
01:21:03,692 --> 01:21:07,532
[Sichuan's rich, spicy flavor]
[Spicy Pork Slices]

1999
01:21:07,532 --> 01:21:09,874
My mouth's tingling...
but it's spicy and delicious!

2000
01:21:09,874 --> 01:21:11,532
[Slurp]

2001
01:21:11,532 --> 01:21:14,032
At some restaurants,
all the spicy food tastes the same.

2002
01:21:14,032 --> 01:21:16,092
But at this place,
every dish has a different kind of spicy!

2003
01:21:16,092 --> 01:21:17,282
Right, right.

2004
01:21:17,282 --> 01:21:18,992
- Because they blend the chilies.
- Right.

2005
01:21:18,992 --> 01:21:22,370
They're definitely saying
the flavors are all different.

2006
01:21:22,370 --> 01:21:26,382
- Seems like a lot of people would come here.
- Right.

2007
01:21:27,312 --> 01:21:31,742
[Getting delivered one after
another to the customers' tables]

2008
01:21:31,742 --> 01:21:34,382
There's one kidney dish.

2009
01:21:34,382 --> 01:21:36,442
Steam this one!

2010
01:21:36,442 --> 01:21:38,752
[The kitchen running nonstop during lunch]
- Really. - It's busy.

2011
01:21:38,752 --> 01:21:41,442
It's really busy.

2012
01:21:41,442 --> 01:21:43,212
[In this busy kitchen]
So here, on her own.

2013
01:21:43,212 --> 01:21:45,022
Unless she does something herself,

2014
01:21:45,022 --> 01:21:46,862
there's no one telling her what to do

2015
01:21:46,862 --> 01:21:49,182
or keeping an eye on her.
There's just no time for that at all.

2016
01:21:49,182 --> 01:21:51,212
- Since it's such a busy place, how could you...
- Exactly.

2017
01:21:51,212 --> 01:21:52,882
- That...
- Why, why, why?

2018
01:21:52,882 --> 01:21:53,952
Chef Yang!

2019
01:21:53,952 --> 01:21:55,712
Did you toast the dried red chilies?

2020
01:21:55,712 --> 01:21:58,672
We can't be without it when we cook later.

2021
01:21:58,672 --> 01:22:01,439
[Grandma has him toast chilies for the powder]
Because the flavor's different.

2022
01:22:02,402 --> 01:22:05,262
Chili powder.

2023
01:22:07,474 --> 01:22:12,062
[Time to properly turn it into the
chili powder that'll be used in cooking]

2024
01:22:12,062 --> 01:22:15,282
[The most senior burner cook
gets ready to toast the chilies]

2025
01:22:15,282 --> 01:22:17,822
That amount of chili is basically mill-level.

2026
01:22:17,822 --> 01:22:20,242
[Let's see]

2027
01:22:20,242 --> 01:22:22,812
[Glancing]

2028
01:22:22,812 --> 01:22:25,682
[The most senior burner cook]
Try toasting the chilies.

2029
01:22:25,682 --> 01:22:27,022
Give it a try.

2030
01:22:27,022 --> 01:22:28,522
Oh, a chance.

2031
01:22:28,522 --> 01:22:30,462
- Telling her to toast chilies.
- Finally, finally.

2032
01:22:30,462 --> 01:22:32,652
- Finally.
- Finally, she's using fire.

2033
01:22:32,652 --> 01:22:34,622
[The burner-station chance has arrived!]
- Try toasting it? - This?

2034
01:22:34,622 --> 01:22:36,332
Telling her to practice once.

2035
01:22:36,332 --> 01:22:38,252
Okay, okay!

2036
01:22:38,252 --> 01:22:39,922
- I like it.
- She's thrilled.

2037
01:22:39,922 --> 01:22:42,592
It was fun that they let me try toasting it.

2038
01:22:42,592 --> 01:22:44,142
Since you've practiced.

2039
01:22:44,142 --> 01:22:45,902
[Before making the staff meal]
This is harder.

2040
01:22:45,902 --> 01:22:46,992
Is it spicier?

2041
01:22:46,992 --> 01:22:49,782
[A good time to get the hang of it!]
I said it's harder.

2042
01:22:49,782 --> 01:22:51,072
But the wok's kind of big.

2043
01:22:51,072 --> 01:22:54,522
Working the wok is harder here!

2044
01:22:54,522 --> 01:22:57,872
[The giant wok stands by]
- Is it spicier? - I said it's harder.

2045
01:22:57,872 --> 01:22:59,642
[Compared to the wok
she'd been practicing with before]

2046
01:22:59,642 --> 01:23:01,772
[A noticeably different-sized wok!]

2047
01:23:01,772 --> 01:23:06,522
[The practice wok doubles as staff-meal wok]
Still, since the wok's so big.

2048
01:23:06,522 --> 01:23:08,272
[About twice the size]

2049
01:23:08,272 --> 01:23:09,822
Twice the size? It got twice as big?

2050
01:23:09,822 --> 01:23:11,762
- This is harder, working this wok.
- It's harder.

2051
01:23:11,762 --> 01:23:14,322
It's harder.

2052
01:23:14,322 --> 01:23:16,122
[But for Sunny?]

2053
01:23:16,122 --> 01:23:19,562
[A chance to handle the 50-serving wok!]

2054
01:23:19,562 --> 01:23:20,802
Did practice go well yesterday?

2055
01:23:20,802 --> 01:23:23,282
She did pretty well yesterday!

2056
01:23:23,282 --> 01:23:25,632
[One round of practice with the glasses senior]
Right, since she practiced last night.

2057
01:23:25,632 --> 01:23:29,682
[Today it's a wok twice as big]
Right, and he showed me how to hold it too.

2058
01:23:29,682 --> 01:23:32,302
[Will Sunny manage with the big wok too?]

2059
01:23:32,302 --> 01:23:33,472
[Curious] [Will she succeed?]
Alright, can she do it?

2060
01:23:33,472 --> 01:23:34,672
It's gotten bigger.

2061
01:23:34,672 --> 01:23:37,132
[Excited]
Everyone's got high hopes.

2062
01:23:38,842 --> 01:23:40,672
[Whoosh]

2063
01:23:40,672 --> 01:23:42,562
Oh, it works.

2064
01:23:42,562 --> 01:23:44,912
- As expected.
- It's flipping.

2065
01:23:44,912 --> 01:23:47,822
[Chilies flow smoothly in the giant wok]
- Nice. - It's working.

2066
01:23:47,822 --> 01:23:49,932
She's good at this.

2067
01:23:49,932 --> 01:23:51,902
Oh, right, right!

2068
01:23:51,902 --> 01:23:53,632
[Satisfied]

2069
01:23:53,632 --> 01:23:57,232
[At this rate, 50 servings
of bulgogi is totally doable!]

2070
01:23:57,232 --> 01:23:59,477
It took me a month.

2071
01:23:59,477 --> 01:24:02,992
- You pulled it off in one day.
- In one day.

2072
01:24:02,992 --> 01:24:04,862
A month... In one day.

2073
01:24:04,862 --> 01:24:06,092
You've learned it all now!

2074
01:24:06,092 --> 01:24:08,282
You could go out on your own!

2075
01:24:08,282 --> 01:24:10,012
- Already?
- Go independent.

2076
01:24:10,012 --> 01:24:11,342
[Thumbs up]
Amazing!

2077
01:24:11,342 --> 01:24:13,772
Amazing!

2078
01:24:13,772 --> 01:24:15,632
She's really the manliest woman around!

2079
01:24:15,632 --> 01:24:18,162
Ah, "manliest woman," huh...

2080
01:24:18,162 --> 01:24:20,002
["Really the manliest woman?"]
She's really the manliest woman around!

2081
01:24:20,002 --> 01:24:22,302
"Manliest woman," this is...

2082
01:24:22,302 --> 01:24:24,272
[It's a compliment!]
So this is... a compliment.

2083
01:24:24,272 --> 01:24:25,932
- "The manliest woman."
- Right.

2084
01:24:25,932 --> 01:24:27,342
[Acknowledged as a compliment]
- It's a compliment. - Not "the manliest man,"

2085
01:24:27,342 --> 01:24:28,972
"the manliest woman."

2086
01:24:28,972 --> 01:24:30,492
This is a compliment.

2087
01:24:30,492 --> 01:24:33,072
[Compliment]
She's really the manliest woman around!

2088
01:24:33,072 --> 01:24:36,002
Everyone else struggles
after just a few wok flips!

2089
01:24:36,002 --> 01:24:38,032
Right! Your arms give out right away.

2090
01:24:38,032 --> 01:24:39,772
But our Sunny used to be a boxer.

2091
01:24:39,772 --> 01:24:41,792
- Athletes really are different.
- She really is an athlete.

2092
01:24:41,792 --> 01:24:44,142
[A former boxer really is different!]

2093
01:24:44,142 --> 01:24:45,322
It's different.

2094
01:24:45,322 --> 01:24:48,092
- Sunny's really a powerhouse of a woman.
- It's because she was a boxer.

2095
01:24:48,092 --> 01:24:51,302
[Former boxer]
Wow, glad I picked that career.

2096
01:24:52,062 --> 01:24:54,032
[Bustling]
Clear this up a bit.

2097
01:24:54,032 --> 01:24:56,602
[Boss Nam appears]

2098
01:24:57,232 --> 01:25:00,972
[Slips over toward the commotion]
The boss is here.

2099
01:25:00,972 --> 01:25:05,292
Everyone's watching.

2100
01:25:05,292 --> 01:25:08,062
[Not realizing Boss Nam has arrived,
fully focused on toasting chilies]

2101
01:25:08,062 --> 01:25:10,522
She's really good with the wok.
It's a really big wok but she's good.

2102
01:25:10,522 --> 01:25:12,252
- It's such a big wok.
- Exactly.

2103
01:25:12,252 --> 01:25:13,902
She flips it well.

2104
01:25:13,902 --> 01:25:17,522
She's really amazing.

2105
01:25:17,522 --> 01:25:19,852
[And...]

2106
01:25:19,852 --> 01:25:23,302
Ah, the boss, sharp-eyed from behind.

2107
01:25:26,302 --> 01:25:28,752
[Showing off her skill]

2108
01:25:28,752 --> 01:25:30,082
She's showing it off, huh?

2109
01:25:30,082 --> 01:25:34,412
Hoping he'll watch and then
ask me to do something else.

2110
01:25:34,412 --> 01:25:37,502
Something about her coordination...

2111
01:25:37,502 --> 01:25:39,910
Her two hands aren't quite in sync yet.

2112
01:25:39,910 --> 01:25:41,912
I can't even do that much.

2113
01:25:41,912 --> 01:25:43,682
You haven't practiced it though.

2114
01:25:43,682 --> 01:25:45,962
[Cheering for Sunny #22]
Sunny really practiced her wok work well!

2115
01:25:45,962 --> 01:25:47,792
She's really good!

2116
01:25:47,792 --> 01:25:49,952
[Cheering for Sunny #333]
It's only been a short time since she learned

2117
01:25:49,952 --> 01:25:52,322
but she flips even the big wok well.

2118
01:25:52,322 --> 01:25:53,442
[A bit sheepish]

2119
01:25:53,442 --> 01:25:55,282
Of course, she might not
measure up in the boss's eyes,

2120
01:25:55,282 --> 01:25:57,042
but everyone still
has that sense of camaraderie.

2121
01:25:57,042 --> 01:25:59,850
[Her wok work gets even more energetic
with everyone cheering her on]

2122
01:26:02,462 --> 01:26:04,752
[Big smiles at how much
Sunny's grown in just one day]

2123
01:26:04,752 --> 01:26:07,552
- Every time I flip it, they cheer.
- They're so happy for her.

2124
01:26:07,552 --> 01:26:09,342
Of course, if a boxer does that.

2125
01:26:09,342 --> 01:26:11,202
- It'd be surprising.
- Right, so no one suspects a thing.

2126
01:26:11,202 --> 01:26:13,072
- Because she's a boxer.
- It's so surprising.

2127
01:26:13,072 --> 01:26:15,322
- That laugh is "because she's a boxer."
- It doesn't make sense.

2128
01:26:15,322 --> 01:26:17,482
A laugh over "because she's a boxer?"

2129
01:26:17,482 --> 01:26:20,743
- Who laughs that genuinely, my goodness?
- Right.

2130
01:26:20,743 --> 01:26:24,835
Seems like she must be practicing hard
even after going home every day, right?

2131
01:26:24,835 --> 01:26:28,302
Guess she looked up
how to flip a wok pretty hard.

2132
01:26:28,302 --> 01:26:31,142
To be able to do this after just a few tries...

2133
01:26:31,884 --> 01:26:33,642
doesn't add up, right?

2134
01:26:33,642 --> 01:26:35,322
In my opinion,

2135
01:26:35,322 --> 01:26:38,322
I think she can do it a little
and seems to have some basic skill too...

2136
01:26:38,322 --> 01:26:40,332
- Right.
- Seems like she can do it a bit, right?

2137
01:26:40,332 --> 01:26:42,912
[Of course it shows!]
- Right, it's showing. - A little suspicious.

2138
01:26:42,912 --> 01:26:47,722
She knows how to
handle that big wok all by herself.

2139
01:26:47,722 --> 01:26:50,202
- Or, in my opinion...
- "In my opinion?"

2140
01:26:50,202 --> 01:26:51,422
No way.

2141
01:26:51,422 --> 01:26:52,512
Wait, are they actually getting suspicious?

2142
01:26:52,512 --> 01:26:54,202
In my opinion,

2143
01:26:54,202 --> 01:26:57,502
she's probably run her own restaurant before.

2144
01:26:57,502 --> 01:26:59,722
[The head prep chef's instincts are no joke!]

2145
01:26:59,722 --> 01:27:01,362
She's caught.

2146
01:27:01,362 --> 01:27:04,442
- She's probably run her own restaurant before.
- So is she acting?

2147
01:27:04,442 --> 01:27:07,212
[Full of suspicion]
She knows how to do all sorts of things.

2148
01:27:07,212 --> 01:27:10,682
- Even her prep work is quick and skilled.
- Exactly my point.

2149
01:27:10,682 --> 01:27:12,242
[I knew it]
See, look at that, right.

2150
01:27:12,242 --> 01:27:13,792
- She's caught.
- Ah, I knew this would happen.

2151
01:27:13,792 --> 01:27:16,892
I told you, I could tell back
when she was using the knife on the bulgogi.

2152
01:27:16,892 --> 01:27:19,232
It was too fast, and the sound then, way too...

2153
01:27:19,232 --> 01:27:20,842
you could hear that rapid
"tak-tak-tak-tak" sound.

2154
01:27:20,842 --> 01:27:22,202
It was so obvious.

2155
01:27:22,202 --> 01:27:23,872
When she was cutting.

2156
01:27:23,872 --> 01:27:25,212
Would this count as a failure?

2157
01:27:25,212 --> 01:27:26,433
Yeah.

2158
01:27:26,433 --> 01:27:28,357
It's a fail.

2159
01:27:29,522 --> 01:27:31,342
[Staff meal ingredients]
She was really fast when she was cutting!

2160
01:27:31,342 --> 01:27:33,472
Right.

2161
01:27:33,472 --> 01:27:35,362
Right, this is strange.

2162
01:27:35,362 --> 01:27:36,652
Isn't this way too obvious?

2163
01:27:36,652 --> 01:27:38,242
- How does it make sense to cut that fast?
- So they got suspicious.

2164
01:27:38,242 --> 01:27:39,422
[Sunny, none the wiser,
just keeps working the wok]

2165
01:27:39,422 --> 01:27:41,772
She has no idea right now.

2166
01:27:41,772 --> 01:27:45,342
[Just as the suspicion deepens]

2167
01:27:45,342 --> 01:27:47,822
[The chilies, all toasted]
It's almost done.

2168
01:27:47,822 --> 01:27:49,372
- Almost done?
- Yes.

2169
01:27:49,372 --> 01:27:51,382
[You're doing great!]

2170
01:27:53,882 --> 01:27:57,692
I feel like I can smell that
all the way over here.

2171
01:27:57,692 --> 01:28:00,102
- Give it a smell.
- It smells great.

2172
01:28:02,462 --> 01:28:04,122
Oh, he's smelling it.

2173
01:28:04,122 --> 01:28:05,242
Yeah, it smells good.

2174
01:28:05,242 --> 01:28:07,632
- If you toast it well?
- Yes. If you toast it well.

2175
01:28:07,632 --> 01:28:11,212
- Chili oil.
- It's nutty, yeah, a nutty aroma comes up.

2176
01:28:13,482 --> 01:28:16,552
[Grandma appears]

2177
01:28:17,342 --> 01:28:19,552
[Sunny's working so hard]
Grandma really loves her.

2178
01:28:19,552 --> 01:28:21,212
Right.

2179
01:28:21,212 --> 01:28:23,642
Sunny's making Grandma laugh.

2180
01:28:24,302 --> 01:28:26,892
Sunny's really good. She's good with the wok.

2181
01:28:26,892 --> 01:28:28,012
Her strength...

2182
01:28:28,012 --> 01:28:29,182
Because she plays basketball.

2183
01:28:29,182 --> 01:28:30,652
- Plays basketball...
- Basketball?

2184
01:28:30,652 --> 01:28:32,332
[Boxing]
She's a boxer.

2185
01:28:32,332 --> 01:28:33,452
Oh, boxing.

2186
01:28:33,452 --> 01:28:35,532
Of course she's strong. She's a boxer!

2187
01:28:35,532 --> 01:28:37,282
You can't just pick up that wok carelessly.

2188
01:28:37,282 --> 01:28:38,722
It takes real know-how.

2189
01:28:38,722 --> 01:28:41,072
[Amazing]

2190
01:28:41,072 --> 01:28:44,122
When you go back to Korea,
you have to open a restaurant.

2191
01:28:44,122 --> 01:28:46,162
- To open a restaurant?
- To open a restaurant.

2192
01:28:46,162 --> 01:28:48,602
Ah... I'd love to, I really would.

2193
01:28:48,602 --> 01:28:51,502
[Avoiding eye contact]
- What did she say? - She said she'd love to.

2194
01:28:51,502 --> 01:28:54,322
Are you really going to open a restaurant?

2195
01:28:54,322 --> 01:28:56,282
- Are you really going to open a restaurant?
- Yes.

2196
01:28:56,282 --> 01:28:59,262
I'll come work for you.

2197
01:28:59,262 --> 01:29:01,772
Sounds good.

2198
01:29:01,772 --> 01:29:04,862
[Definitely open a restaurant]
- Reverse expansion. - Right.

2199
01:29:04,862 --> 01:29:07,232
- Ah, everyone's really rooting for her.
- Yeah.

2200
01:29:07,232 --> 01:29:08,962
[The kitchen crew, cheering for Sunny]
- Really. - Everyone's so warm.

2201
01:29:08,962 --> 01:29:10,272
It's so nice.

2202
01:29:10,272 --> 01:29:13,692
[Toward the end of lunch service,
customers begin leaving one by one]

2203
01:29:14,402 --> 01:29:18,042
[The kitchen finally quiets down too]

2204
01:29:18,042 --> 01:29:21,022
Sunny's going to cook Korean food now.

2205
01:29:21,022 --> 01:29:22,642
- Sunny, you can go ahead now.
- Now.

2206
01:29:22,642 --> 01:29:25,122
- Make the staff meal now.
- Right now?

2207
01:29:25,122 --> 01:29:27,292
[Time to stir-fry a huge batch of bulgogi!]
Now? Where do I do it?

2208
01:29:27,292 --> 01:29:29,022
- Her first staff meal.
- Chef Yang.

2209
01:29:29,022 --> 01:29:30,192
[Thud!]

2210
01:29:30,192 --> 01:29:32,492
[50 servings of beef]

2211
01:29:32,492 --> 01:29:35,402
This amount...

2212
01:29:35,402 --> 01:29:39,052
[50 servings of meat and veggies, all prepped]
- Oh my. - It's a lot.

2213
01:29:39,052 --> 01:29:41,282
[Is this amount for real?]

2214
01:29:41,282 --> 01:29:43,122
[Astonished]
That's really a lot of beef.

2215
01:29:43,122 --> 01:29:44,702
Way too much.

2216
01:29:44,702 --> 01:29:47,422
Is it really that much?

2217
01:29:47,422 --> 01:29:48,492
Everyone says it's a lot.

2218
01:29:48,492 --> 01:29:51,618
I was worried it wouldn't be enough.

2219
01:29:51,618 --> 01:29:55,366
She's just really generous, honestly.

2220
01:29:56,042 --> 01:29:59,872
[Sunny stir-fries 50 servings of bulgogi solo]
- So you're cooking that yourself? - Yes.

2221
01:29:59,872 --> 01:30:01,102
I'm going to make Korean food.

2222
01:30:01,102 --> 01:30:04,112
- Korean food?
- Yes, bulgogi.

2223
01:30:04,112 --> 01:30:06,382
[Anticipation]

2224
01:30:06,382 --> 01:30:08,362
What do you want to do with this?
Should I cut it for you?

2225
01:30:08,362 --> 01:30:10,032
Yes, just half.

2226
01:30:10,032 --> 01:30:13,492
[Leaves the enoki mushroom prep
for the bulgogi to the head prep chef]

2227
01:30:14,172 --> 01:30:16,322
This won't be easy to finish, huh?

2228
01:30:16,322 --> 01:30:20,322
There's so much, I think she'll
have to split it and cook it in batches.

2229
01:30:20,322 --> 01:30:23,442
It'll be hard
to stir-fry it all at once, right?

2230
01:30:23,442 --> 01:30:26,572
[The Prep station seniors say
there's too much to stir-fry it all at once]

2231
01:30:26,572 --> 01:30:29,762
It's Sunny's Korean cooking,
so just leave her be.

2232
01:30:29,762 --> 01:30:33,442
[Full trust]
Just watch and see how Sunny does it.

2233
01:30:33,442 --> 01:30:37,042
[Sunny standing at the burner]
- Is it oil? - Yes.

2234
01:30:37,042 --> 01:30:39,234
[Ladles a scoop of oil into the wok]

2235
01:30:39,234 --> 01:30:42,290
So this is where she shows what she's got.

2236
01:30:42,290 --> 01:30:45,150
[With everyone's eyes on her...]
I'll cook it.

2237
01:30:46,898 --> 01:30:49,074
[All 50 servings of beef go in at once]

2238
01:30:49,074 --> 01:30:51,452
She's putting all of that in at once?

2239
01:30:52,306 --> 01:30:54,578
- Wow, way too...
- Way too much.

2240
01:30:54,578 --> 01:30:56,626
- Wow, way too...
- Way too much.

2241
01:30:56,626 --> 01:30:58,622
Yeah, it really is a lot.

2242
01:31:01,138 --> 01:31:03,394
[Grandma and Boss Nam watch silently]

2243
01:31:03,394 --> 01:31:05,826
They look really surprised.

2244
01:31:05,826 --> 01:31:09,278
There's that much,
and she's stir-frying it all at once?

2245
01:31:10,194 --> 01:31:13,506
[Sunny's 50-serving bulgogi,
carrying everyone's worry and hope at once]

2246
01:31:13,506 --> 01:31:15,426
There's so much meat, it'll be hard to flip.

2247
01:31:15,426 --> 01:31:17,202
- Right.
- It's hard to flip.

2248
01:31:17,202 --> 01:31:19,010
Yeah, because there's so much.

2249
01:31:19,010 --> 01:31:21,858
Sunny can do it.

2250
01:31:21,858 --> 01:31:23,906
[Trust in Sunny]

2251
01:31:23,906 --> 01:31:25,362
Slowly.

2252
01:31:25,362 --> 01:31:28,012
I'll try stir-frying it slowly.

2253
01:31:30,370 --> 01:31:32,610
Whoa, will this work? Will this work?

2254
01:31:32,610 --> 01:31:34,626
[Tries turning the wok
with all her strength...]

2255
01:31:34,626 --> 01:31:36,578
Will this work?

2256
01:31:36,578 --> 01:31:38,994
It's so heavy.

2257
01:31:38,994 --> 01:31:41,122
She's talking to herself, huh.

2258
01:31:41,122 --> 01:31:42,898
[Flustered enough to start
muttering to herself in Korean...]

2259
01:31:42,898 --> 01:31:45,282
- This is so heavy.
- Who's she talking to?

2260
01:31:45,282 --> 01:31:46,498
It's heavy.

2261
01:31:46,498 --> 01:31:48,878
It just wasn't working. It was too heavy.

2262
01:31:51,342 --> 01:31:54,642
[Are we... going to get to eat today?]
"Are we gonna get to eat?"

2263
01:31:55,822 --> 01:31:58,082
[Striding over]

2264
01:31:58,082 --> 01:31:59,474
[To make mixing the meat easier]
Use a spatula.

2265
01:31:59,474 --> 01:32:01,410
Ah, everyone's come to help now.

2266
01:32:01,410 --> 01:32:02,578
It's so heavy.

2267
01:32:02,578 --> 01:32:04,402
- Want to use a spatula?
- Okay.

2268
01:32:04,402 --> 01:32:06,786
That works just fine.

2269
01:32:06,786 --> 01:32:08,762
- Right, right.
- Bulgogi's got moisture in it anyway.

2270
01:32:08,762 --> 01:32:12,306
Korean bulgogi isn't really the kind of dish
you toss in a wok anyway.

2271
01:32:12,306 --> 01:32:14,310
It's so heavy.

2272
01:32:15,170 --> 01:32:18,306
[She must toss the wok for even cooking...]
Wow, that really does look like a lot though.

2273
01:32:18,306 --> 01:32:20,002
Could she scoop some out now,
even at this point?

2274
01:32:20,002 --> 01:32:22,322
I didn't split it up.

2275
01:32:22,322 --> 01:32:24,562
Why was I so stubborn about it?

2276
01:32:24,562 --> 01:32:27,538
[Why did I do that?]
There's just no other way, really.

2277
01:32:27,538 --> 01:32:29,694
[Meanwhile, the head prep chef]

2278
01:32:30,370 --> 01:32:33,666
[A big pile of enoki mushrooms for Sunny]
The vegetables have to go in there too, right?

2279
01:32:33,666 --> 01:32:36,210
[Enoki mushrooms pile onto an already-full wok]
The ingredients just keep piling up.

2280
01:32:36,210 --> 01:32:38,514
[Vegetables start going in]
Right, she has to put all of that in now.

2281
01:32:38,514 --> 01:32:40,418
It's going to overflow.

2282
01:32:40,418 --> 01:32:42,522
Couldn't they eat that stuff the next day too?

2283
01:32:42,522 --> 01:32:45,283
[Why did I really do that?]
- Because there's so much. - No...

2284
01:32:46,066 --> 01:32:49,442
Stir-frying's going to get even harder, huh?

2285
01:32:49,442 --> 01:32:51,314
The vegetables need to wilt down too now.

2286
01:32:51,314 --> 01:32:52,882
That's right.

2287
01:32:52,882 --> 01:32:54,466
[Unbreakable Sunny]
Some broth needs to come out of it too

2288
01:32:54,466 --> 01:32:55,932
as everything wilts down together.

2289
01:32:55,932 --> 01:32:58,386
[Swish]

2290
01:32:58,386 --> 01:33:01,458
[Enough to make her hands sweat]

2291
01:33:01,458 --> 01:33:04,626
[A tremendous amount]
This is way too much.

2292
01:33:04,626 --> 01:33:06,482
Wow, that's a lot.

2293
01:33:06,482 --> 01:33:09,650
[Takes a breath to steady herself]

2294
01:33:09,650 --> 01:33:11,282
[Manages to flip it once, at least!]
She flipped it, look at that.

2295
01:33:11,282 --> 01:33:14,354
[Screech!]
Wait, wait.

2296
01:33:14,354 --> 01:33:16,830
[Not easy...]
This, like this.

2297
01:33:17,490 --> 01:33:19,026
[This time?]
It's too much.

2298
01:33:19,026 --> 01:33:20,850
[Meat escapes]
Hey, the meat's getting away.

2299
01:33:20,850 --> 01:33:24,642
Whoa, hey, meat, meat.

2300
01:33:24,642 --> 01:33:26,802
Wow, it's so heavy.

2301
01:33:26,802 --> 01:33:29,810
Handling a wok this big is really tough.

2302
01:33:29,810 --> 01:33:31,058
[Worried]
Because there's so much.

2303
01:33:31,058 --> 01:33:34,162
- It won't even cook properly.
- Right, there's too much.

2304
01:33:34,162 --> 01:33:36,114
[The meat, not flipped well,
isn't cooking evenly]

2305
01:33:36,114 --> 01:33:38,050
[The meat at the bottom is basically boiling]

2306
01:33:38,050 --> 01:33:40,090
This is a real problem.

2307
01:33:41,298 --> 01:33:43,042
Hey, is everyone just watching all of that?

2308
01:33:43,042 --> 01:33:44,882
- Yeah.
- That must be so much pressure.

2309
01:33:44,882 --> 01:33:46,578
That's really a lot of pressure.

2310
01:33:46,578 --> 01:33:47,682
Because everyone...

2311
01:33:47,682 --> 01:33:49,922
since it's what they themselves have to eat.

2312
01:33:49,922 --> 01:33:51,698
They can't help but care about it
more than anyone.

2313
01:33:51,698 --> 01:33:53,410
I'd probably be nervous about it too.

2314
01:33:53,410 --> 01:33:54,866
Because it's making them anxious.

2315
01:33:54,866 --> 01:33:57,586
It's their one precious
meal for the day right now.

2316
01:33:57,586 --> 01:34:00,926
[Burner cook No.5, watching Sunny's wok work]
There's way too much.

2317
01:34:03,874 --> 01:34:08,252
[Protecting his own meal]
[Takes over the wok for Sunny]

2318
01:34:08,252 --> 01:34:10,872
[Shakes out his hands
once before taking the wok]

2319
01:34:11,778 --> 01:34:13,538
[Heavy]

2320
01:34:16,130 --> 01:34:19,630
- Even he struggles with the wok.
- No good.

2321
01:34:20,450 --> 01:34:22,450
Oh boy, that's a lot.

2322
01:34:22,450 --> 01:34:24,834
[Embarrassed]

2323
01:34:24,834 --> 01:34:26,842
It felt like it was about 15 to 20 kg...

2324
01:34:26,842 --> 01:34:28,594
How do you even lift 15 to 20 kg?

2325
01:34:28,594 --> 01:34:31,330
[20kg]
It's really a huge amount.

2326
01:34:31,330 --> 01:34:35,330
Now that the cabbage has wilted down,
it should stir-fry well.

2327
01:34:35,330 --> 01:34:38,338
[Even if it's hard]
You have to cook it through well!

2328
01:34:38,338 --> 01:34:41,986
[Sunny steps back for a moment
to let the bulgogi cook]

2329
01:34:41,986 --> 01:34:44,434
Come on, come on... thank you.

2330
01:34:44,434 --> 01:34:47,410
I was so embarrassed in that moment.

2331
01:34:47,410 --> 01:34:49,618
Actually, this seems a bit amateurish,
and I like that.

2332
01:34:49,618 --> 01:34:52,050
Ah! On purpose, because you're undercover.

2333
01:34:52,050 --> 01:34:53,570
Because they were getting so suspicious.

2334
01:34:53,570 --> 01:34:56,210
- Since they were getting so suspicious.
- That's the big picture, right now.

2335
01:34:56,210 --> 01:34:58,130
- Undercover.
- The moment she starts stir-frying.

2336
01:34:58,130 --> 01:34:59,906
- She really is a boxer.
- I knew it.

2337
01:34:59,906 --> 01:35:01,346
- As expected.
- No wonder.

2338
01:35:01,346 --> 01:35:03,854
- As expected, she had a plan all along.
- Right.

2339
01:35:05,312 --> 01:35:10,930
[With burner cook No.5's tough wok work,
the bulgogi slowly cooks through]

2340
01:35:10,930 --> 01:35:14,610
[Sorry]
[Embarrassed]

2341
01:35:14,610 --> 01:35:18,002
Guess we'll get a taste of
Korean-style steak today?

2342
01:35:18,002 --> 01:35:20,882
I... I don't think it'll suit my taste.

2343
01:35:20,882 --> 01:35:22,914
He says it might not suit his taste.

2344
01:35:22,914 --> 01:35:24,492
But it doesn't seem like a mala flavor.

2345
01:35:24,492 --> 01:35:25,730
- Ah, right, not a mala flavor.
- Right, it's not.

2346
01:35:25,730 --> 01:35:27,458
It's probably a mild, plain flavor.

2347
01:35:27,458 --> 01:35:29,858
[Sichuan people's taste is spicy food]
That's right.

2348
01:35:29,858 --> 01:35:32,522
It won't be too bad, will it?

2349
01:35:32,522 --> 01:35:34,706
There'll be people who like it too.

2350
01:35:34,706 --> 01:35:37,218
Right, people in Sichuan
basically love spicy food.

2351
01:35:37,218 --> 01:35:38,786
But it's made with our sauce,
so it can't be bad.

2352
01:35:38,786 --> 01:35:40,706
- So there's no chili in this at all, right?
- None at all.

2353
01:35:40,706 --> 01:35:42,482
- I didn't put any in at all.
- Just made it with soy sauce alone, right?

2354
01:35:42,482 --> 01:35:45,662
I figured I could add
spice with pepper instead.

2355
01:35:46,610 --> 01:35:50,258
Want to try a taste?

2356
01:35:50,258 --> 01:35:54,162
[Mid-way taste check on the bulgogi]
Try the bulgogi.

2357
01:35:54,162 --> 01:35:56,942
[A bite of bulgogi]

2358
01:35:56,942 --> 01:35:58,226
Is it bland?

2359
01:35:58,226 --> 01:36:00,572
Is it okay?

2360
01:36:00,572 --> 01:36:02,042
Is it okay? Is it bland?

2361
01:36:02,042 --> 01:36:05,138
It tastes a little bit bland.

2362
01:36:05,138 --> 01:36:06,962
- It's bland.
- He says it's bland.

2363
01:36:06,962 --> 01:36:10,002
[Mid-check, who's next?]
- Right, since there's no spice. - What is it?

2364
01:36:10,002 --> 01:36:12,718
[Boss Nam]

2365
01:36:14,546 --> 01:36:16,162
Is it bland?

2366
01:36:16,162 --> 01:36:18,274
[Anxious look]
Not bland?

2367
01:36:18,274 --> 01:36:20,494
[Tilts head]

2368
01:36:22,514 --> 01:36:24,002
It's sweet.

2369
01:36:24,002 --> 01:36:25,666
It's sweet!

2370
01:36:25,666 --> 01:36:27,314
[Oh no...]
- Right, it's way too sweet. - Sweet.

2371
01:36:27,314 --> 01:36:29,314
- Yeah, I made it sweet.
- Sweet.

2372
01:36:29,314 --> 01:36:31,586
And Chinese food, more than you'd think,

2373
01:36:31,586 --> 01:36:33,426
- doesn't really have many sweet dishes.
- Right.

2374
01:36:33,426 --> 01:36:36,562
The Chinese food we eat
is "Junghwa" style Chinese cuisine,

2375
01:36:36,562 --> 01:36:38,832
so a lot of it has
quite a bit of sweetness added.

2376
01:36:38,832 --> 01:36:42,222
But actual Chinese cooking
barely has any sweetness.

2377
01:36:43,245 --> 01:36:44,942
It's sweet.

2378
01:36:44,942 --> 01:36:47,634
That's why I was going to add pepper.

2379
01:36:47,634 --> 01:36:48,962
- Add it.
- Add it.

2380
01:36:48,962 --> 01:36:51,442
Add a lot.

2381
01:36:51,442 --> 01:36:54,866
[Hastily tries adding pepper]

2382
01:36:54,866 --> 01:36:57,026
[Pepper pours in]
Pepper, pepper.

2383
01:36:57,026 --> 01:36:58,434
All I can taste is sweetness.

2384
01:36:58,434 --> 01:36:59,778
I can't taste anything else.

2385
01:36:59,778 --> 01:37:01,042
- This is bad.
- Oh, really?

2386
01:37:01,042 --> 01:37:02,802
This is a real problem.

2387
01:37:02,802 --> 01:37:05,746
Something this delicious, for once...

2388
01:37:05,746 --> 01:37:09,802
[On top of that, since it's such a huge batch,
the bulgogi's been stir-frying for a long time]

2389
01:37:09,802 --> 01:37:12,402
- It's going to get too tough.
- Right.

2390
01:37:12,402 --> 01:37:14,466
- It'll get stiff.
- It's heavy.

2391
01:37:14,466 --> 01:37:16,514
Let's plate it now.

2392
01:37:16,514 --> 01:37:17,778
Is it all done?

2393
01:37:17,778 --> 01:37:19,170
[Still, the huge batch of bulgogi is finished]

2394
01:37:19,170 --> 01:37:20,825
- So they're eating that with rice now?
- Yes.

2395
01:37:20,825 --> 01:37:22,852
Looks like it'll be delicious.

2396
01:37:23,970 --> 01:37:27,410
[The bulgogi gets neatly
packed into large bowls]

2397
01:37:27,410 --> 01:37:30,274
[Meanwhile, on the other side,
cooking is in full swing too]

2398
01:37:30,274 --> 01:37:34,434
[Another staff meal diss,
Spicy Stir-fried Chili Peppers]

2399
01:37:34,434 --> 01:37:37,678
[1:30 PM, staff meal]

2400
01:37:39,282 --> 01:37:44,662
[Staff members trickle out
one by one to grab a seat]

2401
01:37:46,770 --> 01:37:48,386
[The bulgogi Sunny cooked]

2402
01:37:48,386 --> 01:37:50,414
It's Korean food.

2403
01:37:51,010 --> 01:37:53,042
I wonder how the reaction will be.

2404
01:37:53,042 --> 01:37:55,022
[Nervous]
Whoa, I'm curious too.

2405
01:37:55,022 --> 01:37:57,730
- They'll probably still say it's delicious.
- Right.

2406
01:37:57,730 --> 01:37:59,510
Looks like it'll be delicious.

2407
01:38:00,738 --> 01:38:03,192
I wonder what our Gen MZ guy will say.

2408
01:38:04,050 --> 01:38:06,226
[Staff try Sunny's bulgogi]

2409
01:38:06,226 --> 01:38:08,005
We're having beef today.

2410
01:38:09,102 --> 01:38:11,802
The beef was around 5 to 10 kg... dizzying.

2411
01:38:11,802 --> 01:38:14,844
[Thinking back on it, still an enormous amount]
Ah, that was way too much.

2412
01:38:15,938 --> 01:38:18,418
[The steamed-dish team]
What does it taste like?

2413
01:38:18,418 --> 01:38:21,238
I should try it too.
What kind of Korean dish is this?

2414
01:38:24,786 --> 01:38:26,050
[A smile? Smiling after eating Sunny's dish?]

2415
01:38:26,050 --> 01:38:28,990
But looks like their chopsticks
keep going back for more?

2416
01:38:30,226 --> 01:38:33,026
Mm! Way too sweet.

2417
01:38:33,026 --> 01:38:35,282
I like spicy food.

2418
01:38:35,282 --> 01:38:36,770
[Sunny's dish]
What do we do about this?

2419
01:38:36,770 --> 01:38:38,482
- She says it's sweet.
- She says it's sweet.

2420
01:38:38,482 --> 01:38:40,349
She says she likes spicy.

2421
01:38:41,842 --> 01:38:45,970
[Every chopstick goes for the spicy chilies]
No.

2422
01:38:45,970 --> 01:38:48,114
[What about the other tables' reactions?]

2423
01:38:48,114 --> 01:38:49,714
[Prep station No.2]

2424
01:38:49,714 --> 01:38:51,122
[Wrestling with the meat]

2425
01:38:51,122 --> 01:38:53,310
Tough, tough.

2426
01:38:54,142 --> 01:38:58,514
It's so tough I can't even chew it.

2427
01:38:58,514 --> 01:39:00,562
[The meat, toughened from
being stir-fried too long]

2428
01:39:00,562 --> 01:39:03,986
It's not a familiar flavor either.

2429
01:39:03,986 --> 01:39:06,270
It didn't turn out tender.

2430
01:39:07,186 --> 01:39:09,424
Seems like too much sugar went in.

2431
01:39:11,682 --> 01:39:14,542
[Burner cook No.4 also
takes a bite of Sunny's bulgogi]

2432
01:39:19,970 --> 01:39:23,458
[Switches target to the
spicy stir-fried chilies]

2433
01:39:23,458 --> 01:39:25,970
My spicy stir-fried chilies taste better.

2434
01:39:25,970 --> 01:39:27,954
This dish wouldn't sell here in Sichuan.

2435
01:39:27,954 --> 01:39:29,410
Wouldn't sell in Sichuan, no way.

2436
01:39:29,410 --> 01:39:32,022
Well, every country has different tastes.

2437
01:39:35,126 --> 01:39:37,786
Why are these stir-fried chilies so popular?

2438
01:39:38,542 --> 01:39:39,618
[Xu Jian Kai goes all-in on the bulgogi alone]

2439
01:39:39,618 --> 01:39:41,522
- But it looks like Xu Jian Kai likes it?
- Of course.

2440
01:39:41,522 --> 01:39:42,578
- He's eating it well?
- Sweet.

2441
01:39:42,578 --> 01:39:44,098
[Oh, could it be?]
- Of course, Gen MZ. - Xu Jian Kai.

2442
01:39:44,098 --> 01:39:47,442
It probably didn't suit his taste,
but he's eating it up like that.

2443
01:39:47,442 --> 01:39:48,942
There's no one like him.

2444
01:39:48,942 --> 01:39:50,178
It probably didn't suit him.

2445
01:39:50,178 --> 01:39:52,514
Made by a friend who came all this way...

2446
01:39:52,514 --> 01:39:55,202
It's bulgogi.
How could it possibly not taste good?

2447
01:39:55,202 --> 01:39:56,530
- I need to reconsider our Gen MZ guy.
- How could it not?

2448
01:39:56,530 --> 01:39:57,938
He's eating it all up
so she won't be disappointed.

2449
01:39:57,938 --> 01:40:00,162
[Touched...]
- Ah, our Gen MZ. - Wow, really.

2450
01:40:00,162 --> 01:40:02,205
Such a kind kid, and yet...

2451
01:40:04,066 --> 01:40:06,982
[So that's how it was, Xu Jian Kai...]

2452
01:40:07,938 --> 01:40:09,010
[Grandma appears]

2453
01:40:09,010 --> 01:40:10,370
[Tense]

2454
01:40:10,370 --> 01:40:11,602
Grandma.

2455
01:40:11,602 --> 01:40:14,130
[What will the final boss, Grandma, say?]

2456
01:40:14,130 --> 01:40:15,698
Elders, on the other hand,

2457
01:40:15,698 --> 01:40:18,690
[Sunny's bulgogi]
tend to like things a bit sweet, you know?

2458
01:40:18,690 --> 01:40:20,870
[Let's try it]

2459
01:40:23,778 --> 01:40:26,926
[What will Grandma's verdict be?]
I wonder how it'll go.

2460
01:40:28,386 --> 01:40:30,686
[Nod? Nod?]

2461
01:40:31,394 --> 01:40:33,922
There's a ton of meat

2462
01:40:33,922 --> 01:40:36,718
but only one ladle of oil went in.

2463
01:40:38,130 --> 01:40:39,810
- In Korea,
- Oil.

2464
01:40:39,810 --> 01:40:43,682
we don't really use that much oil.

2465
01:40:43,682 --> 01:40:46,242
And there's way too much pepper.

2466
01:40:46,242 --> 01:40:48,130
- Too much pepper.
- There was a bit too much pepper.

2467
01:40:48,130 --> 01:40:50,702
Wow, that's a really rough review.

2468
01:40:52,082 --> 01:40:53,794
The taste was fine.

2469
01:40:53,794 --> 01:40:55,692
I thought, so this is Korean food.

2470
01:40:55,692 --> 01:40:59,650
- That's not good. Oh no.
- She thinks it's Korean cuisine.

2471
01:40:59,650 --> 01:41:02,482
I think it was good that
she cooked something for us to try.

2472
01:41:02,482 --> 01:41:05,314
Well done!

2473
01:41:05,314 --> 01:41:09,254
[Except for Xu Jian Kai, the spicy stir-fried
chilies remain the hit at this table]

2474
01:41:10,658 --> 01:41:14,594
- Once she comes...
- Suddenly everyone starts eating right away.

2475
01:41:14,594 --> 01:41:17,662
[Sunny comes over to check
the reaction to the bulgogi]

2476
01:41:18,818 --> 01:41:21,218
[As soon as Sunny arrives...]

2477
01:41:21,218 --> 01:41:24,450
[Chopsticks suddenly swarm the bulgogi]
Ah, everyone, seriously...

2478
01:41:24,450 --> 01:41:26,034
Hey, Ji Sun.

2479
01:41:26,034 --> 01:41:27,970
There's no one like them.

2480
01:41:27,970 --> 01:41:29,986
Wow, seriously.

2481
01:41:29,986 --> 01:41:31,922
Is it okay?

2482
01:41:31,922 --> 01:41:34,674
It's so delicious.

2483
01:41:34,674 --> 01:41:36,274
[Just look at how thoughtful they are...]
Wow, seriously.

2484
01:41:36,274 --> 01:41:38,018
Whoa, hey.

2485
01:41:38,018 --> 01:41:39,442
Wow, amazing.

2486
01:41:39,442 --> 01:41:41,072
- They're so kind.
- Were they always this nice?

2487
01:41:41,072 --> 01:41:44,066
- These people are so great.
- Were they always this nice?

2488
01:41:44,066 --> 01:41:46,178
[It's heartwarming... but somehow a bit sad...]
Isn't that a total extreme swing?

2489
01:41:46,178 --> 01:41:47,906
Wow, my goodness.

2490
01:41:47,906 --> 01:41:51,010
It seems like the style Korean people like.

2491
01:41:51,010 --> 01:41:53,810
- People in Sichuan like spicy, oily food.
- So they like it oily.

2492
01:41:53,810 --> 01:41:55,474
Yeah, it has to be spicy

2493
01:41:55,474 --> 01:41:57,682
- and has to be oily.
- It just doesn't match the style.

2494
01:41:57,682 --> 01:41:58,898
Did it suit my taste?

2495
01:41:58,898 --> 01:42:00,066
Of course it didn't.

2496
01:42:00,066 --> 01:42:01,490
- It didn't suit him.
- But the taste

2497
01:42:01,490 --> 01:42:02,706
- was fine.
- Even so.

2498
01:42:02,706 --> 01:42:04,418
It tasted, like, normal?

2499
01:42:04,418 --> 01:42:09,074
But it was sweeter than Sichuan food
and less oily.

2500
01:42:09,074 --> 01:42:10,862
But how was it for your own personal taste?

2501
01:42:10,862 --> 01:42:12,382
- It was sweet.
- Oh, was it?

2502
01:42:12,382 --> 01:42:13,858
- Sweeter than usual, huh.
- Yeah.

2503
01:42:13,858 --> 01:42:15,538
And the soy sauce wasn't salty.

2504
01:42:15,538 --> 01:42:17,250
- The soy sauce was a bit sweet.
- The soy sauce isn't salty.

2505
01:42:17,250 --> 01:42:18,882
- A bit of aroma.
- Mostly just for color.

2506
01:42:18,882 --> 01:42:21,202
No, but this is basically
what we use for foreigners

2507
01:42:21,202 --> 01:42:23,074
as a go-to cheat code when we're hosting them.

2508
01:42:23,074 --> 01:42:24,282
- Right, kind of.
- Always.

2509
01:42:24,282 --> 01:42:25,762
- We think of it as a sure bet.
- Right, right.

2510
01:42:25,762 --> 01:42:27,506
But the country where it just doesn't work

2511
01:42:27,506 --> 01:42:28,882
- seems to be China.
- It's China.

2512
01:42:28,882 --> 01:42:31,730
We actually think of it as
a crowd-pleasing dish,

2513
01:42:31,730 --> 01:42:34,786
but this one just
didn't quite match up with us.

2514
01:42:34,786 --> 01:42:39,138
[For the people of Sichuan,
who love spicy flavors]

2515
01:42:39,138 --> 01:42:43,678
[Sunny's dish, which was just sweet]

2516
01:42:47,490 --> 01:42:50,514
- I felt pretty unsettled.
- Understandably.

2517
01:42:50,514 --> 01:42:51,650
Are you tired?

2518
01:42:51,650 --> 01:42:53,266
Not... not tired.

2519
01:42:53,266 --> 01:42:54,866
It's fun...

2520
01:42:54,866 --> 01:42:57,656
- Huh?
- It's fun.

2521
01:42:57,656 --> 01:42:59,650
Eat up!

2522
01:42:59,650 --> 01:43:02,514
Right, this'll give you the energy
to work hard this afternoon!

2523
01:43:02,514 --> 01:43:05,150
They're all just so kind, really.

2524
01:43:06,786 --> 01:43:08,674
How was it?

2525
01:43:08,674 --> 01:43:11,314
[Thumbs up]

2526
01:43:11,314 --> 01:43:14,262
- Keep up the hard work.
- Thank you.

2527
01:43:15,602 --> 01:43:19,342
[A short break after the staff meal]

2528
01:43:19,952 --> 01:43:24,350
[Sunny, unsettled after the
mixed reactions to her lunch]

2529
01:43:28,386 --> 01:43:29,634
Where are you off to?

2530
01:43:29,634 --> 01:43:31,902
To the market nearby.

2531
01:43:32,642 --> 01:43:34,562
- Planning another staff meal already?
- A redemption attempt?

2532
01:43:34,562 --> 01:43:35,922
- I think someone should stop her.
- Wait, another staff meal.

2533
01:43:35,922 --> 01:43:38,402
- Trying it again? Please.
- Please stop.

2534
01:43:38,402 --> 01:43:41,842
- Please, we want to eat too.
- I haven't even started.

2535
01:43:41,842 --> 01:43:44,482
You haven't even started?

2536
01:43:44,482 --> 01:43:46,434
[The traditional market
near Grandma's restaurant]

2537
01:43:46,434 --> 01:43:48,626
Looking at the restaurant's ingredients here...

2538
01:43:48,626 --> 01:43:50,370
Like frogs and other things.

2539
01:43:50,370 --> 01:43:52,978
There are so many ingredients
that are hard to get used to.

2540
01:43:52,978 --> 01:43:55,122
So from a Korean's point of view,

2541
01:43:55,122 --> 01:43:57,586
I wanted to see how they're used

2542
01:43:57,586 --> 01:43:59,426
and how they're actually applied.

2543
01:43:59,426 --> 01:44:03,070
I figured that would help
me catch on faster overall.

2544
01:44:04,258 --> 01:44:07,026
Oh, so this is how they sell noodles.

2545
01:44:07,026 --> 01:44:09,378
- This place specializes in just noodles too.
- Right.

2546
01:44:09,378 --> 01:44:11,822
There are so many kinds of noodles.

2547
01:44:11,822 --> 01:44:13,322
There are really so many kinds of vegetables.

2548
01:44:13,322 --> 01:44:14,674
- Whoa, that's really big.
- Right.

2549
01:44:14,674 --> 01:44:16,626
I'm really jealous.

2550
01:44:17,490 --> 01:44:20,150
- Types of chili.
- Look at those chili varieties.

2551
01:44:20,866 --> 01:44:24,626
[Checks out the seasoning sauces carefully too]
I wanted to look at the seasonings a bit.

2552
01:44:24,626 --> 01:44:26,386
Zhimajiang.

2553
01:44:26,386 --> 01:44:29,378
- Zhimajiang?
- Yes.

2554
01:44:29,378 --> 01:44:31,202
[A butcher shop this time?]

2555
01:44:31,202 --> 01:44:34,638
I was thinking of buying pork here.

2556
01:44:35,970 --> 01:44:37,026
What's she up to now?

2557
01:44:37,026 --> 01:44:38,674
Getting ready for the staff meal.

2558
01:44:38,674 --> 01:44:40,258
- What's she doing now?
- Another staff meal, huh.

2559
01:44:40,258 --> 01:44:41,762
Another staff meal again?

2560
01:44:41,762 --> 01:44:44,202
- No way.
- We'll have to act surprised.

2561
01:44:44,202 --> 01:44:46,226
- I'm curious about the reaction now.
- Saying "You bought more?"

2562
01:44:46,226 --> 01:44:48,012
The staff is going to be totally shocked.

2563
01:44:48,012 --> 01:44:50,578
Wait, is she really...

2564
01:44:50,578 --> 01:44:53,970
[Keeps going until someone says "delicious"]
One, two, three, four, five pieces.

2565
01:44:53,970 --> 01:44:57,298
Give me five pieces of this!

2566
01:44:57,298 --> 01:45:00,530
[Buys five slabs of five-layer pork belly]

2567
01:45:00,530 --> 01:45:03,838
[Resolute]

2568
01:45:04,682 --> 01:45:07,006
[Chop!]

2569
01:45:07,634 --> 01:45:11,714
[Prep for the second staff
meal already underway]

2570
01:45:11,714 --> 01:45:13,970
[To soothe an uneasy heart]

2571
01:45:13,970 --> 01:45:15,826
[Eating is the best]
Hello.

2572
01:45:15,826 --> 01:45:18,114
Are you open?

2573
01:45:18,114 --> 01:45:20,370
Okay.

2574
01:45:20,370 --> 01:45:21,986
Feichang fen.

2575
01:45:21,986 --> 01:45:23,922
- Feichang fen.
- Yes.

2576
01:45:23,922 --> 01:45:26,418
It's a noodle dish with beef intestine.

2577
01:45:26,418 --> 01:45:29,474
It's really famous in Chengdu.

2578
01:45:29,474 --> 01:45:31,698
Mmm.

2579
01:45:31,698 --> 01:45:36,146
[Hoping it's tasty enough to wash away
the staff-meal heartbreak...]

2580
01:45:36,146 --> 01:45:38,962
Mmm! Try it.

2581
01:45:38,962 --> 01:45:40,194
Looks delicious.

2582
01:45:40,194 --> 01:45:41,874
[A spiciness different from Korean heat]
- Looks delicious. - I'm curious.

2583
01:45:41,874 --> 01:45:44,621
Korean Cheongyang chili spiciness

2584
01:45:44,621 --> 01:45:47,430
and Chinese spiciness are completely different.

2585
01:45:47,997 --> 01:45:50,593
[Sunny suddenly puts down her chopsticks]

2586
01:45:50,593 --> 01:45:54,637
I'm going back over it in my head
what exactly they said.

2587
01:45:55,448 --> 01:46:00,648
[Is she mulling over Chengdu people's tastes?]

2588
01:46:01,436 --> 01:46:03,356
They called me "ayi."

2589
01:46:03,356 --> 01:46:04,476
What's "ayi?"

2590
01:46:04,476 --> 01:46:06,620
[The Chinese word "ayi"]
Auntie.

2591
01:46:06,620 --> 01:46:09,644
Ah, that's not it.

2592
01:46:09,644 --> 01:46:11,148
Why'd it bother you being called "auntie?"

2593
01:46:11,148 --> 01:46:13,340
They should just call me Sunny.

2594
01:46:13,340 --> 01:46:15,212
- So being called "auntie" got to her.
- Really?

2595
01:46:15,212 --> 01:46:16,568
Who's the culprit?

2596
01:46:16,568 --> 01:46:19,052
[Off to find the culprit...]

2597
01:46:19,052 --> 01:46:20,220
[Sunny, who was prepping lunch]

2598
01:46:20,220 --> 01:46:21,484
- No way.
- Who, who did it?

2599
01:46:21,484 --> 01:46:22,918
It's not him, right?

2600
01:46:22,918 --> 01:46:24,012
Xu Jian Kai, it's not you, right?

2601
01:46:24,012 --> 01:46:25,356
It can't be Xu Jian Kai, surely.

2602
01:46:25,356 --> 01:46:27,132
Auntie, one moment.

2603
01:46:27,132 --> 01:46:28,328
- Auntie, one moment.
- It's Xu Jian Kai.

2604
01:46:28,328 --> 01:46:30,188
- Who is it? Who?
- Just look at that hat, it's Xu Jian Kai.

2605
01:46:30,188 --> 01:46:32,172
Who is it?

2606
01:46:32,172 --> 01:46:34,044
[So, who's the culprit?]

2607
01:46:34,044 --> 01:46:36,288
- That's him.
- It's Xu Jian Kai.

2608
01:46:37,180 --> 01:46:38,652
Our Xu Jian Kai.

2609
01:46:38,652 --> 01:46:41,644
- No wonder.
- That's why she doesn't like him.

2610
01:46:41,644 --> 01:46:44,184
[Our Gen MZ guy]
I can't help but not like him!

2611
01:46:45,688 --> 01:46:48,568
[It's me, Gen MZ]

2612
01:46:49,180 --> 01:46:52,474
[Feeling a bit... off...]
A bit off.

2613
01:46:53,062 --> 01:46:57,598
[4:30 PM, break time ends]

2614
01:46:58,460 --> 01:46:59,708
Another briefing.

2615
01:46:59,708 --> 01:47:01,589
Alright, please line up properly.

2616
01:47:03,228 --> 01:47:07,308
[Evening briefing begins]
- Good afternoon. - Good afternoon.

2617
01:47:07,308 --> 01:47:11,068
All the group rooms are
booked today except for one.

2618
01:47:11,068 --> 01:47:12,956
Must be a busy day.

2619
01:47:12,956 --> 01:47:16,728
[Worried]
Ah, there are a lot of group customers today.

2620
01:47:17,372 --> 01:47:20,332
That's the reservation status for tonight.

2621
01:47:20,332 --> 01:47:23,548
And there's one thing I want to ask everyone.

2622
01:47:23,548 --> 01:47:25,964
[To us?]
What, what, no way?

2623
01:47:25,964 --> 01:47:27,820
- What's he going to ask?
- No way?

2624
01:47:27,820 --> 01:47:29,132
[A question?]

2625
01:47:29,132 --> 01:47:30,668
Surely he's not going to ask
about the staff meal, right?

2626
01:47:30,668 --> 01:47:33,238
Don't... don't do it!

2627
01:47:33,238 --> 01:47:36,844
Was the lunch Sunny made today good?

2628
01:47:36,844 --> 01:47:39,196
[Groan...]
Ugh, seriously.

2629
01:47:39,196 --> 01:47:41,964
I really hoped it wasn't about the staff meal.

2630
01:47:41,964 --> 01:47:44,248
[Trembling...]
- A public execution. - Hey, the staff meal.

2631
01:47:44,248 --> 01:47:47,664
[Ha ha... resigned]
Wow, seriously, this...

2632
01:47:48,524 --> 01:47:52,748
Was the lunch Sunny made today good?

2633
01:47:52,748 --> 01:47:55,132
Was the lunch Sunny made today good?

2634
01:47:55,132 --> 01:47:56,988
What do we do?

2635
01:47:56,988 --> 01:47:58,940
[Flustered]
Was it good?

2636
01:47:58,940 --> 01:48:01,100
I was so flustered
when he asked if it was good.

2637
01:48:01,100 --> 01:48:03,852
But somehow I could hear that part clearly.

2638
01:48:03,852 --> 01:48:05,468
[Why was that part of the dialect so clear...]
I couldn't hear anything else.

2639
01:48:05,468 --> 01:48:07,800
I just laughed.

2640
01:48:08,748 --> 01:48:12,092
All sorts of thoughts ran through my head...

2641
01:48:12,092 --> 01:48:15,320
[Boss Nam's unexpected question]
"Was Sunny's lunch good?"

2642
01:48:17,244 --> 01:48:19,315
[Hesitate, unable to answer right away]
They couldn't say anything.

2643
01:48:19,315 --> 01:48:22,207
Couldn't say a word.

2644
01:48:26,572 --> 01:48:28,844
[On pins and needles]

2645
01:48:28,844 --> 01:48:30,140
- It was delicious...
- It was tasty...

2646
01:48:30,140 --> 01:48:32,428
Just be honest about it.

2647
01:48:32,428 --> 01:48:35,436
- It was delicious.
- It was delicious.

2648
01:48:35,436 --> 01:48:36,684
- It was delicious.
- It was delicious.

2649
01:48:36,684 --> 01:48:39,756
[We're on Sunny's side]

2650
01:48:39,756 --> 01:48:41,558
[Moved]
So great, so great.

2651
01:48:41,558 --> 01:48:43,036
Why is everyone here just so wonderful?

2652
01:48:43,036 --> 01:48:44,972
- They're so kind, really.
- So kind.

2653
01:48:44,972 --> 01:48:46,904
It was delicious!

2654
01:48:47,676 --> 01:48:49,484
[Grateful]

2655
01:48:49,484 --> 01:48:51,596
[Again]
Did it suit your taste?

2656
01:48:51,596 --> 01:48:53,418
Yes, it did.

2657
01:48:53,418 --> 01:48:55,404
- Huh?
- It suits my taste!

2658
01:48:55,404 --> 01:48:57,068
[It's me, Xu Jian Kai]
Of course.

2659
01:48:57,068 --> 01:48:58,618
- Xu Jian Kai.
- Wow.

2660
01:48:58,618 --> 01:49:00,780
[Xu Jian Kai, the ever-loyal wingman]
Xu Jian Kai.

2661
01:49:00,780 --> 01:49:02,460
[There's no senior like him]
You'd better treat Xu Jian Kai well.

2662
01:49:02,460 --> 01:49:03,964
Xu Jian Kai, seriously.

2663
01:49:03,964 --> 01:49:05,288
There's no one like him.

2664
01:49:05,288 --> 01:49:07,244
[Xu Jian Kai, what a senior you are...]
Xu Jian Kai, seriously.

2665
01:49:07,244 --> 01:49:08,348
There's no one like him.

2666
01:49:08,348 --> 01:49:09,580
Really, someone like that.

2667
01:49:09,580 --> 01:49:11,748
I really want to adopt Xu Jian Kai
as my own little brother.

2668
01:49:11,748 --> 01:49:14,828
Why is it heading in this direction?

2669
01:49:14,828 --> 01:49:16,918
- Xu Jian Kai's so...
- It's like a romance drama.

2670
01:49:16,918 --> 01:49:18,044
Right.

2671
01:49:18,044 --> 01:49:20,284
- Backing her up behind the scenes.
- It's so hot.

2672
01:49:20,284 --> 01:49:22,278
[Proud, pleased, everyone here won over]
- Really. - Everyone's so sweet, really.

2673
01:49:22,278 --> 01:49:23,516
[Touched]
Really.

2674
01:49:23,516 --> 01:49:26,204
[Uneasy]

2675
01:49:26,204 --> 01:49:28,156
But you didn't even finish the meat, did you?

2676
01:49:28,156 --> 01:49:30,316
There was just so much meat
I couldn't finish it!

2677
01:49:30,316 --> 01:49:33,132
- Right! There was too much to finish.
- Right.

2678
01:49:33,132 --> 01:49:35,980
[The Gen MZ senior,
saying whatever he wants to the boss]

2679
01:49:35,980 --> 01:49:38,584
[Sweating it out]
Overall it was good.

2680
01:49:39,908 --> 01:49:42,956
What I wanted to say was...

2681
01:49:42,956 --> 01:49:47,884
Honestly, at its core, it was a delicious dish.

2682
01:49:47,884 --> 01:49:50,908
But whether it suits
our taste is a different matter.

2683
01:49:50,908 --> 01:49:53,500
That's a separate issue.

2684
01:49:53,500 --> 01:49:58,508
If I judge Sunny's dish
as if it were Sichuan cuisine,

2685
01:49:58,508 --> 01:50:00,252
it's not a dish that suits our taste well.

2686
01:50:00,252 --> 01:50:02,044
Ah, he's really spelling this out clearly.

2687
01:50:02,044 --> 01:50:03,132
She needs to know this, honestly.

2688
01:50:03,132 --> 01:50:06,236
Since we'd never had Korean food,
we were looking forward to it.

2689
01:50:06,236 --> 01:50:10,316
We had no idea what it would taste like at all.

2690
01:50:10,316 --> 01:50:12,588
It was too sweet.

2691
01:50:12,588 --> 01:50:14,940
Of course, some people probably liked it,

2692
01:50:14,940 --> 01:50:18,636
but it doesn't suit the taste
of people from Sichuan.

2693
01:50:18,636 --> 01:50:23,004
[Merit aside, too sweet for Sichuan taste]
And on top of that, she made way too much.

2694
01:50:23,004 --> 01:50:24,716
Please don't take it too hard.

2695
01:50:24,716 --> 01:50:27,478
I'm just being honest with you...

2696
01:50:27,478 --> 01:50:30,876
I see this as part of the process of growth.

2697
01:50:30,876 --> 01:50:35,196
But this much is certain.

2698
01:50:35,196 --> 01:50:38,732
Compared to how fast the other staff have grown

2699
01:50:38,732 --> 01:50:41,612
if we compare them side by side.

2700
01:50:41,612 --> 01:50:43,980
- Sunny is definitely on the faster side.
- Still.

2701
01:50:43,980 --> 01:50:46,888
[Right, right]
Right, she's definitely fast.

2702
01:50:48,468 --> 01:50:50,588
[Boss Nam, giving credit clearly where it's due]

2703
01:50:50,588 --> 01:50:53,398
- The boss is cool.
- Right.

2704
01:50:56,828 --> 01:50:59,948
Once Sunny's finished all the prep work

2705
01:50:59,948 --> 01:51:02,028
when orders come in,
Senior Guo Li Hong in glasses

2706
01:51:02,028 --> 01:51:03,740
should teach her stir-fried vegetables first.

2707
01:51:03,740 --> 01:51:06,758
- Whoa.
- Teach her stir-fried vegetables first.

2708
01:51:06,758 --> 01:51:08,620
- Oh?
- Stir-fried vegetables.

2709
01:51:08,620 --> 01:51:10,268
Stir-fried vegetables?

2710
01:51:10,268 --> 01:51:11,756
Is she moving up to the burner now?

2711
01:51:11,756 --> 01:51:13,324
Really?

2712
01:51:13,324 --> 01:51:16,364
[Sunny gets promoted to the burner station]

2713
01:51:16,364 --> 01:51:20,044
[The senior in glasses]
Guo Li Hong can just teach Sunny slowly.

2714
01:51:20,044 --> 01:51:23,724
[Sunny's staff meal wasn't 100% to their
liking, so why promote her to the burner?]

2715
01:51:23,724 --> 01:51:27,148
She has basic skills.

2716
01:51:27,148 --> 01:51:30,156
Learning Sichuan cooking, generally,

2717
01:51:30,156 --> 01:51:34,188
isn't something you can pick up
in a day or two.

2718
01:51:34,188 --> 01:51:35,308
Right.

2719
01:51:35,308 --> 01:51:38,332
But Sunny has basic cooking skills

2720
01:51:38,332 --> 01:51:40,204
and her wok work too,

2721
01:51:40,204 --> 01:51:44,778
today she used both hands well together.

2722
01:51:44,778 --> 01:51:49,148
I thought she could handle stir-fry dishes

2723
01:51:49,148 --> 01:51:52,698
so I told her to go to the burner.

2724
01:51:52,698 --> 01:51:55,980
[The boss says she's ready for the burner]
- Wow, the boss is cool. - Right.

2725
01:51:55,980 --> 01:51:57,548
Teach her slowly,

2726
01:51:57,548 --> 01:52:00,844
and she absolutely must taste-test everything.

2727
01:52:00,844 --> 01:52:03,532
The taste must always meet the standard.

2728
01:52:03,532 --> 01:52:05,916
[Exactly!]
The taste has to meet the standard.

2729
01:52:05,916 --> 01:52:07,928
[Ugh]

2730
01:52:07,928 --> 01:52:11,752
- He set that up for her assignment.
- I see.

2731
01:52:12,508 --> 01:52:14,492
- If he'd just assigned it out of nowhere,
- Right.

2732
01:52:14,492 --> 01:52:15,658
there'd be pushback.

2733
01:52:15,658 --> 01:52:16,788
- The boss really...
- Let's wrap it up here.

2734
01:52:16,788 --> 01:52:18,348
- He's thinking the big picture.
- Right.

2735
01:52:18,348 --> 01:52:19,868
Be dignified as a person.

2736
01:52:19,868 --> 01:52:21,288
Do the work properly.

2737
01:52:21,288 --> 01:52:22,620
Service and customers.

2738
01:52:22,620 --> 01:52:25,052
First and foremost!

2739
01:52:25,052 --> 01:52:26,428
Right on the busy day.

2740
01:52:26,428 --> 01:52:29,932
[After the briefing where big things happened]
Of all days, it had to be an insanely busy one.

2741
01:52:30,633 --> 01:52:33,636
So you taste-test my dish
before it goes out to customers?

2742
01:52:33,636 --> 01:52:35,564
That's right. For dishes for customers,

2743
01:52:35,564 --> 01:52:37,484
we absolutely have to taste ourselves.

2744
01:52:37,484 --> 01:52:41,238
It only goes out to the customer
once it meets the standard.

2745
01:52:41,238 --> 01:52:46,280
[If the taste falls short,
could she be demoted right away?]

2746
01:52:47,100 --> 01:52:48,805
[Order slips start pouring in]

2747
01:52:48,805 --> 01:52:51,041
So it's already starting up again.

2748
01:52:51,587 --> 01:52:54,984
[Orders from the group customers flood in]

2749
01:52:54,984 --> 01:52:57,212
Seasonal Stir-fried Vegetables.

2750
01:52:57,212 --> 01:53:00,104
Seasonal Stir-fried Vegetables.

2751
01:53:00,729 --> 01:53:03,999
[The dish assigned to Sunny comes in right away]

2752
01:53:03,999 --> 01:53:06,368
[Sunny's first burner-station dish]
[Will it make it safely to the customer's table?]

2753
01:53:06,368 --> 01:53:10,072
[Before you know it, it's day 4]
[The moment of truth approaches]

2754
01:53:10,072 --> 01:53:11,734
[Sharpens his knife]

2755
01:53:11,734 --> 01:53:13,989
[Hee Tae]

2756
01:53:14,952 --> 01:53:17,876
[A finishing-move item? Appears!]

2757
01:53:18,808 --> 01:53:22,456
[Boils the pasta, using...]

2758
01:53:22,456 --> 01:53:24,808
[What is that?]

2759
01:53:24,808 --> 01:53:27,364
[So, how does Hee Tae's pasta taste?]

2760
01:53:28,104 --> 01:53:29,752
I'm not sure...

2761
01:53:29,752 --> 01:53:32,344
[Hee Tae's staff-meal challenge, the result is?]
Yeah, there were a few things left wanting.

2762
01:53:32,344 --> 01:53:34,864
[Meanwhile, Sam Kwon...]

2763
01:53:34,864 --> 01:53:37,664
[What are all these plates even for?]

2764
01:53:37,664 --> 01:53:39,544
[Right here]

2765
01:53:39,544 --> 01:53:42,232
[A 50-guest engagement party banquet]
[Congrats on the engagement! Live happily!]

2766
01:53:42,232 --> 01:53:44,072
[50 plates that all have to go out at once]

2767
01:53:44,072 --> 01:53:45,720
Whoa.

2768
01:53:45,720 --> 01:53:48,632
[Max-busy, extreme-difficulty
kitchen situation]

2769
01:53:48,632 --> 01:53:49,672
[Meanwhile, out in the dining hall]

2770
01:53:49,672 --> 01:53:52,488
[Jumps up]
Excuse me!

2771
01:53:52,488 --> 01:53:55,096
This person can't eat flour.

2772
01:53:55,096 --> 01:53:58,360
One of the appetizers
needs to be swapped for another dish quickly.

2773
01:53:58,360 --> 01:53:59,432
[Now, of all times?]

2774
01:53:59,432 --> 01:54:00,536
[Oh no, don't tell me...]

2775
01:54:00,536 --> 01:54:03,504
Then they really can't eat
any bread or pasta at all.

2776
01:54:05,272 --> 01:54:08,232
[Meanwhile, riding high]
[The wok master Sunny]

2777
01:54:08,232 --> 01:54:10,616
[Handling even the heavy wok like a feather]

2778
01:54:10,616 --> 01:54:12,027
[The senior in glasses looks pleased]
Turn the flame up a bit more.

2779
01:54:12,027 --> 01:54:13,295
[But Sunny's next mission is]

2780
01:54:13,295 --> 01:54:14,370
[A large-batch soup dish]

2781
01:54:14,370 --> 01:54:16,899
The wok's weight is way heavier than I thought.

2782
01:54:16,899 --> 01:54:18,304
[Tries lifting it anyway]

2783
01:54:18,304 --> 01:54:20,843
Oh my.

2784
01:54:20,843 --> 01:54:24,219
[Very flustered]
I'm sorry, I'm so sorry.

2785
01:54:27,080 --> 01:54:29,432
[Sunny's mental state, shattered?]
My mind's completely gone.

2786
01:54:29,432 --> 01:54:31,588
[Even on day 4]
I was a bit worried.

2787
01:54:32,191 --> 01:54:33,528
[The chefs, in a bit of chaos?]

2788
01:54:33,528 --> 01:54:35,403
It wasn't going well.
